 and a more secure future for fruit growers. fruit safety tree orchard device snow farmer https://youtu.be/JV4RARcjzhM', '{"innovation_slug":"the-clipper-fruit-tree-safety-holder","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/the-clipper-fruit-tree-safety-holder/","innovation_title":"The Clipper (Fruit tree safety holder)","innovator_name":"Md. Ishfaq Ahmed Wani","location":"Anantnag , Jammu and Kashmir","innovator_bio":"","innovation_details":"Farmers faced a persistent challenge—trees overloaded with ripening fruits often had their branches snap under pressure, while strong winds, heavy rain, and snowfall further damaged their orchards. This led to significant fruit loss, reducing their overall yield and income. The Mechanical Safety Holder emerged as a game-changer, designed to support and balance multiple branches against external forces. This durable, adjustable clipper prevented breakage, reduced wastage, and even allowed farmers to shape their trees conveniently. With its use, they saved 4-5 extra boxes of fruit per tree, leading to higher earnings. With 3,000 units already sold and three new designs under testing, the impact of this innovation continues to grow. By strengthening trees and protecting harvests, the device is transforming farming, ensuring greater stability, less waste, and a more secure future for fruit growers.","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Ishfaq--scaled.jpg"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Ishfaq-22-768x1024.jpg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Ishfaq-22-scaled.jpg"],"multimedia_links":["https://youtu.be/JV4RARcjzhM"],"tags":["fruit","safety","tree","orchard","device","snow","farmer"],"latitude":null,"longitude":null,"listing_excerpt":"Farmers faced a persistent challenge—trees overloaded with ripening fruits often had their branches snap under pressure, while strong winds, heavy rain, and snowfall further damaged their orchards. This led to significant fruit loss, reducing their overall yield and income."}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('suneel-s1-walnut-variety', 'suneel-singh-jammu-and-kashmir', 'Suneel Singh', 'Suneel S1 Walnut Variety', 'In the high-altitude region of Kishtwar, Jammu & Kashmir, Sunil has pioneered a remarkable transformation in agriculture through his innovative and sustainable practices. Recognising the dangers and inefficiencies of traditional walnut farming—where trees often grow as high as 70 feet—he developed a grafted variety called S1 Walnut by mastering bud grafting techniques under specific temperature and humidity conditions. This not only brought down the height of walnut trees to a manageable 25–30 feet but also achieved a 98% grafting success rate, ensuring uniform quality and safety during harvest. Sunil extended his efforts to a wide variety of crops including hazelnuts, pecan nuts, kiwis, grapes, apricots, and persimmons, all grown sustainably using local mother plants. He also redesigned polyhouse structures to withstand Kishtwar’s heavy snowfall, enabling farmers to continue cultivation through harsh winters. Today, his S1 walnuts have reached global markets, with samples already sent to the U.S., symbolising the world-class potential of Kishtwar’s produce.', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/suneel-s1-walnut-variety/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/02/Copy-of-Suneel-singh-2-edited.jpg', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/02/Copy-of-Suneel-singh-2-edited.jpg"]'::jsonb, '["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3SNHjM2M_IY"]'::jsonb, 'Jammu and Kashmir', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Suneel Singh"},{"key":"Location","value":"Jammu and Kashmir"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"In the high-altitude region of Kishtwar, Jammu & Kashmir, Sunil has pioneered a remarkable transformation in agriculture through his innovative and sustainable practices. Recognising the dangers and inefficiencies of traditional walnut farming—where trees often grow as high as 70 feet—he developed a grafted variety called S1 Walnut by mastering bud grafting techniques under specific temperature and humidity conditions. This not only brought down the height of walnut trees to a manageable 25–30 feet but also achieved a 98% grafting success rate, ensuring uniform quality and safety during harvest. Sunil extended his efforts to a wide variety of crops including hazelnuts, pecan nuts, kiwis, grapes, apricots, and persimmons, all grown sustainably using local mother plants. He also redesigned polyhouse structures to withstand Kishtwar’s heavy snowfall, enabling farmers to continue cultivation through harsh winters. Today, his S1 walnuts have reached global markets, with samples already sent to the U.S., symbolising the world-class potential of Kishtwar’s produce."},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3SNHjM2M_IY"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['agriculture', 'horticulture', 'walnut', 'safety', 'tree', 'kiwi', 'polyhouse', 'snow', 'grafting', 'farmer', 'livelihood']::text[], 'Suneel S1 Walnut Variety Suneel Singh Jammu and Kashmir Sunil, a former soldier who served the Indian Army for 17 years, returned to his native Kishtwar with a vision to reverse the tide of migration and create sustainable livelihoods in his village. What began as a personal quest to improve farming conditions has blossomed into a community-wide movement, empowering over 2000 farmers with knowledge, training, and improved agricultural practices. His relentless experimentation, deep-rooted understanding of the region, and passion for organic farming have led to innovations that not only boost income but also restore ecological balance. From dairy to horticulture to infrastructure, every step of Sunil’s journey is marked by self-taught ingenuity and a drive to serve. His commitment is grounded in local wisdom, adapted to the region’s unique challenges and potentials. “Know about your area, see what potential exists in your area. Work in your area,” he says—words that reflect not just his philosophy but a model of rural innovation rooted in self-reliance, sustainability, and shared growth. In the high-altitude region of Kishtwar, Jammu & Kashmir, Sunil has pioneered a remarkable transformation in agriculture through his innovative and sustainable practices. Recognising the dangers and inefficiencies of traditional walnut farming—where trees often grow as high as 70 feet—he developed a grafted variety called S1 Walnut by mastering bud grafting techniques under specific temperature and humidity conditions. This not only brought down the height of walnut trees to a manageable 25–30 feet but also achieved a 98% grafting success rate, ensuring uniform quality and safety during harvest. Sunil extended his efforts to a wide variety of crops including hazelnuts, pecan nuts, kiwis, grapes, apricots, and persimmons, all grown sustainably using local mother plants. He also redesigned polyhouse structures to withstand Kishtwar’s heavy snowfall, enabling farmers to continue cultivation through harsh winters. Today, his S1 walnuts have reached global markets, with samples already sent to the U.S., symbolising the world-class potential of Kishtwar’s produce. agriculture horticulture walnut safety tree kiwi polyhouse snow grafting farmer livelihood https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3SNHjM2M_IY', '{"innovation_slug":"suneel-s1-walnut-variety","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/suneel-s1-walnut-variety/","innovation_title":"Suneel S1 Walnut Variety","innovator_name":"Suneel Singh","location":"Jammu and Kashmir","innovator_bio":"Sunil, a former soldier who served the Indian Army for 17 years, returned to his native Kishtwar with a vision to reverse the tide of migration and create sustainable livelihoods in his village. What began as a personal quest to improve farming conditions has blossomed into a community-wide movement, empowering over 2000 farmers with knowledge, training, and improved agricultural practices. His relentless experimentation, deep-rooted understanding of the region, and passion for organic farming have led to innovations that not only boost income but also restore ecological balance. From dairy to horticulture to infrastructure, every step of Sunil’s journey is marked by self-taught ingenuity and a drive to serve. His commitment is grounded in local wisdom, adapted to the region’s unique challenges and potentials. “Know about your area, see what potential exists in your area. Work in your area,” he says—words that reflect not just his philosophy but a model of rural innovation rooted in self-reliance, sustainability, and shared growth.","innovation_details":"In the high-altitude region of Kishtwar, Jammu & Kashmir, Sunil has pioneered a remarkable transformation in agriculture through his innovative and sustainable practices. Recognising the dangers and inefficiencies of traditional walnut farming—where trees often grow as high as 70 feet—he developed a grafted variety called S1 Walnut by mastering bud grafting techniques under specific temperature and humidity conditions. This not only brought down the height of walnut trees to a manageable 25–30 feet but also achieved a 98% grafting success rate, ensuring uniform quality and safety during harvest. Sunil extended his efforts to a wide variety of crops including hazelnuts, pecan nuts, kiwis, grapes, apricots, and persimmons, all grown sustainably using local mother plants. He also redesigned polyhouse structures to withstand Kishtwar’s heavy snowfall, enabling farmers to continue cultivation through harsh winters. Today, his S1 walnuts have reached global markets, with samples already sent to the U.S., symbolising the world-class potential of Kishtwar’s produce.","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/01/suneel.jpg"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2025/02/Copy-of-Suneel-singh-2-edited.jpg"],"multimedia_links":["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3SNHjM2M_IY"],"tags":["agriculture","horticulture","walnut","safety","tree","kiwi","polyhouse","snow","grafting","farmer","livelihood"],"latitude":null,"longitude":null,"listing_excerpt":"Suneel S1 Walnut Variety by Suneel Singh"}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('hrmn-99-apple-variety-for-low-altitude', 'hariman-sharma-bilaspur-hp', 'Hariman Sharma', 'HRMN 99 Apple variety for low altitude', 'A well-known progressive farmer cum innovator Hariman Sharma from Bilaspur, Himachal Pradesh, formulated an innovative variety of apples that can be successfully grown in plains. In these tropical and subtropical areas, temperatures can be as high as 40 to 45° Celsius during summers. GIAN and the Honey Bee Network aided this innovation. GIAN and NIF applied on behalf of Hariman Sharma to register HRMN 99 under the PPV and FR Act 2001.', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/hrmn-99-apple-variety-for-low-altitude/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/HRMN-99.jpeg', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/HRMN-99.jpeg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Hrm-99.png"]'::jsonb, '["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JCZskguBNs4"]'::jsonb, 'Bilaspur (HP)', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Hariman Sharma"},{"key":"Location","value":"Bilaspur (HP)"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"A well-known progressive farmer cum innovator Hariman Sharma from Bilaspur, Himachal Pradesh, formulated an innovative variety of apples that can be successfully grown in plains. In these tropical and subtropical areas, temperatures can be as high as 40 to 45° Celsius during summers. GIAN and the Honey Bee Network aided this innovation. GIAN and NIF applied on behalf of Hariman Sharma to register HRMN 99 under the PPV and FR Act 2001."},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JCZskguBNs4"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['fruit', 'tree', 'farmer']::text[], 'HRMN 99 Apple variety for low altitude Hariman Sharma Bilaspur (HP) In 1998, Hariman purchased some apples from a village in Bilaspur. After eating the fruit, he discarded the seeds in his backyard. He noticed that the seeds started germinating in 2001. He got some fruits on that tree. As an experienced farmer, he could sense that this apple tree bearing fruits in a warm area like his village situated at 1800 ft above mean sea level was extraordinary. Hence, he preserved this plant, and the next year, he grafted some branches on a plum tree as no apple tree was available. Proceeding with such research and plantation process. He finally came up with a variety of apples that can be grown in tropical subtropical and plain areas. It was named HRMN -99. Generally, apples can be grown at an altitude of 5000 to 8,500 ft above mean sea level in Himalayan ranges, and it needs 1000 to 1500 hours of chilling. But the variety developed by Hariman can grow at low hills or plain areas, which are about 1800 ft above means sea level. This variety does not require chilling hours. It is a scab disease-resistant apple variety that contains common characteristics such as; it can be grown in high-temperature areas. The plane height is up to 12 -15 ft fruit starts after three years of plantation. Flowering starts in early January, and harvesting can be done after six months, that is, in June. The ripe fruit color is yellow to red, with normal fruit size and sweetness. The only disadvantage of fruit is that it has a short shelf life of around 10 to 12 days at room temperature. The average yield of a well-grown plant is about one quintal per plant. Hariman’s innovation has received various regional, state, and national awards. He has received great recognition, and newspapers and magazines have written about his Apple variety. Today his farming practices are recognized nationally and internationally. A well-known progressive farmer cum innovator Hariman Sharma from Bilaspur, Himachal Pradesh, formulated an innovative variety of apples that can be successfully grown in plains. In these tropical and subtropical areas, temperatures can be as high as 40 to 45° Celsius during summers. GIAN and the Honey Bee Network aided this innovation. GIAN and NIF applied on behalf of Hariman Sharma to register HRMN 99 under the PPV and FR Act 2001. fruit tree farmer https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JCZskguBNs4', '{"innovation_slug":"hrmn-99-apple-variety-for-low-altitude","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/hrmn-99-apple-variety-for-low-altitude/","innovation_title":"HRMN 99 Apple variety for low altitude","innovator_name":"Hariman Sharma","location":"Bilaspur (HP)","innovator_bio":"In 1998, Hariman purchased some apples from a village in Bilaspur. After eating the fruit, he discarded the seeds in his backyard. He noticed that the seeds started germinating in 2001. He got some fruits on that tree. As an experienced farmer, he could sense that this apple tree bearing fruits in a warm area like his village situated at 1800 ft above mean sea level was extraordinary. Hence, he preserved this plant, and the next year, he grafted some branches on a plum tree as no apple tree was available. Proceeding with such research and plantation process. He finally came up with a variety of apples that can be grown in tropical subtropical and plain areas. It was named HRMN -99. Generally, apples can be grown at an altitude of 5000 to 8,500 ft above mean sea level in Himalayan ranges, and it needs 1000 to 1500 hours of chilling. But the variety developed by Hariman can grow at low hills or plain areas, which are about 1800 ft above means sea level. This variety does not require chilling hours. It is a scab disease-resistant apple variety that contains common characteristics such as; it can be grown in high-temperature areas. The plane height is up to 12 -15 ft fruit starts after three years of plantation. Flowering starts in early January, and harvesting can be done after six months, that is, in June. The ripe fruit color is yellow to red, with normal fruit size and sweetness. The only disadvantage of fruit is that it has a short shelf life of around 10 to 12 days at room temperature. The average yield of a well-grown plant is about one quintal per plant. Hariman’s innovation has received various regional, state, and national awards. He has received great recognition, and newspapers and magazines have written about his Apple variety. Today his farming practices are recognized nationally and internationally.","innovation_details":"A well-known progressive farmer cum innovator Hariman Sharma from Bilaspur, Himachal Pradesh, formulated an innovative variety of apples that can be successfully grown in plains. In these tropical and subtropical areas, temperatures can be as high as 40 to 45° Celsius during summers. GIAN and the Honey Bee Network aided this innovation. GIAN and NIF applied on behalf of Hariman Sharma to register HRMN 99 under the PPV and FR Act 2001.","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/HRMN-99-Apple-variety-for-low-altitude-Hariman-Sharma.jpg"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/HRMN-99.jpeg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Hrm-99.png"],"multimedia_links":["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JCZskguBNs4"],"tags":["fruit","tree","farmer"],"latitude":31.4702174,"longitude":76.745195,"listing_excerpt":"HRMN 99 Apple variety for low altitude"}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('automated-arecanut-climbing-and-harvesting-machine', 'suresh-p-v-malappuram-kerala', 'Suresh P V', 'Automated Arecanut climbing and harvesting machine', 'Suresh PV, a 41-year-old enthusiastic innovator from Malappuram, Kerala, developed an automatic arecanut climbing and harvesting machine. The innovation was guided and supported by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network.Suresh, a school dropout, works as a driver and a rubber tapping worker in rubber plantations in his locality. Besides the Arecanut climbing and harvesting machine, he also developed a hydroelectric power plant of 2-kilowatt capacity for his village in 2004 and a ropeway system for transporting goods.', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/automated-arecanut-climbing-and-harvesting-machine/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/suresh-pv.png', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/suresh-pv.png"]'::jsonb, '["https://youtu.be/hHVLK4M_TbE?si=0Tv3Zpja3zClwFxf"]'::jsonb, 'Malappuram , Kerala', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Suresh P V"},{"key":"Location","value":"Malappuram , Kerala"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"Suresh PV, a 41-year-old enthusiastic innovator from Malappuram, Kerala, developed an automatic arecanut climbing and harvesting machine. The innovation was guided and supported by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network.Suresh, a school dropout, works as a driver and a rubber tapping worker in rubber plantations in his locality. Besides the Arecanut climbing and harvesting machine, he also developed a hydroelectric power plant of 2-kilowatt capacity for his village in 2004 and a ropeway system for transporting goods."},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://youtu.be/hHVLK4M_TbE?si=0Tv3Zpja3zClwFxf"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['safety', 'tree', 'machine', 'device']::text[], 'Automated Arecanut climbing and harvesting machine Suresh P V Malappuram , Kerala Arecanut trees have to be climbed three times a year for harvesting. This work involves many risks, and only skilled laborers can do this. Suresh came up with the idea of making a machine to help climb the Arecanut tree. His prototype could carry a man and work on electricity. However, the power supply was an issue, so he fabricated a petrol engine-based automated Arecanut climbing and harvesting machine. The device is powered by a 42cc petrol engine operated using a remote/ mobile app. It comprises dumbbell-shaped rubber grip rollers clamped on the tree, and their rolling motion along the tree trunk provides upward motion. It is a self-adjusting machine for diameters wearing between 100 to 203 mm of the tree and can climb over dents or bumps in the surface of the tree. The machine works on the forward, reverse, neutral, and cutting modes. An accelerator is provided to control the rate of climb. The machine has been designed so that on full throttle, it can climb the tree in 1 minute (approx. 50- 60 ft), perform the cutting operation in 1 minute, and climb down the tree in another minute. The device weighs approx. 28 kg and can run for around 3 hours on 1 l of petrol. By any chance, if the machine stops functioning while climbing up or down the tree, a rope connected to it will enable the user to bring it down without climbing the tree. The innovation enables safety and effective labor performance for Arecanut cutting and harvesting. It has also helped reduce injury and fatalities among laborers climbing the Arecanut tree. Suresh was awarded the third prize at the 10th Biennial innovation award of the national innovation foundation inaugurated by President Ram Nath Kovind in Gujarat. Suresh PV, a 41-year-old enthusiastic innovator from Malappuram, Kerala, developed an automatic arecanut climbing and harvesting machine. The innovation was guided and supported by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network.Suresh, a school dropout, works as a driver and a rubber tapping worker in rubber plantations in his locality. Besides the Arecanut climbing and harvesting machine, he also developed a hydroelectric power plant of 2-kilowatt capacity for his village in 2004 and a ropeway system for transporting goods. safety tree machine device https://youtu.be/hHVLK4M_TbE?si=0Tv3Zpja3zClwFxf', '{"innovation_slug":"automated-arecanut-climbing-and-harvesting-machine","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/automated-arecanut-climbing-and-harvesting-machine/","innovation_title":"Automated Arecanut climbing and harvesting machine","innovator_name":"Suresh P V","location":"Malappuram , Kerala","innovator_bio":"Arecanut trees have to be climbed three times a year for harvesting. This work involves many risks, and only skilled laborers can do this. Suresh came up with the idea of making a machine to help climb the Arecanut tree. His prototype could carry a man and work on electricity. However, the power supply was an issue, so he fabricated a petrol engine-based automated Arecanut climbing and harvesting machine. The device is powered by a 42cc petrol engine operated using a remote/ mobile app. It comprises dumbbell-shaped rubber grip rollers clamped on the tree, and their rolling motion along the tree trunk provides upward motion. It is a self-adjusting machine for diameters wearing between 100 to 203 mm of the tree and can climb over dents or bumps in the surface of the tree. The machine works on the forward, reverse, neutral, and cutting modes. An accelerator is provided to control the rate of climb. The machine has been designed so that on full throttle, it can climb the tree in 1 minute (approx. 50- 60 ft), perform the cutting operation in 1 minute, and climb down the tree in another minute. The device weighs approx. 28 kg and can run for around 3 hours on 1 l of petrol. By any chance, if the machine stops functioning while climbing up or down the tree, a rope connected to it will enable the user to bring it down without climbing the tree. The innovation enables safety and effective labor performance for Arecanut cutting and harvesting. It has also helped reduce injury and fatalities among laborers climbing the Arecanut tree. Suresh was awarded the third prize at the 10th Biennial innovation award of the national innovation foundation inaugurated by President Ram Nath Kovind in Gujarat.","innovation_details":"Suresh PV, a 41-year-old enthusiastic innovator from Malappuram, Kerala, developed an automatic arecanut climbing and harvesting machine. The innovation was guided and supported by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network.Suresh, a school dropout, works as a driver and a rubber tapping worker in rubber plantations in his locality. Besides the Arecanut climbing and harvesting machine, he also developed a hydroelectric power plant of 2-kilowatt capacity for his village in 2004 and a ropeway system for transporting goods.","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/suresh-P.V.png"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/suresh-pv.png"],"multimedia_links":["https://youtu.be/hHVLK4M_TbE?si=0Tv3Zpja3zClwFxf"],"tags":["safety","tree","machine","device"],"latitude":11.2779512,"longitude":76.4331698,"listing_excerpt":"Automated Arecanut climbing and harvesting machine"}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('automatic-weft-winding-machine', 'ram-prasad-meher-bargarh-orissa', 'Ram Prasad Meher', 'Automatic weft winding machine', 'Innovator Ram Prasad, a school dropout from Bargarh, Orissa, fabricated an automatic weft winding machine that can wind cotton automatically. The innovation was recognized and underpinned by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network.Since childhood, Ram Prasad has been interested in arts and crafts and joined his family’s weaving business. He owns a small workshop and develops textiles and saree weaving machines, mainly Sambalpuri sarees.', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/automatic-weft-winding-machine/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/ramprasad-mehar-1024x1013.jpg', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/ramprasad-mehar-1024x1013.jpg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/1681883722295-1024x862.jpg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/1681883722295.jpg"]'::jsonb, '["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iQ_3FjTwAr8"]'::jsonb, 'Bargarh , Orissa', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Ram Prasad Meher"},{"key":"Location","value":"Bargarh , Orissa"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"Innovator Ram Prasad, a school dropout from Bargarh, Orissa, fabricated an automatic weft winding machine that can wind cotton automatically. The innovation was recognized and underpinned by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network.Since childhood, Ram Prasad has been interested in arts and crafts and joined his family’s weaving business. He owns a small workshop and develops textiles and saree weaving machines, mainly Sambalpuri sarees."},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iQ_3FjTwAr8"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['tree', 'machine', 'weaving']::text[], 'Automatic weft winding machine Ram Prasad Meher Bargarh , Orissa Prasad’s father used tree trunks to make thread bundles for dying and making different designs. The process involves walking around the tree trunks making an elliptical shape for winding the thread bundle. The traditional method leads to less output with more time consumption. Looking at this, Ram Prasad started designing a machine that could do winding and spinning work at high speed. After working hard for over two months, he designed a prototype that could wind cotton automatically. The machine is fabricated with a drum over which weft winding works using power from a 0.25 HP electric motor. The innovator fabricated the special component that rotates periodically due to the impulse provided by the flat bars with the help of its cutting edges; this is responsible for feeding the threads in both forward and reverse movement. A uniform thread distribution system is attached to the chain and moves along the length of the drum. The attached lever controls the forward and reverse action of the uniform thread distribution system. A foot pedal-actuated brake system is provided to stop the drum’s rotation. Ram Prasad’s innovation can wind five bundles of yarn within an hour, which otherwise takes two to three days. The Innovator has successfully sold more than 90 units of the machines. The innovation was appreciated and awarded at the 10th national grassroots innovation and outstanding traditional knowledge awards in 2019 Innovator Ram Prasad, a school dropout from Bargarh, Orissa, fabricated an automatic weft winding machine that can wind cotton automatically. The innovation was recognized and underpinned by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network.Since childhood, Ram Prasad has been interested in arts and crafts and joined his family’s weaving business. He owns a small workshop and develops textiles and saree weaving machines, mainly Sambalpuri sarees. tree machine weaving https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iQ_3FjTwAr8', '{"innovation_slug":"automatic-weft-winding-machine","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/automatic-weft-winding-machine/","innovation_title":"Automatic weft winding machine","innovator_name":"Ram Prasad Meher","location":"Bargarh , Orissa","innovator_bio":"Prasad’s father used tree trunks to make thread bundles for dying and making different designs. The process involves walking around the tree trunks making an elliptical shape for winding the thread bundle. The traditional method leads to less output with more time consumption. Looking at this, Ram Prasad started designing a machine that could do winding and spinning work at high speed. After working hard for over two months, he designed a prototype that could wind cotton automatically. The machine is fabricated with a drum over which weft winding works using power from a 0.25 HP electric motor. The innovator fabricated the special component that rotates periodically due to the impulse provided by the flat bars with the help of its cutting edges; this is responsible for feeding the threads in both forward and reverse movement. A uniform thread distribution system is attached to the chain and moves along the length of the drum. The attached lever controls the forward and reverse action of the uniform thread distribution system. A foot pedal-actuated brake system is provided to stop the drum’s rotation. Ram Prasad’s innovation can wind five bundles of yarn within an hour, which otherwise takes two to three days. The Innovator has successfully sold more than 90 units of the machines. The innovation was appreciated and awarded at the 10th national grassroots innovation and outstanding traditional knowledge awards in 2019","innovation_details":"Innovator Ram Prasad, a school dropout from Bargarh, Orissa, fabricated an automatic weft winding machine that can wind cotton automatically. The innovation was recognized and underpinned by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network.Since childhood, Ram Prasad has been interested in arts and crafts and joined his family’s weaving business. He owns a small workshop and develops textiles and saree weaving machines, mainly Sambalpuri sarees.","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Ramprasad-mehar-1.png"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/ramprasad-mehar-1024x1013.jpg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/1681883722295-1024x862.jpg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/1681883722295.jpg"],"multimedia_links":["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=iQ_3FjTwAr8"],"tags":["tree","machine","weaving"],"latitude":21.3303107,"longitude":83.6135572,"listing_excerpt":"Automatic weft winding machine by Ram Prasad Meher"}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('balwan-pyaj-onion', 'balwan-singh-bhiwani-haryana', 'Balwan Singh', 'Balwan Pyaj – Onion', '50-year-old innovator and progressive farmer Balwan Singh from Bhavani, Haryana, has developed a high-yield improved variety of onions with good keeping quality. GIAN and the Honey Bee Network supported the innovation. The Honey Bee Network helped Balwan Singh represent his innovation at various agricultural exhibitions, including the People’s Festival Of Innovation in New Delhi. NIF facilitated the variety testing at the vegetable research farm department of vegetable science in CCS HAU, Haryana, in 2010-11.', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/balwan-pyaj-onion/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/onion.jpg', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/onion.jpg"]'::jsonb, '["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MDNwlL1GySY"]'::jsonb, 'Bhiwani , Haryana', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Balwan Singh"},{"key":"Location","value":"Bhiwani , Haryana"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"50-year-old innovator and progressive farmer Balwan Singh from Bhavani, Haryana, has developed a high-yield improved variety of onions with good keeping quality. GIAN and the Honey Bee Network supported the innovation. The Honey Bee Network helped Balwan Singh represent his innovation at various agricultural exhibitions, including the People’s Festival Of Innovation in New Delhi. NIF facilitated the variety testing at the vegetable research farm department of vegetable science in CCS HAU, Haryana, in 2010-11."},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MDNwlL1GySY"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['fruit', 'health', 'farmer']::text[], 'Balwan Pyaj – Onion Balwan Singh Bhiwani , Haryana The quality of seeds supplied by different companies and the farmers’ expectations in growing onions are clashing. Hence, Balwan thought of developing some variety of his own that could provide a high yield to the farmers. Once, Balwan’s brother bought some onions from the neighboring village. Balwan observed that the onions were large and well-shaped bulbs, red-colored, thick, and tight-skinned. Being an experienced farmer, he knew that good quality plants yield good fruits, and hence he started greeting and breeding through selection considering parameters such as the plant’s health, tight skin, large size, and well-shaped red-colored bulb. After years of repeating the same process to purify the variety and stabilize the characters, he finally developed Balwan Pyaj, a good-quality onion variety. This yield of onion is about 350 q/ha and has a good thickness of rings tolerance to Stemphylium blight and moderate pungency. The onions are 5 cm in diameter with dark red colored globular shaped bulbs. The neck thickness is 0.8 cm, weighing 50 to 60 g. It is attractive compared to conventional ones with firm, bright red colored mild pungent bulbs with an average yield of 200 q/ha. Balwan Singh, a generous person, gained a very respectful place in the village community and local administrations. Many local and national media covered his innovative work, and he does not mind sharing his knowledge and seeds with other farmers for prosperity 50-year-old innovator and progressive farmer Balwan Singh from Bhavani, Haryana, has developed a high-yield improved variety of onions with good keeping quality. GIAN and the Honey Bee Network supported the innovation. The Honey Bee Network helped Balwan Singh represent his innovation at various agricultural exhibitions, including the People’s Festival Of Innovation in New Delhi. NIF facilitated the variety testing at the vegetable research farm department of vegetable science in CCS HAU, Haryana, in 2010-11. fruit health farmer https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MDNwlL1GySY', '{"innovation_slug":"balwan-pyaj-onion","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/balwan-pyaj-onion/","innovation_title":"Balwan Pyaj – Onion","innovator_name":"Balwan Singh","location":"Bhiwani , Haryana","innovator_bio":"The quality of seeds supplied by different companies and the farmers’ expectations in growing onions are clashing. Hence, Balwan thought of developing some variety of his own that could provide a high yield to the farmers. Once, Balwan’s brother bought some onions from the neighboring village. Balwan observed that the onions were large and well-shaped bulbs, red-colored, thick, and tight-skinned. Being an experienced farmer, he knew that good quality plants yield good fruits, and hence he started greeting and breeding through selection considering parameters such as the plant’s health, tight skin, large size, and well-shaped red-colored bulb. After years of repeating the same process to purify the variety and stabilize the characters, he finally developed Balwan Pyaj, a good-quality onion variety. This yield of onion is about 350 q/ha and has a good thickness of rings tolerance to Stemphylium blight and moderate pungency. The onions are 5 cm in diameter with dark red colored globular shaped bulbs. The neck thickness is 0.8 cm, weighing 50 to 60 g. It is attractive compared to conventional ones with firm, bright red colored mild pungent bulbs with an average yield of 200 q/ha. Balwan Singh, a generous person, gained a very respectful place in the village community and local administrations. Many local and national media covered his innovative work, and he does not mind sharing his knowledge and seeds with other farmers for prosperity","innovation_details":"50-year-old innovator and progressive farmer Balwan Singh from Bhavani, Haryana, has developed a high-yield improved variety of onions with good keeping quality. GIAN and the Honey Bee Network supported the innovation. The Honey Bee Network helped Balwan Singh represent his innovation at various agricultural exhibitions, including the People’s Festival Of Innovation in New Delhi. NIF facilitated the variety testing at the vegetable research farm department of vegetable science in CCS HAU, Haryana, in 2010-11.","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/balwant-singh.jpg"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/onion.jpg"],"multimedia_links":["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=MDNwlL1GySY"],"tags":["fruit","health","farmer"],"latitude":28.7693181,"longitude":76.1551866,"listing_excerpt":"Balwan Pyaj – Onion"}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('groundnut-digger-with-vibration-pads', 'ratanram-dudhval-sikar-rajasthan', 'Ratanram Dudhval', 'Groundnut digger with Vibration pads', 'Ratanram Dudhval is an innovator from Rajasthan. He modified the groundnut digger by adding a vibration pad shock absorber spring, and two pivoted wheels to its rear. The innovation was acknowledged and supported by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network.Ratanram Dudhval is a mechanic, and he runs his small-scale industry named Jai Kishan Krishi Yantra Udyog with his younger brother in Rajasthan.', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/groundnut-digger-with-vibration-pads/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/ratanram-dudhval.jpg', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/ratanram-dudhval.jpg"]'::jsonb, '["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9jtm58N-Q7Q"]'::jsonb, 'Sikar, Rajasthan', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Ratanram Dudhval"},{"key":"Location","value":"Sikar, Rajasthan"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"Ratanram Dudhval is an innovator from Rajasthan. He modified the groundnut digger by adding a vibration pad shock absorber spring, and two pivoted wheels to its rear. The innovation was acknowledged and supported by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network.Ratanram Dudhval is a mechanic, and he runs his small-scale industry named Jai Kishan Krishi Yantra Udyog with his younger brother in Rajasthan."},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9jtm58N-Q7Q"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['machine', 'farmer']::text[], 'Groundnut digger with Vibration pads Ratanram Dudhval Sikar, Rajasthan Ratanram observed the difficulties associated with commercial tractor-operated groundnut diggers and problems farmers face in getting laborers and also incurring losses due to insufficient digging and problems of wear and tear and maneuverability, especially at the corners. His small-scale industry manufactures agricultural machinery like blocks, seed drills, groundnut, digger, trolley, chaff cutter, tractor-operated bulldozers, etc. As an experienced manufacturer, he decided to modify the conventional groundnut digger with an additional vibration pad/ shock, absorbers spring, and two pivoted wheels in the rear of the groundnut digger. It reduces the load in the tractor’s 3-point leakages and increases maneuverability due to wheels, reduction in breakages due to the vibration pad, the approach of the machine in corners, and is easily driven on bunds and channels in the field. The modified innovation can fit any standard 540 rpm PTO, cover 4 ha in 8 hours, and consume only six lit diesel. The innovation is a great help to farmers, and Ratanram managed to sell more than 400 machines in just five years. The customers who purchased the machine in 2011 are still using the machine, and the sale is mainly based on word of mouth, which confirms the acceptability of the machine among the farmers. Ratanram received an award at the 9th National grassroots innovation award 2017 Ratanram Dudhval is an innovator from Rajasthan. He modified the groundnut digger by adding a vibration pad shock absorber spring, and two pivoted wheels to its rear. The innovation was acknowledged and supported by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network.Ratanram Dudhval is a mechanic, and he runs his small-scale industry named Jai Kishan Krishi Yantra Udyog with his younger brother in Rajasthan. machine farmer https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9jtm58N-Q7Q', '{"innovation_slug":"groundnut-digger-with-vibration-pads","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/groundnut-digger-with-vibration-pads/","innovation_title":"Groundnut digger with Vibration pads","innovator_name":"Ratanram Dudhval","location":"Sikar, Rajasthan","innovator_bio":"Ratanram observed the difficulties associated with commercial tractor-operated groundnut diggers and problems farmers face in getting laborers and also incurring losses due to insufficient digging and problems of wear and tear and maneuverability, especially at the corners. His small-scale industry manufactures agricultural machinery like blocks, seed drills, groundnut, digger, trolley, chaff cutter, tractor-operated bulldozers, etc. As an experienced manufacturer, he decided to modify the conventional groundnut digger with an additional vibration pad/ shock, absorbers spring, and two pivoted wheels in the rear of the groundnut digger. It reduces the load in the tractor’s 3-point leakages and increases maneuverability due to wheels, reduction in breakages due to the vibration pad, the approach of the machine in corners, and is easily driven on bunds and channels in the field. The modified innovation can fit any standard 540 rpm PTO, cover 4 ha in 8 hours, and consume only six lit diesel. The innovation is a great help to farmers, and Ratanram managed to sell more than 400 machines in just five years. The customers who purchased the machine in 2011 are still using the machine, and the sale is mainly based on word of mouth, which confirms the acceptability of the machine among the farmers. Ratanram received an award at the 9th National grassroots innovation award 2017","innovation_details":"Ratanram Dudhval is an innovator from Rajasthan. He modified the groundnut digger by adding a vibration pad shock absorber spring, and two pivoted wheels to its rear. The innovation was acknowledged and supported by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network.Ratanram Dudhval is a mechanic, and he runs his small-scale industry named Jai Kishan Krishi Yantra Udyog with his younger brother in Rajasthan.","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/IMG-20240308-WA0006.jpg"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/ratanram-dudhval.jpg"],"multimedia_links":["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9jtm58N-Q7Q"],"tags":["machine","farmer"],"latitude":27.1659844,"longitude":75.1895576,"listing_excerpt":"Groundnut digger with Vibration pads"}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('paddy-husk-stove', 'mr-ashok-thakur-east-champaran-bihar', 'Mr. Ashok Thakur', 'Paddy Husk Stove', 'The innovator Mr. Ashok Thakur, a 44-year-old professional blacksmith from East Champaran, Bihar, developed a stove that uses paddy husk as a fuel. GIAN and the Honey Bee Network supported his innovation as a good example of sustainable living. GIAN and NIF filed a patent in the innovator’s name.Ashok Thakur is a school dropout who started working in a factory but returned to his village and started his fabrication workshop under the guidance of his father. He started his journey by making and selling coal and wood husk Chulhas (stoves).', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/paddy-husk-stove/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/paddy-husk-stov-1024x1024.jpg', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/paddy-husk-stov-1024x1024.jpg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/paddy-husk-stov.jpg"]'::jsonb, '["https://youtu.be/OciBojiS6EQ%20"]'::jsonb, 'East Champaran , Bihar', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Mr. Ashok Thakur"},{"key":"Location","value":"East Champaran , Bihar"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"The innovator Mr. Ashok Thakur, a 44-year-old professional blacksmith from East Champaran, Bihar, developed a stove that uses paddy husk as a fuel. GIAN and the Honey Bee Network supported his innovation as a good example of sustainable living. GIAN and NIF filed a patent in the innovator’s name.Ashok Thakur is a school dropout who started working in a factory but returned to his village and started his fabrication workshop under the guidance of his father. He started his journey by making and selling coal and wood husk Chulhas (stoves)."},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://youtu.be/OciBojiS6EQ%20"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['food']::text[], 'Paddy Husk Stove Mr. Ashok Thakur East Champaran , Bihar Ashok Thakur observed that a large amount of paddy husk was discarded as agricultural waste in his area. As a professional fabricator of coal and wood husk stoves, he fabricated an efficient stove that can use paddy husk as fuel. He experimented with the common stove and suitably modified it for paddy husk. The stove consists of a frustum made up of an iron sheet of thickness 22 gauge and has a lot of holes of sizes 6 mm in a zigzag manner on the downward side. It weighs 4 kg and has a height of 8 inches. It is designed so that it can use paddy husk as fuel. It can be used anywhere as it is a portable stove. IIT GUWAHATI and TERI University, New Delhi, have tested it. Good reports stated that the stove has a fuel combustion rate of 4.67%, and the thermal efficiency is 23% in the cold and hot start and 32% during simmering. The innovator claims this stove can safely be used on a boat to cook food. It is a very good innovation for the regions where paddy is abundant. The innovation was appreciated and awarded at the 7th National grassroots innovation awards 2013 The innovator Mr. Ashok Thakur, a 44-year-old professional blacksmith from East Champaran, Bihar, developed a stove that uses paddy husk as a fuel. GIAN and the Honey Bee Network supported his innovation as a good example of sustainable living. GIAN and NIF filed a patent in the innovator’s name.Ashok Thakur is a school dropout who started working in a factory but returned to his village and started his fabrication workshop under the guidance of his father. He started his journey by making and selling coal and wood husk Chulhas (stoves). food https://youtu.be/OciBojiS6EQ%20', '{"innovation_slug":"paddy-husk-stove","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/paddy-husk-stove/","innovation_title":"Paddy Husk Stove","innovator_name":"Mr. Ashok Thakur","location":"East Champaran , Bihar","innovator_bio":"Ashok Thakur observed that a large amount of paddy husk was discarded as agricultural waste in his area. As a professional fabricator of coal and wood husk stoves, he fabricated an efficient stove that can use paddy husk as fuel. He experimented with the common stove and suitably modified it for paddy husk. The stove consists of a frustum made up of an iron sheet of thickness 22 gauge and has a lot of holes of sizes 6 mm in a zigzag manner on the downward side. It weighs 4 kg and has a height of 8 inches. It is designed so that it can use paddy husk as fuel. It can be used anywhere as it is a portable stove. IIT GUWAHATI and TERI University, New Delhi, have tested it. Good reports stated that the stove has a fuel combustion rate of 4.67%, and the thermal efficiency is 23% in the cold and hot start and 32% during simmering. The innovator claims this stove can safely be used on a boat to cook food. It is a very good innovation for the regions where paddy is abundant. The innovation was appreciated and awarded at the 7th National grassroots innovation awards 2013","innovation_details":"The innovator Mr. Ashok Thakur, a 44-year-old professional blacksmith from East Champaran, Bihar, developed a stove that uses paddy husk as a fuel. GIAN and the Honey Bee Network supported his innovation as a good example of sustainable living. GIAN and NIF filed a patent in the innovator’s name.Ashok Thakur is a school dropout who started working in a factory but returned to his village and started his fabrication workshop under the guidance of his father. He started his journey by making and selling coal and wood husk Chulhas (stoves).","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/paddy-husk-stove-Ashok-Thakur.jpg"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/paddy-husk-stov-1024x1024.jpg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/paddy-husk-stov.jpg"],"multimedia_links":["https://youtu.be/OciBojiS6EQ%20"],"tags":["food"],"latitude":26.6704794,"longitude":84.9088938,"listing_excerpt":"Paddy Husk Stove"}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('intelligent-sunglasses-for-the-blind', 'anang-tadar-papum-parearunachal-pradesh', 'Anang Tadar', 'Intelligent sunglasses for the blind', 'The 25-year-old innovator Anang Tadar from Papum Pare, Arunachal Pradesh, pursuing college, developed intelligent sunglasses for visually impaired people when he was a school student. His innovation was appreciated and supported by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network.', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/intelligent-sunglasses-for-the-blind/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/anang-3.jpg', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/anang-3.jpg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/anang-2.jpg"]'::jsonb, '["https://youtu.be/SFhHPFBZbUo%20"]'::jsonb, 'Papum Pare,Arunachal Pradesh', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Anang Tadar"},{"key":"Location","value":"Papum Pare,Arunachal Pradesh"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"The 25-year-old innovator Anang Tadar from Papum Pare, Arunachal Pradesh, pursuing college, developed intelligent sunglasses for visually impaired people when he was a school student. His innovation was appreciated and supported by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network."},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://youtu.be/SFhHPFBZbUo%20"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY[]::text[], 'Intelligent sunglasses for the blind Anang Tadar Papum Pare,Arunachal Pradesh Anang once helped a blind lady find directions; this incident made him ponder the difficulties visually impaired people face in their daily lives. Visually challenged people face many difficulties walking and navigating due to obstacles. This incident made him study and research the problems faced by blind people. He found out that blind man sticks and smart walking sticks are already available in the market, which can detect obstacles at the ground level to help visually impaired people. Still, nothing in the market can detect obstacles at waist level and above. Anang then developed an intelligent goggle for the blind called G4B. Anang took inspiration from the navigation mechanism used by bats and integrated the same into a goggle. Bats emit specific frequency ultrasound from their nostrils or mouth and detect obstacles by sensing the echo bounced back from the obstacles. Bats do not use their eyes for navigation. Anang developed intelligent sunglasses which could detect obstacles present ahead of the usually challenged people and give an alert in the form of vibrations. The innovative goggle comprises an ultrasonic transmitter-receiver and a microprocessor. The normal sunglasses are fitted with sensors to alert visually challenged users about the obstacles ahead. Nissan glasses contain vibration alerts on the sides, and as the user moves nearer to the obstruction, the vibrations get stronger. These intelligent sunglasses complement blind man sticks/ smart walking sticks and are not designed to replace them. The innovation announcement was so impactful that UNICEF expressed interest in refining the prototype to make it market ready. His innovation has won many awards, including Dr. APJ Abdul Kalam’s ignite awards 2017, the Deena Nath Pandey smart India innovation award 2017, and the national award at the 10th National grassroots innovation award. 2019. The 25-year-old innovator Anang Tadar from Papum Pare, Arunachal Pradesh, pursuing college, developed intelligent sunglasses for visually impaired people when he was a school student. His innovation was appreciated and supported by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network. https://youtu.be/SFhHPFBZbUo%20', '{"innovation_slug":"intelligent-sunglasses-for-the-blind","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/intelligent-sunglasses-for-the-blind/","innovation_title":"Intelligent sunglasses for the blind","innovator_name":"Anang Tadar","location":"Papum Pare,Arunachal Pradesh","innovator_bio":"Anang once helped a blind lady find directions; this incident made him ponder the difficulties visually impaired people face in their daily lives. Visually challenged people face many difficulties walking and navigating due to obstacles. This incident made him study and research the problems faced by blind people. He found out that blind man sticks and smart walking sticks are already available in the market, which can detect obstacles at the ground level to help visually impaired people. Still, nothing in the market can detect obstacles at waist level and above. Anang then developed an intelligent goggle for the blind called G4B. Anang took inspiration from the navigation mechanism used by bats and integrated the same into a goggle. Bats emit specific frequency ultrasound from their nostrils or mouth and detect obstacles by sensing the echo bounced back from the obstacles. Bats do not use their eyes for navigation. Anang developed intelligent sunglasses which could detect obstacles present ahead of the usually challenged people and give an alert in the form of vibrations. The innovative goggle comprises an ultrasonic transmitter-receiver and a microprocessor. The normal sunglasses are fitted with sensors to alert visually challenged users about the obstacles ahead. Nissan glasses contain vibration alerts on the sides, and as the user moves nearer to the obstruction, the vibrations get stronger. These intelligent sunglasses complement blind man sticks/ smart walking sticks and are not designed to replace them. The innovation announcement was so impactful that UNICEF expressed interest in refining the prototype to make it market ready. His innovation has won many awards, including Dr. APJ Abdul Kalam’s ignite awards 2017, the Deena Nath Pandey smart India innovation award 2017, and the national award at the 10th National grassroots innovation award. 2019.","innovation_details":"The 25-year-old innovator Anang Tadar from Papum Pare, Arunachal Pradesh, pursuing college, developed intelligent sunglasses for visually impaired people when he was a school student. His innovation was appreciated and supported by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network.","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/6253Anang-Tadar.jpg"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/anang-3.jpg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/anang-2.jpg"],"multimedia_links":["https://youtu.be/SFhHPFBZbUo%20"],"tags":[],"latitude":27.0820739,"longitude":93.5407909,"listing_excerpt":"Intelligent sunglasses for the blind"}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('rise-bionics-by-arun-cherian-karnataka', 'arun-cherian-bengaluru-karnataka', 'Arun Cherian', 'Rise Bionics by Arun Cherian (Karnataka)', 'Innovator Arun Joshua Cherian, who completed his master’s and mechanical engineering degree with a specialization in robotics, innovated and developed Rise Bionics, an accessible and affordable health tech company for prosthetics and orthotics. Apart from this innovation, he developed the 4th generation of wearable medical exoskeletal suits.Rise Bionics is a one-stop solution for custom-fitted prosthetic or orthotic devices such as arms and legs. Rise Bionics develops natural composite-based flexible feet and arms with which people can run, play and dance at a small fraction of the cost of carbon fiber prosthetic legs.', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/rise-bionics-by-arun-cherian-karnataka/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/IMG_6430-1024x768.jpg', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/IMG_6430-1024x768.jpg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/IMG_6430-scaled.jpg"]'::jsonb, '["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=38cFpEfv03E"]'::jsonb, 'Bengaluru , Karnataka', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Arun Cherian"},{"key":"Location","value":"Bengaluru , Karnataka"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"Innovator Arun Joshua Cherian, who completed his master’s and mechanical engineering degree with a specialization in robotics, innovated and developed Rise Bionics, an accessible and affordable health tech company for prosthetics and orthotics. Apart from this innovation, he developed the 4th generation of wearable medical exoskeletal suits.Rise Bionics is a one-stop solution for custom-fitted prosthetic or orthotic devices such as arms and legs. Rise Bionics develops natural composite-based flexible feet and arms with which people can run, play and dance at a small fraction of the cost of carbon fiber prosthetic legs."},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=38cFpEfv03E"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['machine', 'device', 'health', 'bamboo']::text[], 'Rise Bionics by Arun Cherian (Karnataka) Arun Cherian Bengaluru , Karnataka As per WHO estimates, around 1.5 million people undergo amputations yearly and require prosthetic services, of which only 5 to 15% of patients have access to devices in low and middle-income countries. Orthotic and prosthetic devices have significant capabilities to improve mobility and reduce mortality, and yet over 70% of patients in India do not have access to it. The main reasons are the concentration of medical centers in urban areas leading to large travel and stay expenses, traditional casting methods limited to the geographical reach, and high device prices and delivery times. To overcome the main downsides associated with this, Arun decided to work on finding a solution. After completing his Master’s, Arun Cherian started his Ph.D. at Purdue University in developing exoskeletal suits. However, he left it incomplete and pursued recreating high-quality, affordable assistive devices from natural composite bamboo. After more than a year of research and testing through multi-center clinical trials, Rise Bionics developed a natural composite-based flexible foot using which people can run, play, and dance. Started in 2015, Rise Bionics provides custom-fitted prosthetic or orthotic devices within a day or two of scanning the patient. Arun Cherian spent over six years developing this system. Hence, today they can 3D scan a patient any part of the body, head, neck, spine, skull, hand, or leg at their home. We can digitally manufacture any bionics with subliminal accuracy in 2-3 hrs. The process is simple; a local healthcare practitioner scans the patient in their home or neighborhood hospital in two to three minutes and uploads the file to the cloud. Secondly, the central facility digitally modifies and fabricates the file per the diagnosis. Rise Bionics does not 3D print; because it takes 15-24 hrs minimum to print one device. They create prosthetics with their proprietary machine, which they wholly make in their facility; Rise Bionics’ digital carving will take about 7-8 minutes only. Thirdly, it is couriered within a few hours to the medical practitioner for patient fitting and device service. The cane prosthetics leg is now less than 1% of their business. Arun and his team went to Zurich and competed with German, Japanese, and American teams, which came up with experimental devices like 100000$, theirs was a couple of 100$, and they came first in the competition in 2016. Athletes wearing Rise Bionics devices clocked in the fastest lap time and came first in two of the three obstacle races for prosthetic legs at the Cybathlon in Zurich. Physical disability can be financially stressful; hence, Rise Bionics works towards reintegrating patients into society as soon as possible. They have served more than 1000 patients across India with assistive devices for the whole body. They serve at corporate hospitals, community hospitals, and not-for-profit organizations. They are planning a pan-India rollout with the Indian central government and even other state governments mixed; they are doing their first project with the Karnataka state government starting February 2023. They also work with ALIMCO, a central government PSU for all-India expansion. The challenge faced by Arun in expanding is that they are looking for Capex Infrastructure investment to shift their manufacturing unit to a 4000 sq. ft. place and also need help in finding ancillary personnel to train other hospitals and also sales and marketing personnel. In all of Asia, Rise Bionics is the only one providing this, and if the central government can take up this technology, Arun has already cleared clinical evaluation and trained all the 12 centers of the central government across India; they have purchased the Rise Bionics scanners, and now they are doing a pilot pan India roll-out, and if the central government can take this up, this would put India ahead of US and Europe in providing access to patients to high quality bionic assistive devices. Innovator Arun Joshua Cherian, who completed his master’s and mechanical engineering degree with a specialization in robotics, innovated and developed Rise Bionics, an accessible and affordable health tech company for prosthetics and orthotics. Apart from this innovation, he developed the 4th generation of wearable medical exoskeletal suits.Rise Bionics is a one-stop solution for custom-fitted prosthetic or orthotic devices such as arms and legs. Rise Bionics develops natural composite-based flexible feet and arms with which people can run, play and dance at a small fraction of the cost of carbon fiber prosthetic legs. machine device health bamboo https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=38cFpEfv03E', '{"innovation_slug":"rise-bionics-by-arun-cherian-karnataka","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/rise-bionics-by-arun-cherian-karnataka/","innovation_title":"Rise Bionics by Arun Cherian (Karnataka)","innovator_name":"Arun Cherian","location":"Bengaluru , Karnataka","innovator_bio":"As per WHO estimates, around 1.5 million people undergo amputations yearly and require prosthetic services, of which only 5 to 15% of patients have access to devices in low and middle-income countries. Orthotic and prosthetic devices have significant capabilities to improve mobility and reduce mortality, and yet over 70% of patients in India do not have access to it. The main reasons are the concentration of medical centers in urban areas leading to large travel and stay expenses, traditional casting methods limited to the geographical reach, and high device prices and delivery times. To overcome the main downsides associated with this, Arun decided to work on finding a solution. After completing his Master’s, Arun Cherian started his Ph.D. at Purdue University in developing exoskeletal suits. However, he left it incomplete and pursued recreating high-quality, affordable assistive devices from natural composite bamboo. After more than a year of research and testing through multi-center clinical trials, Rise Bionics developed a natural composite-based flexible foot using which people can run, play, and dance. Started in 2015, Rise Bionics provides custom-fitted prosthetic or orthotic devices within a day or two of scanning the patient. Arun Cherian spent over six years developing this system. Hence, today they can 3D scan a patient any part of the body, head, neck, spine, skull, hand, or leg at their home. We can digitally manufacture any bionics with subliminal accuracy in 2-3 hrs. The process is simple; a local healthcare practitioner scans the patient in their home or neighborhood hospital in two to three minutes and uploads the file to the cloud. Secondly, the central facility digitally modifies and fabricates the file per the diagnosis. Rise Bionics does not 3D print; because it takes 15-24 hrs minimum to print one device. They create prosthetics with their proprietary machine, which they wholly make in their facility; Rise Bionics’ digital carving will take about 7-8 minutes only. Thirdly, it is couriered within a few hours to the medical practitioner for patient fitting and device service. The cane prosthetics leg is now less than 1% of their business. Arun and his team went to Zurich and competed with German, Japanese, and American teams, which came up with experimental devices like 100000$, theirs was a couple of 100$, and they came first in the competition in 2016. Athletes wearing Rise Bionics devices clocked in the fastest lap time and came first in two of the three obstacle races for prosthetic legs at the Cybathlon in Zurich. Physical disability can be financially stressful; hence, Rise Bionics works towards reintegrating patients into society as soon as possible. They have served more than 1000 patients across India with assistive devices for the whole body. They serve at corporate hospitals, community hospitals, and not-for-profit organizations. They are planning a pan-India rollout with the Indian central government and even other state governments mixed; they are doing their first project with the Karnataka state government starting February 2023. They also work with ALIMCO, a central government PSU for all-India expansion. The challenge faced by Arun in expanding is that they are looking for Capex Infrastructure investment to shift their manufacturing unit to a 4000 sq. ft. place and also need help in finding ancillary personnel to train other hospitals and also sales and marketing personnel. In all of Asia, Rise Bionics is the only one providing this, and if the central government can take up this technology, Arun has already cleared clinical evaluation and trained all the 12 centers of the central government across India; they have purchased the Rise Bionics scanners, and now they are doing a pilot pan India roll-out, and if the central government can take this up, this would put India ahead of US and Europe in providing access to patients to high quality bionic assistive devices.","innovation_details":"Innovator Arun Joshua Cherian, who completed his master’s and mechanical engineering degree with a specialization in robotics, innovated and developed Rise Bionics, an accessible and affordable health tech company for prosthetics and orthotics. Apart from this innovation, he developed the 4th generation of wearable medical exoskeletal suits.Rise Bionics is a one-stop solution for custom-fitted prosthetic or orthotic devices such as arms and legs. Rise Bionics develops natural composite-based flexible feet and arms with which people can run, play and dance at a small fraction of the cost of carbon fiber prosthetic legs.","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Screenshot-2024-03-08-175915.png"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/IMG_6430-1024x768.jpg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/IMG_6430-scaled.jpg"],"multimedia_links":["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=38cFpEfv03E"],"tags":["machine","device","health","bamboo"],"latitude":13.10197,"longitude":77.5863591,"listing_excerpt":"Rise Bionics by Arun Cherian (Karnataka)"}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('modha-technologies', 'sivakumar-modha-hyderabad-telangana', 'Sivakumar Modha', 'Modha Technologies', 'A young degree holder from the United Andhra Pradesh, Sivakumar Modha chose to become an innovator to help the weaving community instead of pursuing his MCA. His innovation of the Modha device replacing Jacquard in handlooms took a decade and a half to complete. His prototype was recognized and facilitated by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network. GIAN (Grassroots Innovation Augmentation Network) encouraged and reinforced the innovation.', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/modha-technologies/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/modha-Technologies.png', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/modha-Technologies.png"]'::jsonb, '["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=I9qguPlIIAY"]'::jsonb, 'Hyderabad , Telangana', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Sivakumar Modha"},{"key":"Location","value":"Hyderabad , Telangana"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"A young degree holder from the United Andhra Pradesh, Sivakumar Modha chose to become an innovator to help the weaving community instead of pursuing his MCA. His innovation of the Modha device replacing Jacquard in handlooms took a decade and a half to complete. His prototype was recognized and facilitated by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network. GIAN (Grassroots Innovation Augmentation Network) encouraged and reinforced the innovation."},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=I9qguPlIIAY"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['machine', 'device', 'weaving']::text[], 'Modha Technologies Sivakumar Modha Hyderabad , Telangana After completing his bachelor’s in 2000, Sivakumar Modha was set to pursue his MCA at a private college in Hyderabad. The direction of his life changed when he visited a village named Moda near his hometown Hindupur, where many people are employed in the weaving industry. Here the weavers’ committee designs the silk sarees using punch card-based Jacquard machines, where the weaver manually creates and controls every single card. Not only is this punch card process time-consuming, but the efforts of the weavers are quite short-lived, as the cards last only up to 3 years. Every design easily takes a minimum of 15 days to complete on a punch card. Looking at this, Sivakumar Modha decided to help the weavers’ committee, which had suffered losses due to this manual system. “If I cannot catalyze a change in people’s lives, what is the use of higher education and modern technology? I will alter this industry fully,” Sivakumar remarked. After 14 years of struggle, research, and hard work, Sivakumar developed an electronic Jacquard machine. This machine was prototyped to replace the traditional punch card machines with an image-based system integrated into the loom through a pen drive. This technology not only downsizes the time and effort but can also design sarees using distinct patterns or portraits. After the innovation was successful, Sivakumar received an offer of 20 crores rupees from a Kolkata-based firm to sell his innovation and machine to them. Sivakumar refused the offer as he believed this innovation was not for his profit but for the betterment of handloom weavers. GIAN recognized and awarded him the Honey Bee Network Creativity & Inclusive Innovation Awards (HBNCRIIA) 2020 A young degree holder from the United Andhra Pradesh, Sivakumar Modha chose to become an innovator to help the weaving community instead of pursuing his MCA. His innovation of the Modha device replacing Jacquard in handlooms took a decade and a half to complete. His prototype was recognized and facilitated by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network. GIAN (Grassroots Innovation Augmentation Network) encouraged and reinforced the innovation. machine device weaving https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=I9qguPlIIAY', '{"innovation_slug":"modha-technologies","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/modha-technologies/","innovation_title":"Modha Technologies","innovator_name":"Sivakumar Modha","location":"Hyderabad , Telangana","innovator_bio":"After completing his bachelor’s in 2000, Sivakumar Modha was set to pursue his MCA at a private college in Hyderabad. The direction of his life changed when he visited a village named Moda near his hometown Hindupur, where many people are employed in the weaving industry. Here the weavers’ committee designs the silk sarees using punch card-based Jacquard machines, where the weaver manually creates and controls every single card. Not only is this punch card process time-consuming, but the efforts of the weavers are quite short-lived, as the cards last only up to 3 years. Every design easily takes a minimum of 15 days to complete on a punch card. Looking at this, Sivakumar Modha decided to help the weavers’ committee, which had suffered losses due to this manual system. “If I cannot catalyze a change in people’s lives, what is the use of higher education and modern technology? I will alter this industry fully,” Sivakumar remarked. After 14 years of struggle, research, and hard work, Sivakumar developed an electronic Jacquard machine. This machine was prototyped to replace the traditional punch card machines with an image-based system integrated into the loom through a pen drive. This technology not only downsizes the time and effort but can also design sarees using distinct patterns or portraits. After the innovation was successful, Sivakumar received an offer of 20 crores rupees from a Kolkata-based firm to sell his innovation and machine to them. Sivakumar refused the offer as he believed this innovation was not for his profit but for the betterment of handloom weavers. GIAN recognized and awarded him the Honey Bee Network Creativity & Inclusive Innovation Awards (HBNCRIIA) 2020","innovation_details":"A young degree holder from the United Andhra Pradesh, Sivakumar Modha chose to become an innovator to help the weaving community instead of pursuing his MCA. His innovation of the Modha device replacing Jacquard in handlooms took a decade and a half to complete. His prototype was recognized and facilitated by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network. GIAN (Grassroots Innovation Augmentation Network) encouraged and reinforced the innovation.","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/Sivkumar-modha-.png"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/12/modha-Technologies.png"],"multimedia_links":["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=I9qguPlIIAY"],"tags":["machine","device","weaving"],"latitude":null,"longitude":null,"listing_excerpt":"Modha Technologies"}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('selroti-maker', 'bisu-hang-limbu-west-sikkim', 'Bisu Hang Limbu', 'Selroti Maker', 'Traditionally Selroti is made by hand, but there is a high risk of burning the skin with this flash of hot cooking oil while preparing it. Bisu innovated equipment to use whereby Selroti can be made safely. The device consists of two main components: a food-grade stainless steel cup with a hole for consistent and even flow of batter and a wooden handle attached to it to prevent heat flow to the user’s hand. The Selroti maker is portable, budget-friendly, easy to use, and quickly cleaned. It is helpful to reduce first and second-degree burns on the hands and body of the Selroti maker, increase efficiency and decrease cooking time. It is widely accepted in households in hilly regions. The innovator has sold several units of Selroti makers in Sikkim and West Bengal. It also has high demand in Nepal and Bhutan.', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/selroti-maker/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/20220325_215711-929x1024.jpg', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/20220325_215711-929x1024.jpg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/20220325_215711.jpg"]'::jsonb, '["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4oXt60PSbZc"]'::jsonb, 'West Sikkim', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Bisu Hang Limbu"},{"key":"Location","value":"West Sikkim"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"Traditionally Selroti is made by hand, but there is a high risk of burning the skin with this flash of hot cooking oil while preparing it. Bisu innovated equipment to use whereby Selroti can be made safely. The device consists of two main components: a food-grade stainless steel cup with a hole for consistent and even flow of batter and a wooden handle attached to it to prevent heat flow to the user’s hand. The Selroti maker is portable, budget-friendly, easy to use, and quickly cleaned. It is helpful to reduce first and second-degree burns on the hands and body of the Selroti maker, increase efficiency and decrease cooking time. It is widely accepted in households in hilly regions. The innovator has sold several units of Selroti makers in Sikkim and West Bengal. It also has high demand in Nepal and Bhutan."},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4oXt60PSbZc"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['device', 'food']::text[], 'Selroti Maker Bisu Hang Limbu West Sikkim Bisu Hang Lambu, a 22-year-old innovator from West Sikkim, came up with a Selroti maker. Selroti is a traditional sweet bread of Nepali culture. GIAN and the Honey Bee Network accepted and appreciated the innovation. Traditionally Selroti is made by hand, but there is a high risk of burning the skin with this flash of hot cooking oil while preparing it. Bisu innovated equipment to use whereby Selroti can be made safely. The device consists of two main components: a food-grade stainless steel cup with a hole for consistent and even flow of batter and a wooden handle attached to it to prevent heat flow to the user’s hand. The Selroti maker is portable, budget-friendly, easy to use, and quickly cleaned. It is helpful to reduce first and second-degree burns on the hands and body of the Selroti maker, increase efficiency and decrease cooking time. It is widely accepted in households in hilly regions. The innovator has sold several units of Selroti makers in Sikkim and West Bengal. It also has high demand in Nepal and Bhutan. device food https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4oXt60PSbZc', '{"innovation_slug":"selroti-maker","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/selroti-maker/","innovation_title":"Selroti Maker","innovator_name":"Bisu Hang Limbu","location":"West Sikkim","innovator_bio":"Bisu Hang Lambu, a 22-year-old innovator from West Sikkim, came up with a Selroti maker. Selroti is a traditional sweet bread of Nepali culture. GIAN and the Honey Bee Network accepted and appreciated the innovation.","innovation_details":"Traditionally Selroti is made by hand, but there is a high risk of burning the skin with this flash of hot cooking oil while preparing it. Bisu innovated equipment to use whereby Selroti can be made safely. The device consists of two main components: a food-grade stainless steel cup with a hole for consistent and even flow of batter and a wooden handle attached to it to prevent heat flow to the user’s hand. The Selroti maker is portable, budget-friendly, easy to use, and quickly cleaned. It is helpful to reduce first and second-degree burns on the hands and body of the Selroti maker, increase efficiency and decrease cooking time. It is widely accepted in households in hilly regions. The innovator has sold several units of Selroti makers in Sikkim and West Bengal. It also has high demand in Nepal and Bhutan.","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Bishu-limbu.jpeg"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/20220325_215711-929x1024.jpg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/20220325_215711.jpg"],"multimedia_links":["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4oXt60PSbZc"],"tags":["device","food"],"latitude":27.3158027,"longitude":88.2753144,"listing_excerpt":"Selroti Maker by Bisu Hang Limbu"}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('sunbird-straw-drinking-straws-from-coconut-leaves', 'prof-saji-varghese-bangalore-karnataka', 'Prof. Saji Varghese', 'Sunbird straw: Drinking straws from coconut leaves', 'According to a survey conducted in 2018, India creates 25,000 tons of plastic waste every year, of which only 9% is recycled. One of the classic examples of single-use plastic is plastic straws. Plastic products are majorly made from polypropylene, a material that degrades very slowly, out of which small items are even more difficult to recycle; hence materials like straws end up in a landfill or damage our oceans and marine wildlife. Professor Saji devised an alternative to replace plastic straws with eco-friendly straws made from coconut leaves. From 1 fallen coconut leaf, 150 -200 straws can be made; they realized it is a very good scalable and sustainable product and an alternative to plastic straws. The country aims to revolutionize rural employment and meet global demand. These straws are developed from falling coconut leaves which are abundant in our country and are mostly discarded or burned. As the first sample, Saji developed a single-layer coconut leaf straw in 2017. But by 2018, Prof. Saji came up with a final product of coconut leaf straws available, from regular ones to straws that can be used for cocktails, shakes, smoothies, and boba tea. These eco-friendly straws range from 4 to 8 inches long and 3 to 13 mm in diameter. They developed a 2nd gen machine (multi-purpose machine), which took 45s to develop one straw. They recently upgraded the technology and have developed a conveyor system where time has reduced to 1.5s from 45s, and fatigue is also reduced. Machines are developed in-house and are patented. The product process technology is also patented and has 31 claims under it. The company aims to employ 2000 women at the end of the year and reach production of 1 lakh/day. Prof. Saji has developed a start-up named Sunbird straw to make a difference. This innovation is a blessing to mother nature as it has prevented the burning of coconut leaves, has played a part in reducing the usage of plastic straws and has empowered women in rural communities through employment. Also, this innovation has received several acknowledgments and awards, including the Shreshta Udyami Guru Puraskar 2020 from the entrepreneurship development institute of India and the first position at the startup launchpad by the ASSOCHAM, New Delhi.', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/sunbird-straw-drinking-straws-from-coconut-leaves/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Straws-page.png', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Straws-page.png"]'::jsonb, '["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lOB4blYxUtI"]'::jsonb, 'Bangalore , Karnataka', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Prof. Saji Varghese"},{"key":"Location","value":"Bangalore , Karnataka"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"According to a survey conducted in 2018, India creates 25,000 tons of plastic waste every year, of which only 9% is recycled. One of the classic examples of single-use plastic is plastic straws. Plastic products are majorly made from polypropylene, a material that degrades very slowly, out of which small items are even more difficult to recycle; hence materials like straws end up in a landfill or damage our oceans and marine wildlife. Professor Saji devised an alternative to replace plastic straws with eco-friendly straws made from coconut leaves. From 1 fallen coconut leaf, 150 -200 straws can be made; they realized it is a very good scalable and sustainable product and an alternative to plastic straws. The country aims to revolutionize rural employment and meet global demand. These straws are developed from falling coconut leaves which are abundant in our country and are mostly discarded or burned. As the first sample, Saji developed a single-layer coconut leaf straw in 2017. But by 2018, Prof. Saji came up with a final product of coconut leaf straws available, from regular ones to straws that can be used for cocktails, shakes, smoothies, and boba tea. These eco-friendly straws range from 4 to 8 inches long and 3 to 13 mm in diameter. They developed a 2nd gen machine (multi-purpose machine), which took 45s to develop one straw. They recently upgraded the technology and have developed a conveyor system where time has reduced to 1.5s from 45s, and fatigue is also reduced. Machines are developed in-house and are patented. The product process technology is also patented and has 31 claims under it. The company aims to employ 2000 women at the end of the year and reach production of 1 lakh/day. Prof. Saji has developed a start-up named Sunbird straw to make a difference. This innovation is a blessing to mother nature as it has prevented the burning of coconut leaves, has played a part in reducing the usage of plastic straws and has empowered women in rural communities through employment. Also, this innovation has received several acknowledgments and awards, including the Shreshta Udyami Guru Puraskar 2020 from the entrepreneurship development institute of India and the first position at the startup launchpad by the ASSOCHAM, New Delhi."},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lOB4blYxUtI"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['tree', 'machine']::text[], 'Sunbird straw: Drinking straws from coconut leaves Prof. Saji Varghese Bangalore , Karnataka Innovator cum associate professor at the department of English, Christ University, Bangalore professor Saji Varghese developed straws from coconut leaves that are fallen from trees as an eco-friendly alternative to the available plastic straws. Christ University initially funded the innovation, but GIAN and the Honey Bee Network eventually supported the project in whatever way needed. Straws developed from coconut leaves are a good alternative to plastic straws and create impact. Apart from these straws, they also started producing pens and pencils made of coconut leaves. Prof. Saji has received around 20 million orders for his innovative drinking straw. Professor Saji received many inquiries; he could send it to 10 countries, including the Netherlands, Australia, New Zealand, Canada, the Middle East, Belgium, the US, Dubai, and others. In India, Sunbird Straws onboarded major hotel chains like four seasons, 46 Ounces, and JW Marriot, and they all are repeat customers. The Philippines and people from other countries abroad have sent an inquiry to adopt their technology. According to a survey conducted in 2018, India creates 25,000 tons of plastic waste every year, of which only 9% is recycled. One of the classic examples of single-use plastic is plastic straws. Plastic products are majorly made from polypropylene, a material that degrades very slowly, out of which small items are even more difficult to recycle; hence materials like straws end up in a landfill or damage our oceans and marine wildlife. Professor Saji devised an alternative to replace plastic straws with eco-friendly straws made from coconut leaves. From 1 fallen coconut leaf, 150 -200 straws can be made; they realized it is a very good scalable and sustainable product and an alternative to plastic straws. The country aims to revolutionize rural employment and meet global demand. These straws are developed from falling coconut leaves which are abundant in our country and are mostly discarded or burned. As the first sample, Saji developed a single-layer coconut leaf straw in 2017. But by 2018, Prof. Saji came up with a final product of coconut leaf straws available, from regular ones to straws that can be used for cocktails, shakes, smoothies, and boba tea. These eco-friendly straws range from 4 to 8 inches long and 3 to 13 mm in diameter. They developed a 2nd gen machine (multi-purpose machine), which took 45s to develop one straw. They recently upgraded the technology and have developed a conveyor system where time has reduced to 1.5s from 45s, and fatigue is also reduced. Machines are developed in-house and are patented. The product process technology is also patented and has 31 claims under it. The company aims to employ 2000 women at the end of the year and reach production of 1 lakh/day. Prof. Saji has developed a start-up named Sunbird straw to make a difference. This innovation is a blessing to mother nature as it has prevented the burning of coconut leaves, has played a part in reducing the usage of plastic straws and has empowered women in rural communities through employment. Also, this innovation has received several acknowledgments and awards, including the Shreshta Udyami Guru Puraskar 2020 from the entrepreneurship development institute of India and the first position at the startup launchpad by the ASSOCHAM, New Delhi. tree machine https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lOB4blYxUtI', '{"innovation_slug":"sunbird-straw-drinking-straws-from-coconut-leaves","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/sunbird-straw-drinking-straws-from-coconut-leaves/","innovation_title":"Sunbird straw: Drinking straws from coconut leaves","innovator_name":"Prof. Saji Varghese","location":"Bangalore , Karnataka","innovator_bio":"Innovator cum associate professor at the department of English, Christ University, Bangalore professor Saji Varghese developed straws from coconut leaves that are fallen from trees as an eco-friendly alternative to the available plastic straws. Christ University initially funded the innovation, but GIAN and the Honey Bee Network eventually supported the project in whatever way needed. Straws developed from coconut leaves are a good alternative to plastic straws and create impact. Apart from these straws, they also started producing pens and pencils made of coconut leaves. Prof. Saji has received around 20 million orders for his innovative drinking straw. Professor Saji received many inquiries; he could send it to 10 countries, including the Netherlands, Australia, New Zealand, Canada, the Middle East, Belgium, the US, Dubai, and others. In India, Sunbird Straws onboarded major hotel chains like four seasons, 46 Ounces, and JW Marriot, and they all are repeat customers. The Philippines and people from other countries abroad have sent an inquiry to adopt their technology.","innovation_details":"According to a survey conducted in 2018, India creates 25,000 tons of plastic waste every year, of which only 9% is recycled. One of the classic examples of single-use plastic is plastic straws. Plastic products are majorly made from polypropylene, a material that degrades very slowly, out of which small items are even more difficult to recycle; hence materials like straws end up in a landfill or damage our oceans and marine wildlife. Professor Saji devised an alternative to replace plastic straws with eco-friendly straws made from coconut leaves. From 1 fallen coconut leaf, 150 -200 straws can be made; they realized it is a very good scalable and sustainable product and an alternative to plastic straws. The country aims to revolutionize rural employment and meet global demand. These straws are developed from falling coconut leaves which are abundant in our country and are mostly discarded or burned. As the first sample, Saji developed a single-layer coconut leaf straw in 2017. But by 2018, Prof. Saji came up with a final product of coconut leaf straws available, from regular ones to straws that can be used for cocktails, shakes, smoothies, and boba tea. These eco-friendly straws range from 4 to 8 inches long and 3 to 13 mm in diameter. They developed a 2nd gen machine (multi-purpose machine), which took 45s to develop one straw. They recently upgraded the technology and have developed a conveyor system where time has reduced to 1.5s from 45s, and fatigue is also reduced. Machines are developed in-house and are patented. The product process technology is also patented and has 31 claims under it. The company aims to employ 2000 women at the end of the year and reach production of 1 lakh/day. Prof. Saji has developed a start-up named Sunbird straw to make a difference. This innovation is a blessing to mother nature as it has prevented the burning of coconut leaves, has played a part in reducing the usage of plastic straws and has empowered women in rural communities through employment. Also, this innovation has received several acknowledgments and awards, including the Shreshta Udyami Guru Puraskar 2020 from the entrepreneurship development institute of India and the first position at the startup launchpad by the ASSOCHAM, New Delhi.","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG_20230313_103757_404.webp"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Straws-page.png"],"multimedia_links":["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lOB4blYxUtI"],"tags":["tree","machine"],"latitude":12.9866413,"longitude":77.4904285,"listing_excerpt":"Sunbird straw: Drinking straws from coconut leaves"}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('battery-operated-bike', 'manish-patel-deoria-uttar-pradesh', 'Manish Patel', 'Battery-operated bike', 'So many youngsters often ride bikes without wearing helmets and after drinking alcohol. Being a young innovator, Manish thought of innovating a device with a bike so that if a rider is not wearing a helmet or is under the influence of alcohol, the bike will not run. Manish then fabricated his circuits for a cycle with the dynamo attached. The sensors present in the circuit detect the faces and smell alcohol, so if the rider is not wearing a helmet or is under the influence of alcohol, the bike will not start. It will greatly help to prevent drunk driving and accident casualties. The bike prototype is ready but yet to commercialize as the innovator needs more help with design inputs, manufacturability, and robustness of the functionality. The innovation has been successfully presented at the IIC’s People’s Festival of Innovation.', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/battery-operated-bike/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-04-11-at-19.49.31-1024x768.jpeg', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-04-11-at-19.49.31-1024x768.jpeg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-04-11-at-19.49.31.jpeg"]'::jsonb, '["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G1GafdcqpNo"]'::jsonb, 'Deoria , Uttar Pradesh', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Manish Patel"},{"key":"Location","value":"Deoria , Uttar Pradesh"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"So many youngsters often ride bikes without wearing helmets and after drinking alcohol. Being a young innovator, Manish thought of innovating a device with a bike so that if a rider is not wearing a helmet or is under the influence of alcohol, the bike will not run. Manish then fabricated his circuits for a cycle with the dynamo attached. The sensors present in the circuit detect the faces and smell alcohol, so if the rider is not wearing a helmet or is under the influence of alcohol, the bike will not start. It will greatly help to prevent drunk driving and accident casualties. The bike prototype is ready but yet to commercialize as the innovator needs more help with design inputs, manufacturability, and robustness of the functionality. The innovation has been successfully presented at the IIC’s People’s Festival of Innovation."},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G1GafdcqpNo"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['device']::text[], 'Battery-operated bike Manish Patel Deoria , Uttar Pradesh A student innovator Manish Patel innovated a battery-operated bike that will not allow the rider to ride without a helmet and after drinking alcohol. The Honey Bee Network and GIAN governed this innovation. The innovation is unique and has been appreciated by many innovators. GIAN helped the innovator with marketing and participation in different events for more visibility. The innovation is with advanced technology and is successfully prototyped. So many youngsters often ride bikes without wearing helmets and after drinking alcohol. Being a young innovator, Manish thought of innovating a device with a bike so that if a rider is not wearing a helmet or is under the influence of alcohol, the bike will not run. Manish then fabricated his circuits for a cycle with the dynamo attached. The sensors present in the circuit detect the faces and smell alcohol, so if the rider is not wearing a helmet or is under the influence of alcohol, the bike will not start. It will greatly help to prevent drunk driving and accident casualties. The bike prototype is ready but yet to commercialize as the innovator needs more help with design inputs, manufacturability, and robustness of the functionality. The innovation has been successfully presented at the IIC’s People’s Festival of Innovation. device https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G1GafdcqpNo', '{"innovation_slug":"battery-operated-bike","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/battery-operated-bike/","innovation_title":"Battery-operated bike","innovator_name":"Manish Patel","location":"Deoria , Uttar Pradesh","innovator_bio":"A student innovator Manish Patel innovated a battery-operated bike that will not allow the rider to ride without a helmet and after drinking alcohol. The Honey Bee Network and GIAN governed this innovation. The innovation is unique and has been appreciated by many innovators. GIAN helped the innovator with marketing and participation in different events for more visibility. The innovation is with advanced technology and is successfully prototyped.","innovation_details":"So many youngsters often ride bikes without wearing helmets and after drinking alcohol. Being a young innovator, Manish thought of innovating a device with a bike so that if a rider is not wearing a helmet or is under the influence of alcohol, the bike will not run. Manish then fabricated his circuits for a cycle with the dynamo attached. The sensors present in the circuit detect the faces and smell alcohol, so if the rider is not wearing a helmet or is under the influence of alcohol, the bike will not start. It will greatly help to prevent drunk driving and accident casualties. The bike prototype is ready but yet to commercialize as the innovator needs more help with design inputs, manufacturability, and robustness of the functionality. The innovation has been successfully presented at the IIC’s People’s Festival of Innovation.","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/manish-patel.jpeg"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-04-11-at-19.49.31-1024x768.jpeg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-04-11-at-19.49.31.jpeg"],"multimedia_links":["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=G1GafdcqpNo"],"tags":["device"],"latitude":26.2111973,"longitude":83.985008,"listing_excerpt":"Manish Patel"}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('tractor-mounted-mini-crane-by-niki-bharatbhai-parmar-gujarat', 'niki-bharatbhai-parmar-amreli-gujarat', 'Niki Bharatbhai Parmar', 'Tractor-mounted mini crane by Niki Bharatbhai Parmar (Gujarat)', 'An engineer thought of a tractor-mounted mini crane that can be used when the place is congested, and a huge industrial crane cannot be used. The mini attachments are equipped with advanced technologies and all the necessary tools to carry out assigned tasks efficiently. It can also be customized as per the customers’ requirements. It is a great alternative and will directly create employment opportunities for the operator. It can also be aided in farming and infrastructure building. It is a mini crane that can be mounted to any 25 HP tractor, providing an option to small-scale buyers across India who earlier were strained by high-cost machines. At first, they created a modified crane design according to its usage and capacity of 1.5 tons. They made it cost-effective as 80% of customers needed such equipment but could not afford it. Their focus was on tractor attachments because it is the only viable and feasible machine that farmers can afford and is easily available. A project of a 360-degree mounted crane starts around 12- 16 lakhs in the market; Parmar engineers launched it at the cost of 5-8 lakhs. Then after tractor-mounted loaders, which come for 4.5 lahks in the market, they made similar models for 1.5-2 lakhs. Niki Parmar also designed a stone picker machine and sold it in Akola, Maharashtra, which was five lakhs in the market, and he made it available for 2.5 lahks. They focus on equipment customization, giving them the upper hand in the market because very few companies offer customized products. The innovation was successful, and the order flow is also quite high. In total, they have sold 200+ mini cranes since 2015, more than 200 mini loaders, 360 degrees sold five units; and in 3 months, they managed to sell six stone pickers. In 2018 their turnover was ten lakhs; in 2020, it was 83 lakhs; and in the last audit, Parmar engineer’s turnover was 1.9 Cr', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/tractor-mounted-mini-crane-by-niki-bharatbhai-parmar-gujarat/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/enlarge_product-jpeg-500x5001-2.png', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/enlarge_product-jpeg-500x5001-2.png"]'::jsonb, '["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VeSu7Bvsr9s"]'::jsonb, 'Amreli , Gujarat', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Niki Bharatbhai Parmar"},{"key":"Location","value":"Amreli , Gujarat"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"An engineer thought of a tractor-mounted mini crane that can be used when the place is congested, and a huge industrial crane cannot be used. The mini attachments are equipped with advanced technologies and all the necessary tools to carry out assigned tasks efficiently. It can also be customized as per the customers’ requirements. It is a great alternative and will directly create employment opportunities for the operator. It can also be aided in farming and infrastructure building. It is a mini crane that can be mounted to any 25 HP tractor, providing an option to small-scale buyers across India who earlier were strained by high-cost machines. At first, they created a modified crane design according to its usage and capacity of 1.5 tons. They made it cost-effective as 80% of customers needed such equipment but could not afford it. Their focus was on tractor attachments because it is the only viable and feasible machine that farmers can afford and is easily available. A project of a 360-degree mounted crane starts around 12- 16 lakhs in the market; Parmar engineers launched it at the cost of 5-8 lakhs. Then after tractor-mounted loaders, which come for 4.5 lahks in the market, they made similar models for 1.5-2 lakhs. Niki Parmar also designed a stone picker machine and sold it in Akola, Maharashtra, which was five lakhs in the market, and he made it available for 2.5 lahks. They focus on equipment customization, giving them the upper hand in the market because very few companies offer customized products. The innovation was successful, and the order flow is also quite high. In total, they have sold 200+ mini cranes since 2015, more than 200 mini loaders, 360 degrees sold five units; and in 3 months, they managed to sell six stone pickers. In 2018 their turnover was ten lakhs; in 2020, it was 83 lakhs; and in the last audit, Parmar engineer’s turnover was 1.9 Cr"},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VeSu7Bvsr9s"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['tool', 'machine', 'farmer']::text[], 'Tractor-mounted mini crane by Niki Bharatbhai Parmar (Gujarat) Niki Bharatbhai Parmar Amreli , Gujarat The innovator Niki Bharatbhai Parmar, based in Amreli, Gujarat, innovated a tractor-mounted crane that is portable, low-cost, and more efficient. The innovation was appreciated and aided by the Honey Bee Network and GIAN. Niki Bharatbhai Parmar owns Parmar Engineers, and other than mini cranes, there are several products under the brand name of Parmar Engineers. Apart from this, Niki has also started making firefighting equipment and several other innovations and modifications for different types of crops which are not yet present in the market. They are passionate and are doing a lot of R&D in this field. An engineer thought of a tractor-mounted mini crane that can be used when the place is congested, and a huge industrial crane cannot be used. The mini attachments are equipped with advanced technologies and all the necessary tools to carry out assigned tasks efficiently. It can also be customized as per the customers’ requirements. It is a great alternative and will directly create employment opportunities for the operator. It can also be aided in farming and infrastructure building. It is a mini crane that can be mounted to any 25 HP tractor, providing an option to small-scale buyers across India who earlier were strained by high-cost machines. At first, they created a modified crane design according to its usage and capacity of 1.5 tons. They made it cost-effective as 80% of customers needed such equipment but could not afford it. Their focus was on tractor attachments because it is the only viable and feasible machine that farmers can afford and is easily available. A project of a 360-degree mounted crane starts around 12- 16 lakhs in the market; Parmar engineers launched it at the cost of 5-8 lakhs. Then after tractor-mounted loaders, which come for 4.5 lahks in the market, they made similar models for 1.5-2 lakhs. Niki Parmar also designed a stone picker machine and sold it in Akola, Maharashtra, which was five lakhs in the market, and he made it available for 2.5 lahks. They focus on equipment customization, giving them the upper hand in the market because very few companies offer customized products. The innovation was successful, and the order flow is also quite high. In total, they have sold 200+ mini cranes since 2015, more than 200 mini loaders, 360 degrees sold five units; and in 3 months, they managed to sell six stone pickers. In 2018 their turnover was ten lakhs; in 2020, it was 83 lakhs; and in the last audit, Parmar engineer’s turnover was 1.9 Cr tool machine farmer https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VeSu7Bvsr9s', '{"innovation_slug":"tractor-mounted-mini-crane-by-niki-bharatbhai-parmar-gujarat","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/tractor-mounted-mini-crane-by-niki-bharatbhai-parmar-gujarat/","innovation_title":"Tractor-mounted mini crane by Niki Bharatbhai Parmar (Gujarat)","innovator_name":"Niki Bharatbhai Parmar","location":"Amreli , Gujarat","innovator_bio":"The innovator Niki Bharatbhai Parmar, based in Amreli, Gujarat, innovated a tractor-mounted crane that is portable, low-cost, and more efficient. The innovation was appreciated and aided by the Honey Bee Network and GIAN. Niki Bharatbhai Parmar owns Parmar Engineers, and other than mini cranes, there are several products under the brand name of Parmar Engineers. Apart from this, Niki has also started making firefighting equipment and several other innovations and modifications for different types of crops which are not yet present in the market. They are passionate and are doing a lot of R&D in this field.","innovation_details":"An engineer thought of a tractor-mounted mini crane that can be used when the place is congested, and a huge industrial crane cannot be used. The mini attachments are equipped with advanced technologies and all the necessary tools to carry out assigned tasks efficiently. It can also be customized as per the customers’ requirements. It is a great alternative and will directly create employment opportunities for the operator. It can also be aided in farming and infrastructure building. It is a mini crane that can be mounted to any 25 HP tractor, providing an option to small-scale buyers across India who earlier were strained by high-cost machines. At first, they created a modified crane design according to its usage and capacity of 1.5 tons. They made it cost-effective as 80% of customers needed such equipment but could not afford it. Their focus was on tractor attachments because it is the only viable and feasible machine that farmers can afford and is easily available. A project of a 360-degree mounted crane starts around 12- 16 lakhs in the market; Parmar engineers launched it at the cost of 5-8 lakhs. Then after tractor-mounted loaders, which come for 4.5 lahks in the market, they made similar models for 1.5-2 lakhs. Niki Parmar also designed a stone picker machine and sold it in Akola, Maharashtra, which was five lakhs in the market, and he made it available for 2.5 lahks. They focus on equipment customization, giving them the upper hand in the market because very few companies offer customized products. The innovation was successful, and the order flow is also quite high. In total, they have sold 200+ mini cranes since 2015, more than 200 mini loaders, 360 degrees sold five units; and in 3 months, they managed to sell six stone pickers. In 2018 their turnover was ten lakhs; in 2020, it was 83 lakhs; and in the last audit, Parmar engineer’s turnover was 1.9 Cr","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Nikki-parmar-tractor-mounted-mini-crane-11.jpg"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/enlarge_product-jpeg-500x5001-2.png"],"multimedia_links":["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VeSu7Bvsr9s"],"tags":["tool","machine","farmer"],"latitude":21.6425971,"longitude":71.2161428,"listing_excerpt":"Niki Bharatbhai Parmar"}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('bamboo-splint-and-stick-making-machine', 'ralte-and-l-salio-aizawl-mizoram', 'Ralte and L Salio', 'Bamboo Splint and Stick Making Machine', 'Making strips and sticks with the conventional knife method is time-consuming, tedious, and risky. Electrically operated high-power machines are available for industries; the rural community cannot afford such tools due to the village’s lack of electricity and finances. Ralte and L. Salio decided to create an affordable bamboo splint and stick-making machine to assist the tribal community in overcoming the problems associated with the traditional method. The innovator successfully prototyped a manually operated bamboo splint-making machine that can convert bamboo into 1.2 mm thick strips and sticks. It is made of carbon steel and has a capacity of 5,000 splints/hour or 5 kg /hour. It is easy to operate, affordable, and easy to maintain. It can be used to generate employment in rural areas and to make toothpicks, ice cream sticks, etc. They have been recognized for their innovation all around the country and are getting inquiries for sale in Brazil and Sri Lanka', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/bamboo-splint-and-stick-making-machine/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/ralte.png', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/ralte.png"]'::jsonb, '["https://youtu.be/0cjtLGVgpcY?si=8dRyPCZiW8bgABEy"]'::jsonb, 'Aizawl , Mizoram', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Ralte and L Salio"},{"key":"Location","value":"Aizawl , Mizoram"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"Making strips and sticks with the conventional knife method is time-consuming, tedious, and risky. Electrically operated high-power machines are available for industries; the rural community cannot afford such tools due to the village’s lack of electricity and finances. Ralte and L. Salio decided to create an affordable bamboo splint and stick-making machine to assist the tribal community in overcoming the problems associated with the traditional method. The innovator successfully prototyped a manually operated bamboo splint-making machine that can convert bamboo into 1.2 mm thick strips and sticks. It is made of carbon steel and has a capacity of 5,000 splints/hour or 5 kg /hour. It is easy to operate, affordable, and easy to maintain. It can be used to generate employment in rural areas and to make toothpicks, ice cream sticks, etc. They have been recognized for their innovation all around the country and are getting inquiries for sale in Brazil and Sri Lanka"},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://youtu.be/0cjtLGVgpcY?si=8dRyPCZiW8bgABEy"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['tool', 'machine', 'water', 'bamboo']::text[], 'Bamboo Splint and Stick Making Machine Ralte and L Salio Aizawl , Mizoram The innovators, Ralte and L Salio from Aizawl, Mizoram, developed a bamboo splint and stick-making machine which can be used for incense stick-making. This machine is manually operated and hence is eco-friendly. It was supported and guided by the Honey Bee Network and GIAN under the MVIF scheme. In the whole world, India is the largest producer of incense sticks. They are mostly manufactured in the interior part of northeastern states (like Tripura, Assam, Mizoram, etc.) by tribal people. This innovation is a boon for the tribal community of India, and innovators have managed to sell more than 2500 units in the northeastern hilly state of India and neighboring states of Nepal and Bangladesh. The innovator has also developed prototypes, such as room lighting systems, river water-operated grinders, and huskers. Making strips and sticks with the conventional knife method is time-consuming, tedious, and risky. Electrically operated high-power machines are available for industries; the rural community cannot afford such tools due to the village’s lack of electricity and finances. Ralte and L. Salio decided to create an affordable bamboo splint and stick-making machine to assist the tribal community in overcoming the problems associated with the traditional method. The innovator successfully prototyped a manually operated bamboo splint-making machine that can convert bamboo into 1.2 mm thick strips and sticks. It is made of carbon steel and has a capacity of 5,000 splints/hour or 5 kg /hour. It is easy to operate, affordable, and easy to maintain. It can be used to generate employment in rural areas and to make toothpicks, ice cream sticks, etc. They have been recognized for their innovation all around the country and are getting inquiries for sale in Brazil and Sri Lanka tool machine water bamboo https://youtu.be/0cjtLGVgpcY?si=8dRyPCZiW8bgABEy', '{"innovation_slug":"bamboo-splint-and-stick-making-machine","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/bamboo-splint-and-stick-making-machine/","innovation_title":"Bamboo Splint and Stick Making Machine","innovator_name":"Ralte and L Salio","location":"Aizawl , Mizoram","innovator_bio":"The innovators, Ralte and L Salio from Aizawl, Mizoram, developed a bamboo splint and stick-making machine which can be used for incense stick-making. This machine is manually operated and hence is eco-friendly. It was supported and guided by the Honey Bee Network and GIAN under the MVIF scheme. In the whole world, India is the largest producer of incense sticks. They are mostly manufactured in the interior part of northeastern states (like Tripura, Assam, Mizoram, etc.) by tribal people. This innovation is a boon for the tribal community of India, and innovators have managed to sell more than 2500 units in the northeastern hilly state of India and neighboring states of Nepal and Bangladesh. The innovator has also developed prototypes, such as room lighting systems, river water-operated grinders, and huskers.","innovation_details":"Making strips and sticks with the conventional knife method is time-consuming, tedious, and risky. Electrically operated high-power machines are available for industries; the rural community cannot afford such tools due to the village’s lack of electricity and finances. Ralte and L. Salio decided to create an affordable bamboo splint and stick-making machine to assist the tribal community in overcoming the problems associated with the traditional method. The innovator successfully prototyped a manually operated bamboo splint-making machine that can convert bamboo into 1.2 mm thick strips and sticks. It is made of carbon steel and has a capacity of 5,000 splints/hour or 5 kg /hour. It is easy to operate, affordable, and easy to maintain. It can be used to generate employment in rural areas and to make toothpicks, ice cream sticks, etc. They have been recognized for their innovation all around the country and are getting inquiries for sale in Brazil and Sri Lanka","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG-20230310-WA0006.jpg"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/ralte.png"],"multimedia_links":["https://youtu.be/0cjtLGVgpcY?si=8dRyPCZiW8bgABEy"],"tags":["tool","machine","water","bamboo"],"latitude":23.734269387887775,"longitude":92.72361797130237,"listing_excerpt":"Ralte and L. Salio"}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('cow-dung-pot-making-machines-by-gopal-surtia-and-paresh-panchal-gujarat', 'gopal-surtia-right-and-paresh-panchal-left-ahmedabad-gujarat', 'Gopal Surtia (right) and Paresh Panchal (left)', 'Cow dung pot-making machines by Gopal Surtia and Paresh Panchal (Gujarat)', 'The innovative idea came from Gopal Surtia, who made a crude pot manually. Gopal developed the idea of a cow dung pot machine, and Paresh Panchal was connected with him by the Honey Bee Network to design and modify it. The innovators have used animal manure, locally known as cow dung and wheat flour, in the ratio of 20:1 kg, along with agricultural waste and basic raw materials to prepare eco-friendly pots. Spoiled bajra flowers or shells of caster leaves or neem leaves were used in the mixture to protect the pot from pest attacks, as they have insecticidal properties that prevent termite attacks. The innovation is biodegradable and eco-friendly. The leaching of nutrients is prevented as the water absorption rate of the pot is very slow. It has advantages such as faster growth of the plant as it is made of cow dung, and employment generation is possible through local manufacturing and sourcing of these cow dung pots. This innovation of garden pot-making machines has employed jail inmates. It was successfully incorporated by Dharamshala prison. The forest departments and prisons of many states in India are using it. It won many awards and was showcased at Rashtrapati Bhavan at the festival of innovation by the Honey Bee Network and the National Innovation Foundation.', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/cow-dung-pot-making-machines-by-gopal-surtia-and-paresh-panchal-gujarat/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/paresh-bhai-innovation-1.jpeg', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/paresh-bhai-innovation-1.jpeg"]'::jsonb, '["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xT__jkmano0"]'::jsonb, 'Ahmedabad , Gujarat', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Gopal Surtia (right) and Paresh Panchal (left)"},{"key":"Location","value":"Ahmedabad , Gujarat"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"The innovative idea came from Gopal Surtia, who made a crude pot manually. Gopal developed the idea of a cow dung pot machine, and Paresh Panchal was connected with him by the Honey Bee Network to design and modify it. The innovators have used animal manure, locally known as cow dung and wheat flour, in the ratio of 20:1 kg, along with agricultural waste and basic raw materials to prepare eco-friendly pots. Spoiled bajra flowers or shells of caster leaves or neem leaves were used in the mixture to protect the pot from pest attacks, as they have insecticidal properties that prevent termite attacks. The innovation is biodegradable and eco-friendly. The leaching of nutrients is prevented as the water absorption rate of the pot is very slow. It has advantages such as faster growth of the plant as it is made of cow dung, and employment generation is possible through local manufacturing and sourcing of these cow dung pots. This innovation of garden pot-making machines has employed jail inmates. It was successfully incorporated by Dharamshala prison. The forest departments and prisons of many states in India are using it. It won many awards and was showcased at Rashtrapati Bhavan at the festival of innovation by the Honey Bee Network and the National Innovation Foundation."},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xT__jkmano0"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['machine', 'water']::text[], 'Cow dung pot-making machines by Gopal Surtia and Paresh Panchal (Gujarat) Gopal Surtia (right) and Paresh Panchal (left) Ahmedabad , Gujarat The cow dung pot-making machine was innovated by two innovators, Gopal Bhai Surtia and Prakash Bhai Panchal, from Ahmedabad, Gujarat. This eco-friendly, sustainable innovation was successfully developed and marketed with the help of the Honey Bee Network and GIAN. Also, both innovators filed a patent for the machine in the year 2017 with the help of GIAN. It is an eco-friendly manufacturing machine that does not cause any pollution. The innovators have already sold multiple units of the innovative product. The innovative idea came from Gopal Surtia, who made a crude pot manually. Gopal developed the idea of a cow dung pot machine, and Paresh Panchal was connected with him by the Honey Bee Network to design and modify it. The innovators have used animal manure, locally known as cow dung and wheat flour, in the ratio of 20:1 kg, along with agricultural waste and basic raw materials to prepare eco-friendly pots. Spoiled bajra flowers or shells of caster leaves or neem leaves were used in the mixture to protect the pot from pest attacks, as they have insecticidal properties that prevent termite attacks. The innovation is biodegradable and eco-friendly. The leaching of nutrients is prevented as the water absorption rate of the pot is very slow. It has advantages such as faster growth of the plant as it is made of cow dung, and employment generation is possible through local manufacturing and sourcing of these cow dung pots. This innovation of garden pot-making machines has employed jail inmates. It was successfully incorporated by Dharamshala prison. The forest departments and prisons of many states in India are using it. It won many awards and was showcased at Rashtrapati Bhavan at the festival of innovation by the Honey Bee Network and the National Innovation Foundation. machine water https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xT__jkmano0', '{"innovation_slug":"cow-dung-pot-making-machines-by-gopal-surtia-and-paresh-panchal-gujarat","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/cow-dung-pot-making-machines-by-gopal-surtia-and-paresh-panchal-gujarat/","innovation_title":"Cow dung pot-making machines by Gopal Surtia and Paresh Panchal (Gujarat)","innovator_name":"Gopal Surtia (right) and Paresh Panchal (left)","location":"Ahmedabad , Gujarat","innovator_bio":"The cow dung pot-making machine was innovated by two innovators, Gopal Bhai Surtia and Prakash Bhai Panchal, from Ahmedabad, Gujarat. This eco-friendly, sustainable innovation was successfully developed and marketed with the help of the Honey Bee Network and GIAN. Also, both innovators filed a patent for the machine in the year 2017 with the help of GIAN. It is an eco-friendly manufacturing machine that does not cause any pollution. The innovators have already sold multiple units of the innovative product.","innovation_details":"The innovative idea came from Gopal Surtia, who made a crude pot manually. Gopal developed the idea of a cow dung pot machine, and Paresh Panchal was connected with him by the Honey Bee Network to design and modify it. The innovators have used animal manure, locally known as cow dung and wheat flour, in the ratio of 20:1 kg, along with agricultural waste and basic raw materials to prepare eco-friendly pots. Spoiled bajra flowers or shells of caster leaves or neem leaves were used in the mixture to protect the pot from pest attacks, as they have insecticidal properties that prevent termite attacks. The innovation is biodegradable and eco-friendly. The leaching of nutrients is prevented as the water absorption rate of the pot is very slow. It has advantages such as faster growth of the plant as it is made of cow dung, and employment generation is possible through local manufacturing and sourcing of these cow dung pots. This innovation of garden pot-making machines has employed jail inmates. It was successfully incorporated by Dharamshala prison. The forest departments and prisons of many states in India are using it. It won many awards and was showcased at Rashtrapati Bhavan at the festival of innovation by the Honey Bee Network and the National Innovation Foundation.","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Gopalbhai_suritya-imageonline.co-merged.png"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/paresh-bhai-innovation-1.jpeg"],"multimedia_links":["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xT__jkmano0"],"tags":["machine","water"],"latitude":23.0513311,"longitude":72.5319491,"listing_excerpt":"Gopal Surtia and Paresh Panchal"}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('improved-varieties-of-wheat-paddy-and-pigeon-pe', 'prakash-singh-raghuvanshi-varanasi-uttar-pradesh', 'Prakash Singh Raghuvanshi', 'Improved varieties of wheat, paddy, and pigeon pea by Prakash Singh Raghuvanshi (Uttar Pradesh)', 'Prakash likes to keep himself updated in the field of agriculture, and hence he regularly participates in agricultural fairs and meets scientists and agricultural officers. The inspiration for the innovation came from Dr. Mahatim Singh, former professor at Banaras Hindu University (BHU) and former vice chancellor of GB Pant, University of Agriculture and Technology (GBPUAT). Dr. Singh motivated Prakash to develop varieties that could be useful for other farmers to increase their yield and improve their livelihood.Prakash has developed numerous improved high-yielding wheat, paddy, and pigeon pea varieties with the best disease-resistant seeds and good flavors. Prakash developed all these varieties using the simple selection-based method in which specific characteristic features of the plants are observed. The new, improved variety of wheat, paddy, and pigeon pea gives around 27, 30, and 12 quintals per acre of yield, respectively.He has distributed his variety of seeds to the farmers of almost all the states of India and has received appreciable reports and feedback. He has participated in the National Innovation Foundation’s informal research advisory committee for evaluating technologies for the fourth competition. He has also participated in many agricultural Mila and food festivals that received a great response for his varieties. He was also awarded at the 4th National National Grassroots Innovations and traditional knowledge competition in 2007.', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/improved-varieties-of-wheat-paddy-and-pigeon-pe/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-04-08-at-12.53.41-768x1024.jpeg', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-04-08-at-12.53.41-768x1024.jpeg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-04-08-at-15.25.54.jpeg"]'::jsonb, '["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CxR9PfYZgAA"]'::jsonb, 'Varanasi , Uttar Pradesh', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Prakash Singh Raghuvanshi"},{"key":"Location","value":"Varanasi , Uttar Pradesh"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"Prakash likes to keep himself updated in the field of agriculture, and hence he regularly participates in agricultural fairs and meets scientists and agricultural officers. The inspiration for the innovation came from Dr. Mahatim Singh, former professor at Banaras Hindu University (BHU) and former vice chancellor of GB Pant, University of Agriculture and Technology (GBPUAT). Dr. Singh motivated Prakash to develop varieties that could be useful for other farmers to increase their yield and improve their livelihood.Prakash has developed numerous improved high-yielding wheat, paddy, and pigeon pea varieties with the best disease-resistant seeds and good flavors. Prakash developed all these varieties using the simple selection-based method in which specific characteristic features of the plants are observed. The new, improved variety of wheat, paddy, and pigeon pea gives around 27, 30, and 12 quintals per acre of yield, respectively.He has distributed his variety of seeds to the farmers of almost all the states of India and has received appreciable reports and feedback. He has participated in the National Innovation Foundation’s informal research advisory committee for evaluating technologies for the fourth competition. He has also participated in many agricultural Mila and food festivals that received a great response for his varieties. He was also awarded at the 4th National National Grassroots Innovations and traditional knowledge competition in 2007."},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CxR9PfYZgAA"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['agriculture', 'food', 'farmer', 'livelihood']::text[], 'Improved varieties of wheat, paddy, and pigeon pea by Prakash Singh Raghuvanshi (Uttar Pradesh) Prakash Singh Raghuvanshi Varanasi , Uttar Pradesh A 49 years old innovator and enterprising farmer from Varanasi, Uttar Pradesh, who believes in promoting self-sustainability, has developed better and high-yielding wheat, paddy, and pigeon pea varieties, supported by the Honey Bee Network and GIAN under MVIF in association with NIF. Prakash’s brother owns a seed company and sells the seeds developed by him. Prakash owns three and a half acres of agricultural land on which he cultivates wheat, paddy, and pigeon peas. Instead of just farming, Prakash works hard to develop an improved variety of crops so that good quality seeds of higher-yielding varieties can benefit farmers and the country. Prakash likes to keep himself updated in the field of agriculture, and hence he regularly participates in agricultural fairs and meets scientists and agricultural officers. The inspiration for the innovation came from Dr. Mahatim Singh, former professor at Banaras Hindu University (BHU) and former vice chancellor of GB Pant, University of Agriculture and Technology (GBPUAT). Dr. Singh motivated Prakash to develop varieties that could be useful for other farmers to increase their yield and improve their livelihood.Prakash has developed numerous improved high-yielding wheat, paddy, and pigeon pea varieties with the best disease-resistant seeds and good flavors. Prakash developed all these varieties using the simple selection-based method in which specific characteristic features of the plants are observed. The new, improved variety of wheat, paddy, and pigeon pea gives around 27, 30, and 12 quintals per acre of yield, respectively.He has distributed his variety of seeds to the farmers of almost all the states of India and has received appreciable reports and feedback. He has participated in the National Innovation Foundation’s informal research advisory committee for evaluating technologies for the fourth competition. He has also participated in many agricultural Mila and food festivals that received a great response for his varieties. He was also awarded at the 4th National National Grassroots Innovations and traditional knowledge competition in 2007. agriculture food farmer livelihood https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CxR9PfYZgAA', '{"innovation_slug":"improved-varieties-of-wheat-paddy-and-pigeon-pe","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/improved-varieties-of-wheat-paddy-and-pigeon-pe/","innovation_title":"Improved varieties of wheat, paddy, and pigeon pea by Prakash Singh Raghuvanshi (Uttar Pradesh)","innovator_name":"Prakash Singh Raghuvanshi","location":"Varanasi , Uttar Pradesh","innovator_bio":"A 49 years old innovator and enterprising farmer from Varanasi, Uttar Pradesh, who believes in promoting self-sustainability, has developed better and high-yielding wheat, paddy, and pigeon pea varieties, supported by the Honey Bee Network and GIAN under MVIF in association with NIF. Prakash’s brother owns a seed company and sells the seeds developed by him. Prakash owns three and a half acres of agricultural land on which he cultivates wheat, paddy, and pigeon peas. Instead of just farming, Prakash works hard to develop an improved variety of crops so that good quality seeds of higher-yielding varieties can benefit farmers and the country.","innovation_details":"Prakash likes to keep himself updated in the field of agriculture, and hence he regularly participates in agricultural fairs and meets scientists and agricultural officers. The inspiration for the innovation came from Dr. Mahatim Singh, former professor at Banaras Hindu University (BHU) and former vice chancellor of GB Pant, University of Agriculture and Technology (GBPUAT). Dr. Singh motivated Prakash to develop varieties that could be useful for other farmers to increase their yield and improve their livelihood.Prakash has developed numerous improved high-yielding wheat, paddy, and pigeon pea varieties with the best disease-resistant seeds and good flavors. Prakash developed all these varieties using the simple selection-based method in which specific characteristic features of the plants are observed. The new, improved variety of wheat, paddy, and pigeon pea gives around 27, 30, and 12 quintals per acre of yield, respectively.He has distributed his variety of seeds to the farmers of almost all the states of India and has received appreciable reports and feedback. He has participated in the National Innovation Foundation’s informal research advisory committee for evaluating technologies for the fourth competition. He has also participated in many agricultural Mila and food festivals that received a great response for his varieties. He was also awarded at the 4th National National Grassroots Innovations and traditional knowledge competition in 2007.","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-04-08-at-12.53.39.jpeg"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-04-08-at-12.53.41-768x1024.jpeg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-04-08-at-15.25.54.jpeg"],"multimedia_links":["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CxR9PfYZgAA"],"tags":["agriculture","food","farmer","livelihood"],"latitude":25.1941606,"longitude":82.8532928,"listing_excerpt":"Improved varieties of wheat, paddy, and pigeon pea by Prakash Singh Raghuvanshi (Uttar Pradesh)"}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('biomass-gasifier-system', 'rai-singh-dahiya-hanumangarh-rajasthan', 'Rai Singh Dahiya', 'Biomass Gasifier System', 'Back in 1982, Rai Singh had set up a kiln for baking bricks which had a capacity of 12000 bricks. He observed that burning wood and other fuels in the kiln produced some gas that was burning more furiously. In 1991, Singh started his workshop repairing tractors, Jeep trucks, and other engines. After observing the increasing demand and price for diesel engines in the agricultural sector, he decided to modify the diesel engine to operate on an economical LPG. After this LPG engine was successful, he considered making an engine that could run on wood-burning gas. Then after a series of experiments, he successfully developed a device that consists of a gasifier that helps convert biomass into producer gas. The conventional diesel engine was then modified with a spark plug and a fuel pump with a distributor setup. The modified diesel engine was running using the gasifier but for a very short time. Singh found the glitch in the device, and impurities in the producer gas and worked out several mechanisms and filtering sieves to develop a filtering mechanism so that gas could be supplied to the modified engine. He successfully developed his biomass gasifier system, reducing maintenance and increasing the capability to operate for 40 hours continuously. The system is a success as it uses all types of wood waste and fuel. Wood stocks of cotton pulses, coconut shells and palm stocks, maize cobs, branches and twigs, various agricultural residues, certain industrial waste of paper, plywood, etc. The reported fuel consumption of the system is 1 kg/kVA, approximately 30 to 35%, less than conventional gasifiers. Singh’s biomass gasifier system has won many awards for sustainable technological development. He was also honored at Rashtrapati Bhavan by NIF. In 2002, he was honored by the gram panchayat, and in 2004 by the district collector. The innovator has also been awarded a national award in the 5th Biennial annual award function.', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/biomass-gasifier-system/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-04-14-at-13.15.11-480x1024.jpeg', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-04-14-at-13.15.11-480x1024.jpeg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-04-14-at-13.15.11.jpeg"]'::jsonb, '["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tvEYAO4N4Uk"]'::jsonb, 'Hanumangarh , Rajasthan', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Rai Singh Dahiya"},{"key":"Location","value":"Hanumangarh , Rajasthan"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"Back in 1982, Rai Singh had set up a kiln for baking bricks which had a capacity of 12000 bricks. He observed that burning wood and other fuels in the kiln produced some gas that was burning more furiously. In 1991, Singh started his workshop repairing tractors, Jeep trucks, and other engines. After observing the increasing demand and price for diesel engines in the agricultural sector, he decided to modify the diesel engine to operate on an economical LPG. After this LPG engine was successful, he considered making an engine that could run on wood-burning gas. Then after a series of experiments, he successfully developed a device that consists of a gasifier that helps convert biomass into producer gas. The conventional diesel engine was then modified with a spark plug and a fuel pump with a distributor setup. The modified diesel engine was running using the gasifier but for a very short time. Singh found the glitch in the device, and impurities in the producer gas and worked out several mechanisms and filtering sieves to develop a filtering mechanism so that gas could be supplied to the modified engine. He successfully developed his biomass gasifier system, reducing maintenance and increasing the capability to operate for 40 hours continuously. The system is a success as it uses all types of wood waste and fuel. Wood stocks of cotton pulses, coconut shells and palm stocks, maize cobs, branches and twigs, various agricultural residues, certain industrial waste of paper, plywood, etc. The reported fuel consumption of the system is 1 kg/kVA, approximately 30 to 35%, less than conventional gasifiers. Singh’s biomass gasifier system has won many awards for sustainable technological development. He was also honored at Rashtrapati Bhavan by NIF. In 2002, he was honored by the gram panchayat, and in 2004 by the district collector. The innovator has also been awarded a national award in the 5th Biennial annual award function."},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tvEYAO4N4Uk"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['machine', 'device']::text[], 'Biomass Gasifier System Rai Singh Dahiya Hanumangarh , Rajasthan An innovator Rai Singh from Hanumangarh, Rajasthan, has created an efficient biomass gasifier system to smooth engine operation and minimize operational costs. The Honey Bee Network and GIAN North under MVIF supported this innovation. With the guidance and support from GIAN, the innovator has been able to manufacture on a large scale and sell more than 50 units of his gasifier. The innovator Rai Singh had no formal education. Still, because of his love for science and machines, he gained knowledge by dismantling and repairing gadgets and listening to science programs on the radio. His dedication and hard work made him successful and the owner of Enersol Biopower private limited. Back in 1982, Rai Singh had set up a kiln for baking bricks which had a capacity of 12000 bricks. He observed that burning wood and other fuels in the kiln produced some gas that was burning more furiously. In 1991, Singh started his workshop repairing tractors, Jeep trucks, and other engines. After observing the increasing demand and price for diesel engines in the agricultural sector, he decided to modify the diesel engine to operate on an economical LPG. After this LPG engine was successful, he considered making an engine that could run on wood-burning gas. Then after a series of experiments, he successfully developed a device that consists of a gasifier that helps convert biomass into producer gas. The conventional diesel engine was then modified with a spark plug and a fuel pump with a distributor setup. The modified diesel engine was running using the gasifier but for a very short time. Singh found the glitch in the device, and impurities in the producer gas and worked out several mechanisms and filtering sieves to develop a filtering mechanism so that gas could be supplied to the modified engine. He successfully developed his biomass gasifier system, reducing maintenance and increasing the capability to operate for 40 hours continuously. The system is a success as it uses all types of wood waste and fuel. Wood stocks of cotton pulses, coconut shells and palm stocks, maize cobs, branches and twigs, various agricultural residues, certain industrial waste of paper, plywood, etc. The reported fuel consumption of the system is 1 kg/kVA, approximately 30 to 35%, less than conventional gasifiers. Singh’s biomass gasifier system has won many awards for sustainable technological development. He was also honored at Rashtrapati Bhavan by NIF. In 2002, he was honored by the gram panchayat, and in 2004 by the district collector. The innovator has also been awarded a national award in the 5th Biennial annual award function. machine device https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tvEYAO4N4Uk', '{"innovation_slug":"biomass-gasifier-system","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/biomass-gasifier-system/","innovation_title":"Biomass Gasifier System","innovator_name":"Rai Singh Dahiya","location":"Hanumangarh , Rajasthan","innovator_bio":"An innovator Rai Singh from Hanumangarh, Rajasthan, has created an efficient biomass gasifier system to smooth engine operation and minimize operational costs. The Honey Bee Network and GIAN North under MVIF supported this innovation. With the guidance and support from GIAN, the innovator has been able to manufacture on a large scale and sell more than 50 units of his gasifier. The innovator Rai Singh had no formal education. Still, because of his love for science and machines, he gained knowledge by dismantling and repairing gadgets and listening to science programs on the radio. His dedication and hard work made him successful and the owner of Enersol Biopower private limited.","innovation_details":"Back in 1982, Rai Singh had set up a kiln for baking bricks which had a capacity of 12000 bricks. He observed that burning wood and other fuels in the kiln produced some gas that was burning more furiously. In 1991, Singh started his workshop repairing tractors, Jeep trucks, and other engines. After observing the increasing demand and price for diesel engines in the agricultural sector, he decided to modify the diesel engine to operate on an economical LPG. After this LPG engine was successful, he considered making an engine that could run on wood-burning gas. Then after a series of experiments, he successfully developed a device that consists of a gasifier that helps convert biomass into producer gas. The conventional diesel engine was then modified with a spark plug and a fuel pump with a distributor setup. The modified diesel engine was running using the gasifier but for a very short time. Singh found the glitch in the device, and impurities in the producer gas and worked out several mechanisms and filtering sieves to develop a filtering mechanism so that gas could be supplied to the modified engine. He successfully developed his biomass gasifier system, reducing maintenance and increasing the capability to operate for 40 hours continuously. The system is a success as it uses all types of wood waste and fuel. Wood stocks of cotton pulses, coconut shells and palm stocks, maize cobs, branches and twigs, various agricultural residues, certain industrial waste of paper, plywood, etc. The reported fuel consumption of the system is 1 kg/kVA, approximately 30 to 35%, less than conventional gasifiers. Singh’s biomass gasifier system has won many awards for sustainable technological development. He was also honored at Rashtrapati Bhavan by NIF. In 2002, he was honored by the gram panchayat, and in 2004 by the district collector. The innovator has also been awarded a national award in the 5th Biennial annual award function.","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Bio-gasifier-.jpeg"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-04-14-at-13.15.11-480x1024.jpeg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-04-14-at-13.15.11.jpeg"],"multimedia_links":["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=tvEYAO4N4Uk"],"tags":["machine","device"],"latitude":29.0019411,"longitude":74.3587473,"listing_excerpt":"Rai Singh Dahiya"}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('farmyard-manure-distributor-in-the-field-by-ashikbhai-gani-gujarat', 'ashikbhai-gani-banaskantha-gujarat', 'Ashikbhai Gani', 'Farmyard manure distributor in the field by Ashikbhai Gani (Gujarat)', 'As an innovator, Ashikbhai noticed that if any farmer wants to spread farm yard manure on their farm, they always have to ask the service provider who will come with their tractor, trolley, and JCB with labor. In this process, the service provider makes piles in the farm by picking them up manually from the farmer’s dump site. Further, these piles had to be spread in the field, which is labor-intensive and time-consuming. The main problem was putting manure on the farm. He saw a foreign machine serving the task, but it was expensive for Indian farmers. So in 2017, he made a design that took three years to develop. The prototype was ready in 2018 for testing. We asked a farmer to give us feedback on the problems faced for one year. We did R&D to solve the problems, and the final model was ready by 2019, which they launched in the market. Many experiments were done on RPM, torque, weight balancing, turning weight optimization, etc., before finalizing the trolley compatible with the conventional tractor arrangement. It is 11ft in length, 6 ft in width, and 2 ft in height. 3,300 kg weight of the machine. This is the standard size. It can hold 4.5 tons of wet manure and 2.5-3 tons of dry manure. This machine is attached to a tractor and is controlled by a remote. Machines do not have many maintenance costs. Ashikbhai conducts feedback sessions with the consumers every week to keep track of the issues and setbacks of the machine, if any. The customers are delighted with the product as well as the services provided by the company. The machine was then able to spread both dry and wet manure on the field. This helps farmers in many ways, such as saving precious time, spreading manure uniformly over the field, and reducing labor expenses. The team has 24 people; they only make the Farmyard Manure Spreader machine and distribute it all over India. The cost of the machine is 6,50,000, with a gross margin of 30% and a net margin of 10%. Ashikbhai has applied for a subsidy, which is in the process; the machine has been tested and approved, so the certificate is in progress. With subsidies, their production will increase by 20%. He has successfully sold this manual spreader to many farmers and is getting queries from far and wide for his farm yard manure spreader', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/farmyard-manure-distributor-in-the-field-by-ashikbhai-gani-gujarat/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/TSK_8256-1024x678.jpg', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/TSK_8256-1024x678.jpg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/TSK_8250-1024x678.jpg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/TSK_8250-scaled.jpg"]'::jsonb, '["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TRBxP0arN6M"]'::jsonb, 'Banaskantha , Gujarat', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Ashikbhai Gani"},{"key":"Location","value":"Banaskantha , Gujarat"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"As an innovator, Ashikbhai noticed that if any farmer wants to spread farm yard manure on their farm, they always have to ask the service provider who will come with their tractor, trolley, and JCB with labor. In this process, the service provider makes piles in the farm by picking them up manually from the farmer’s dump site. Further, these piles had to be spread in the field, which is labor-intensive and time-consuming. The main problem was putting manure on the farm. He saw a foreign machine serving the task, but it was expensive for Indian farmers. So in 2017, he made a design that took three years to develop. The prototype was ready in 2018 for testing. We asked a farmer to give us feedback on the problems faced for one year. We did R&D to solve the problems, and the final model was ready by 2019, which they launched in the market. Many experiments were done on RPM, torque, weight balancing, turning weight optimization, etc., before finalizing the trolley compatible with the conventional tractor arrangement. It is 11ft in length, 6 ft in width, and 2 ft in height. 3,300 kg weight of the machine. This is the standard size. It can hold 4.5 tons of wet manure and 2.5-3 tons of dry manure. This machine is attached to a tractor and is controlled by a remote. Machines do not have many maintenance costs. Ashikbhai conducts feedback sessions with the consumers every week to keep track of the issues and setbacks of the machine, if any. The customers are delighted with the product as well as the services provided by the company. The machine was then able to spread both dry and wet manure on the field. This helps farmers in many ways, such as saving precious time, spreading manure uniformly over the field, and reducing labor expenses. The team has 24 people; they only make the Farmyard Manure Spreader machine and distribute it all over India. The cost of the machine is 6,50,000, with a gross margin of 30% and a net margin of 10%. Ashikbhai has applied for a subsidy, which is in the process; the machine has been tested and approved, so the certificate is in progress. With subsidies, their production will increase by 20%. He has successfully sold this manual spreader to many farmers and is getting queries from far and wide for his farm yard manure spreader"},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TRBxP0arN6M"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['machine', 'farmer']::text[], 'Farmyard manure distributor in the field by Ashikbhai Gani (Gujarat) Ashikbhai Gani Banaskantha , Gujarat Ashikbhai Gani from Gujarat innovated a farmyard manure distributor in the field, which can be used to spread the farmyard manure in farms without any labor-intensive work. The Honey Bee Network and GIAN supported his innovation to help scale it up. Innovator Ashikbhai is dedicated to his innovation, and today he has set up a company named Greenland agro Enterprise. After launch, Ashikbhai and the team have sold up to 185 units and have 30 machine orders. They have a design patent on the name of their company Greenland agro. Manufacturing is continued, and they keep at least ten machines in stock. As an innovator, Ashikbhai noticed that if any farmer wants to spread farm yard manure on their farm, they always have to ask the service provider who will come with their tractor, trolley, and JCB with labor. In this process, the service provider makes piles in the farm by picking them up manually from the farmer’s dump site. Further, these piles had to be spread in the field, which is labor-intensive and time-consuming. The main problem was putting manure on the farm. He saw a foreign machine serving the task, but it was expensive for Indian farmers. So in 2017, he made a design that took three years to develop. The prototype was ready in 2018 for testing. We asked a farmer to give us feedback on the problems faced for one year. We did R&D to solve the problems, and the final model was ready by 2019, which they launched in the market. Many experiments were done on RPM, torque, weight balancing, turning weight optimization, etc., before finalizing the trolley compatible with the conventional tractor arrangement. It is 11ft in length, 6 ft in width, and 2 ft in height. 3,300 kg weight of the machine. This is the standard size. It can hold 4.5 tons of wet manure and 2.5-3 tons of dry manure. This machine is attached to a tractor and is controlled by a remote. Machines do not have many maintenance costs. Ashikbhai conducts feedback sessions with the consumers every week to keep track of the issues and setbacks of the machine, if any. The customers are delighted with the product as well as the services provided by the company. The machine was then able to spread both dry and wet manure on the field. This helps farmers in many ways, such as saving precious time, spreading manure uniformly over the field, and reducing labor expenses. The team has 24 people; they only make the Farmyard Manure Spreader machine and distribute it all over India. The cost of the machine is 6,50,000, with a gross margin of 30% and a net margin of 10%. Ashikbhai has applied for a subsidy, which is in the process; the machine has been tested and approved, so the certificate is in progress. With subsidies, their production will increase by 20%. He has successfully sold this manual spreader to many farmers and is getting queries from far and wide for his farm yard manure spreader machine farmer https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TRBxP0arN6M', '{"innovation_slug":"farmyard-manure-distributor-in-the-field-by-ashikbhai-gani-gujarat","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/farmyard-manure-distributor-in-the-field-by-ashikbhai-gani-gujarat/","innovation_title":"Farmyard manure distributor in the field by Ashikbhai Gani (Gujarat)","innovator_name":"Ashikbhai Gani","location":"Banaskantha , Gujarat","innovator_bio":"Ashikbhai Gani from Gujarat innovated a farmyard manure distributor in the field, which can be used to spread the farmyard manure in farms without any labor-intensive work. The Honey Bee Network and GIAN supported his innovation to help scale it up. Innovator Ashikbhai is dedicated to his innovation, and today he has set up a company named Greenland agro Enterprise. After launch, Ashikbhai and the team have sold up to 185 units and have 30 machine orders. They have a design patent on the name of their company Greenland agro. Manufacturing is continued, and they keep at least ten machines in stock.","innovation_details":"As an innovator, Ashikbhai noticed that if any farmer wants to spread farm yard manure on their farm, they always have to ask the service provider who will come with their tractor, trolley, and JCB with labor. In this process, the service provider makes piles in the farm by picking them up manually from the farmer’s dump site. Further, these piles had to be spread in the field, which is labor-intensive and time-consuming. The main problem was putting manure on the farm. He saw a foreign machine serving the task, but it was expensive for Indian farmers. So in 2017, he made a design that took three years to develop. The prototype was ready in 2018 for testing. We asked a farmer to give us feedback on the problems faced for one year. We did R&D to solve the problems, and the final model was ready by 2019, which they launched in the market. Many experiments were done on RPM, torque, weight balancing, turning weight optimization, etc., before finalizing the trolley compatible with the conventional tractor arrangement. It is 11ft in length, 6 ft in width, and 2 ft in height. 3,300 kg weight of the machine. This is the standard size. It can hold 4.5 tons of wet manure and 2.5-3 tons of dry manure. This machine is attached to a tractor and is controlled by a remote. Machines do not have many maintenance costs. Ashikbhai conducts feedback sessions with the consumers every week to keep track of the issues and setbacks of the machine, if any. The customers are delighted with the product as well as the services provided by the company. The machine was then able to spread both dry and wet manure on the field. This helps farmers in many ways, such as saving precious time, spreading manure uniformly over the field, and reducing labor expenses. The team has 24 people; they only make the Farmyard Manure Spreader machine and distribute it all over India. The cost of the machine is 6,50,000, with a gross margin of 30% and a net margin of 10%. Ashikbhai has applied for a subsidy, which is in the process; the machine has been tested and approved, so the certificate is in progress. With subsidies, their production will increase by 20%. He has successfully sold this manual spreader to many farmers and is getting queries from far and wide for his farm yard manure spreader","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/TEJS9626-scaled.jpg"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/TSK_8256-1024x678.jpg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/TSK_8250-1024x678.jpg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/TSK_8250-scaled.jpg"],"multimedia_links":["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TRBxP0arN6M"],"tags":["machine","farmer"],"latitude":24.0858656,"longitude":72.36663,"listing_excerpt":"Farmyard manure distributor in the field by Ashikbhai Gani (Gujarat)"}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('low-cost-orchard-sprayer-by-deepakbhai-patel-gujarat', 'deepakbhai-patel-kutch-gujarat', 'Deepakbhai Patel', 'Low-Cost Orchard Sprayer by Deepakbhai Patel (Gujarat)', 'While working as a technical person at a workshop of rewinding motors, Deepakbhai conversed with local farmers. During this conversation, he learned about farmers’ difficulties spraying pesticides in orchards. Also, it’s done manually by labor and has a high labor cost. He also discovered the unproductive method, shortage of labels, and lack of specialized devices cause high losses to farmers. Looking at these disadvantages, Deepakbhai developed a low-cost tractor-operated hybrid orchard sprayer. First, he made simple pumps, modified them to automatic pumps, and launched them in the market in 2012. The innovator prototyped the sprayer with a tractor of more than 20 HP and 3 HP pressure pumps used for spraying pesticide more efficiently onto the plants at 15 km/h. The drops of pesticides are converted to microparticles using a fan running at 450 to 550 RPM speeds. The range of spray is 1200 ft. The simple spray is 1000 liters, but mostly Anar Spray is more in demand. Simple pumps require ten days, and blower pumps require 15 days to manufacture. They use a high-quality reliance tank and Victor pump in the sprayer. Deepakbhai buys raw materials from Bhuj. This sprayer’s spraying capacity is 1 acre per hour for a specific pomegranate crop, which can vary depending on crop and planting pattern. The innovation was appreciated by many institutions and was used by local municipal corporations for sanitization during the COVID-19 pandemic', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/low-cost-orchard-sprayer-by-deepakbhai-patel-gujarat/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/low-cost-orchid-sprayer-.png', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/low-cost-orchid-sprayer-.png"]'::jsonb, '["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pVYq30RSkBo"]'::jsonb, 'Kutch , Gujarat', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Deepakbhai Patel"},{"key":"Location","value":"Kutch , Gujarat"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"While working as a technical person at a workshop of rewinding motors, Deepakbhai conversed with local farmers. During this conversation, he learned about farmers’ difficulties spraying pesticides in orchards. Also, it’s done manually by labor and has a high labor cost. He also discovered the unproductive method, shortage of labels, and lack of specialized devices cause high losses to farmers. Looking at these disadvantages, Deepakbhai developed a low-cost tractor-operated hybrid orchard sprayer. First, he made simple pumps, modified them to automatic pumps, and launched them in the market in 2012. The innovator prototyped the sprayer with a tractor of more than 20 HP and 3 HP pressure pumps used for spraying pesticide more efficiently onto the plants at 15 km/h. The drops of pesticides are converted to microparticles using a fan running at 450 to 550 RPM speeds. The range of spray is 1200 ft. The simple spray is 1000 liters, but mostly Anar Spray is more in demand. Simple pumps require ten days, and blower pumps require 15 days to manufacture. They use a high-quality reliance tank and Victor pump in the sprayer. Deepakbhai buys raw materials from Bhuj. This sprayer’s spraying capacity is 1 acre per hour for a specific pomegranate crop, which can vary depending on crop and planting pattern. The innovation was appreciated by many institutions and was used by local municipal corporations for sanitization during the COVID-19 pandemic"},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pVYq30RSkBo"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['orchard', 'device', 'farmer']::text[], 'Low-Cost Orchard Sprayer by Deepakbhai Patel (Gujarat) Deepakbhai Patel Kutch , Gujarat A grassroots innovator and an incubator of GIAN Deepakbhai Patel from Bharuch, Gujarat, has innovated a low-cost orchard sprayer for spraying pesticides and insecticides to the orchard plants. His innovation was guided and supported by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network. The innovation of this orchard sprayer is a boon for all the farmers involved in orchard farming. It is an active alternative to conventional techniques, and Deepakbhai has managed to sell his product to multiple cities. He has sold more than 90 units in the market till today and modifies the sprayer pump according to customers’ needs. While working as a technical person at a workshop of rewinding motors, Deepakbhai conversed with local farmers. During this conversation, he learned about farmers’ difficulties spraying pesticides in orchards. Also, it’s done manually by labor and has a high labor cost. He also discovered the unproductive method, shortage of labels, and lack of specialized devices cause high losses to farmers. Looking at these disadvantages, Deepakbhai developed a low-cost tractor-operated hybrid orchard sprayer. First, he made simple pumps, modified them to automatic pumps, and launched them in the market in 2012. The innovator prototyped the sprayer with a tractor of more than 20 HP and 3 HP pressure pumps used for spraying pesticide more efficiently onto the plants at 15 km/h. The drops of pesticides are converted to microparticles using a fan running at 450 to 550 RPM speeds. The range of spray is 1200 ft. The simple spray is 1000 liters, but mostly Anar Spray is more in demand. Simple pumps require ten days, and blower pumps require 15 days to manufacture. They use a high-quality reliance tank and Victor pump in the sprayer. Deepakbhai buys raw materials from Bhuj. This sprayer’s spraying capacity is 1 acre per hour for a specific pomegranate crop, which can vary depending on crop and planting pattern. The innovation was appreciated by many institutions and was used by local municipal corporations for sanitization during the COVID-19 pandemic orchard device farmer https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pVYq30RSkBo', '{"innovation_slug":"low-cost-orchard-sprayer-by-deepakbhai-patel-gujarat","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/low-cost-orchard-sprayer-by-deepakbhai-patel-gujarat/","innovation_title":"Low-Cost Orchard Sprayer by Deepakbhai Patel (Gujarat)","innovator_name":"Deepakbhai Patel","location":"Kutch , Gujarat","innovator_bio":"A grassroots innovator and an incubator of GIAN Deepakbhai Patel from Bharuch, Gujarat, has innovated a low-cost orchard sprayer for spraying pesticides and insecticides to the orchard plants. His innovation was guided and supported by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network. The innovation of this orchard sprayer is a boon for all the farmers involved in orchard farming. It is an active alternative to conventional techniques, and Deepakbhai has managed to sell his product to multiple cities. He has sold more than 90 units in the market till today and modifies the sprayer pump according to customers’ needs.","innovation_details":"While working as a technical person at a workshop of rewinding motors, Deepakbhai conversed with local farmers. During this conversation, he learned about farmers’ difficulties spraying pesticides in orchards. Also, it’s done manually by labor and has a high labor cost. He also discovered the unproductive method, shortage of labels, and lack of specialized devices cause high losses to farmers. Looking at these disadvantages, Deepakbhai developed a low-cost tractor-operated hybrid orchard sprayer. First, he made simple pumps, modified them to automatic pumps, and launched them in the market in 2012. The innovator prototyped the sprayer with a tractor of more than 20 HP and 3 HP pressure pumps used for spraying pesticide more efficiently onto the plants at 15 km/h. The drops of pesticides are converted to microparticles using a fan running at 450 to 550 RPM speeds. The range of spray is 1200 ft. The simple spray is 1000 liters, but mostly Anar Spray is more in demand. Simple pumps require ten days, and blower pumps require 15 days to manufacture. They use a high-quality reliance tank and Victor pump in the sprayer. Deepakbhai buys raw materials from Bhuj. This sprayer’s spraying capacity is 1 acre per hour for a specific pomegranate crop, which can vary depending on crop and planting pattern. The innovation was appreciated by many institutions and was used by local municipal corporations for sanitization during the COVID-19 pandemic","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2022-03-30-at-18.01.34.jpeg"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/low-cost-orchid-sprayer-.png"],"multimedia_links":["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pVYq30RSkBo"],"tags":["orchard","device","farmer"],"latitude":23.368105,"longitude":70.1932084,"listing_excerpt":"Deepakbhai Patel"}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('sanajing-sana-thambal', 'mstongbram-bijayashanti-devi-bishnupur-manipur', 'Ms.Tongbram Bijayashanti Devi', 'Sanajing Sana Thambal by Ms.Tongbram Bijayashanti Devi (Manipur)', 'Talking about her idea and innovation. Bijayashanti Devi said, “in our village, there are no options to do work except fishing and farming. Many women cannot work in this field, so I thought of making textiles from Lotus Stem as it is available in abundance in Loktak lake.” In this process, the innovation breaks the lotus stem at the length of a thumb and pulls and expands the fiber from the lotus stem. Then, the fiber is hand rolled into its desired size using the wooden plank and palms. Using a loin loom, the fiber extracted from the lotus stems and stock is produced as yarns for weaving clothes, neckties, scarves, and mufflers. This innovation can potentially open new avenues in Lotus farming and textile along with female empowerment. Clothes made out of lotus stem fibers have health benefits, but as it is labor-intensive work, it is very costly and hence, highly in demand in foreign countries than in local markets', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/sanajing-sana-thambal/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/20230405111752_0Y9A0384-1024x683.jpg', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/20230405111752_0Y9A0384-1024x683.jpg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/20230405103711_0Y9A0354-1024x683.jpg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/20230405111752_0Y9A0384-scaled.jpg"]'::jsonb, '["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0Ln_XwEbCPQ"]'::jsonb, 'Bishnupur , Manipur', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Ms.Tongbram Bijayashanti Devi"},{"key":"Location","value":"Bishnupur , Manipur"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"Talking about her idea and innovation. Bijayashanti Devi said, “in our village, there are no options to do work except fishing and farming. Many women cannot work in this field, so I thought of making textiles from Lotus Stem as it is available in abundance in Loktak lake.” In this process, the innovation breaks the lotus stem at the length of a thumb and pulls and expands the fiber from the lotus stem. Then, the fiber is hand rolled into its desired size using the wooden plank and palms. Using a loin loom, the fiber extracted from the lotus stems and stock is produced as yarns for weaving clothes, neckties, scarves, and mufflers. This innovation can potentially open new avenues in Lotus farming and textile along with female empowerment. Clothes made out of lotus stem fibers have health benefits, but as it is labor-intensive work, it is very costly and hence, highly in demand in foreign countries than in local markets"},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0Ln_XwEbCPQ"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['weaving', 'health']::text[], 'Sanajing Sana Thambal by Ms.Tongbram Bijayashanti Devi (Manipur) Ms.Tongbram Bijayashanti Devi Bishnupur , Manipur A young, empowered innovator Bijayashanti Devi from Bishnupur in Manipur, extracts fibers from Lotus stems to make fabric. GIAN and the Honey Bee Network bolstered the innovation of silk from lotus stems under the MVIF scheme. Bijayashanti received aid from GIAN and Honey Bee Network to seek wider markets and online sales. Talking about her idea and innovation. Bijayashanti Devi said, “in our village, there are no options to do work except fishing and farming. Many women cannot work in this field, so I thought of making textiles from Lotus Stem as it is available in abundance in Loktak lake.” In this process, the innovation breaks the lotus stem at the length of a thumb and pulls and expands the fiber from the lotus stem. Then, the fiber is hand rolled into its desired size using the wooden plank and palms. Using a loin loom, the fiber extracted from the lotus stems and stock is produced as yarns for weaving clothes, neckties, scarves, and mufflers. This innovation can potentially open new avenues in Lotus farming and textile along with female empowerment. Clothes made out of lotus stem fibers have health benefits, but as it is labor-intensive work, it is very costly and hence, highly in demand in foreign countries than in local markets weaving health https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0Ln_XwEbCPQ', '{"innovation_slug":"sanajing-sana-thambal","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/sanajing-sana-thambal/","innovation_title":"Sanajing Sana Thambal by Ms.Tongbram Bijayashanti Devi (Manipur)","innovator_name":"Ms.Tongbram Bijayashanti Devi","location":"Bishnupur , Manipur","innovator_bio":"A young, empowered innovator Bijayashanti Devi from Bishnupur in Manipur, extracts fibers from Lotus stems to make fabric. GIAN and the Honey Bee Network bolstered the innovation of silk from lotus stems under the MVIF scheme. Bijayashanti received aid from GIAN and Honey Bee Network to seek wider markets and online sales.","innovation_details":"Talking about her idea and innovation. Bijayashanti Devi said, “in our village, there are no options to do work except fishing and farming. Many women cannot work in this field, so I thought of making textiles from Lotus Stem as it is available in abundance in Loktak lake.” In this process, the innovation breaks the lotus stem at the length of a thumb and pulls and expands the fiber from the lotus stem. Then, the fiber is hand rolled into its desired size using the wooden plank and palms. Using a loin loom, the fiber extracted from the lotus stems and stock is produced as yarns for weaving clothes, neckties, scarves, and mufflers. This innovation can potentially open new avenues in Lotus farming and textile along with female empowerment. Clothes made out of lotus stem fibers have health benefits, but as it is labor-intensive work, it is very costly and hence, highly in demand in foreign countries than in local markets","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/1603700382258_BijiyashantiDevi.jpg"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/20230405111752_0Y9A0384-1024x683.jpg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/20230405103711_0Y9A0354-1024x683.jpg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/20230405111752_0Y9A0384-scaled.jpg"],"multimedia_links":["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0Ln_XwEbCPQ"],"tags":["weaving","health"],"latitude":24.4528388,"longitude":93.8044831,"listing_excerpt":"Sanajing Sana Thambal by Ms.Tongbram Bijayashanti Devi"}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('destoner-machine-by-janakbhai-rathod-gujarat', 'janakbhai-rathod-surendranagar-gujarat', 'Janakbhai Rathod', 'Destoner Machine by Janakbhai Rathod (Gujarat)', 'At the time of groundnut harvesting, the soil clods, small stones, and other materials from the earth are anchored to the pods. Clearing this manually takes time, and good results are not obtained. To overcome this setback, Janakbhai developed a destoner machine to separate soil and other materials attached to the pods. This device can clean soil from 120 to 140 kg of ground nuts in just 1 hour. It consumes just 2 to 2.5 l of diesel per hour. It does not require any parts replacement and hence has low maintenance. It needs to be greased regularly and can be attached to a tractor. It can also be carried anywhere. This device cleans the pods properly without any damage to the seeds and hence helps farmers to get good rates of ground nuts. Janakbhai has produced and sold many destoner machines so far. His innovation was recognized by many farmers and was appreciated. He also presented his innovation at IIC’s People’s Festival of Innovation through GIAN.', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/destoner-machine-by-janakbhai-rathod-gujarat/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Destoner-machine-1-1024x768.jpg', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Destoner-machine-1-1024x768.jpg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/destoner-machine-1024x768.jpg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Destoner-machine-1-scaled.jpg"]'::jsonb, '["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hEBL8VZq6VE"]'::jsonb, 'Surendranagar , Gujarat', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Janakbhai Rathod"},{"key":"Location","value":"Surendranagar , Gujarat"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"At the time of groundnut harvesting, the soil clods, small stones, and other materials from the earth are anchored to the pods. Clearing this manually takes time, and good results are not obtained. To overcome this setback, Janakbhai developed a destoner machine to separate soil and other materials attached to the pods. This device can clean soil from 120 to 140 kg of ground nuts in just 1 hour. It consumes just 2 to 2.5 l of diesel per hour. It does not require any parts replacement and hence has low maintenance. It needs to be greased regularly and can be attached to a tractor. It can also be carried anywhere. This device cleans the pods properly without any damage to the seeds and hence helps farmers to get good rates of ground nuts. Janakbhai has produced and sold many destoner machines so far. His innovation was recognized by many farmers and was appreciated. He also presented his innovation at IIC’s People’s Festival of Innovation through GIAN."},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hEBL8VZq6VE"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['machine', 'device', 'farmer']::text[], 'Destoner Machine by Janakbhai Rathod (Gujarat) Janakbhai Rathod Surendranagar , Gujarat Janakbhai Rathod, an enthusiastic farmer and innovator, created a destoner machine to separate the soil and other pebbles attached to the ground nut pods. His innovation was funded and supported during the COVID-19 pandemic by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network under MVIF in assistance with SIDBI. At the time of groundnut harvesting, the soil clods, small stones, and other materials from the earth are anchored to the pods. Clearing this manually takes time, and good results are not obtained. To overcome this setback, Janakbhai developed a destoner machine to separate soil and other materials attached to the pods. This device can clean soil from 120 to 140 kg of ground nuts in just 1 hour. It consumes just 2 to 2.5 l of diesel per hour. It does not require any parts replacement and hence has low maintenance. It needs to be greased regularly and can be attached to a tractor. It can also be carried anywhere. This device cleans the pods properly without any damage to the seeds and hence helps farmers to get good rates of ground nuts. Janakbhai has produced and sold many destoner machines so far. His innovation was recognized by many farmers and was appreciated. He also presented his innovation at IIC’s People’s Festival of Innovation through GIAN. machine device farmer https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hEBL8VZq6VE', '{"innovation_slug":"destoner-machine-by-janakbhai-rathod-gujarat","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/destoner-machine-by-janakbhai-rathod-gujarat/","innovation_title":"Destoner Machine by Janakbhai Rathod (Gujarat)","innovator_name":"Janakbhai Rathod","location":"Surendranagar , Gujarat","innovator_bio":"Janakbhai Rathod, an enthusiastic farmer and innovator, created a destoner machine to separate the soil and other pebbles attached to the ground nut pods. His innovation was funded and supported during the COVID-19 pandemic by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network under MVIF in assistance with SIDBI.","innovation_details":"At the time of groundnut harvesting, the soil clods, small stones, and other materials from the earth are anchored to the pods. Clearing this manually takes time, and good results are not obtained. To overcome this setback, Janakbhai developed a destoner machine to separate soil and other materials attached to the pods. This device can clean soil from 120 to 140 kg of ground nuts in just 1 hour. It consumes just 2 to 2.5 l of diesel per hour. It does not require any parts replacement and hence has low maintenance. It needs to be greased regularly and can be attached to a tractor. It can also be carried anywhere. This device cleans the pods properly without any damage to the seeds and hence helps farmers to get good rates of ground nuts. Janakbhai has produced and sold many destoner machines so far. His innovation was recognized by many farmers and was appreciated. He also presented his innovation at IIC’s People’s Festival of Innovation through GIAN.","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Ambika-janakbhai-rathod-.png"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Destoner-machine-1-1024x768.jpg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/destoner-machine-1024x768.jpg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Destoner-machine-1-scaled.jpg"],"multimedia_links":["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=hEBL8VZq6VE"],"tags":["machine","device","farmer"],"latitude":22.9403063,"longitude":71.1448516,"listing_excerpt":"Janakbhai Rathod"}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('vehicle-disinfectant-bay-by-bisu-hang-limbu-sikkim', 'bisu-hang-limbu-west-sikkim', 'Bisu Hang Limbu', 'Vehicle disinfectant bay by Bisu Hang Limbu (Sikkim)', 'A 22-year-old innovator, Bisu Hang Limbu from West Sikkim, developed an electric disinfecting device designated to sanitize vehicles at checkposts to regulate the spread of coronavirus. GIAN and the Honey Bee Network appreciated and supported this innovation to ensure it can reach the maximum places in and around Sikkim. He is a young inspired innovator who has innovated much other equipment besides vehicle disinfectants, such as the Noha Seleoti maker, Sena 05 Broom, Corn Roaster, Security foot mat, Milk carrying tank, and Crocodile fork, Handset fork. His vehicle disinfectant bay was a useful innovation during COVID-19 and helped the state government maintain the score of zero coronavirus cases.', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/vehicle-disinfectant-bay-by-bisu-hang-limbu-sikkim/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG-20200815-WA0006-472x1024.jpg', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG-20200815-WA0006-472x1024.jpg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG-20200815-WA0006.jpg"]'::jsonb, '["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l-hdwRdCaec"]'::jsonb, 'West Sikkim', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Bisu Hang Limbu"},{"key":"Location","value":"West Sikkim"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"A 22-year-old innovator, Bisu Hang Limbu from West Sikkim, developed an electric disinfecting device designated to sanitize vehicles at checkposts to regulate the spread of coronavirus. GIAN and the Honey Bee Network appreciated and supported this innovation to ensure it can reach the maximum places in and around Sikkim. He is a young inspired innovator who has innovated much other equipment besides vehicle disinfectants, such as the Noha Seleoti maker, Sena 05 Broom, Corn Roaster, Security foot mat, Milk carrying tank, and Crocodile fork, Handset fork. His vehicle disinfectant bay was a useful innovation during COVID-19 and helped the state government maintain the score of zero coronavirus cases."},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l-hdwRdCaec"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['machine', 'device']::text[], 'Vehicle disinfectant bay by Bisu Hang Limbu (Sikkim) Bisu Hang Limbu West Sikkim Bisu, a young innovation enthusiast, noted tedious and time-consuming non-safe methods used at check posts to sanitize cars. He then prototyped a device that can be used at the checkpost for vehicle sanitization in no time. The vehicle sanitization bay is a gate-like structure containing nozzles for spraying disinfectant. The device is attached to a storage tank, and the force and pressure of the liquid to be sprayed are decided by the motor of 250 volts attached to the bay. Bisu’s machine was a miracle for the government in the tough time of COVID-19 and was approved by the Sikkim state government to be used at the checkpost of Melli and Rangpo. A 22-year-old innovator, Bisu Hang Limbu from West Sikkim, developed an electric disinfecting device designated to sanitize vehicles at checkposts to regulate the spread of coronavirus. GIAN and the Honey Bee Network appreciated and supported this innovation to ensure it can reach the maximum places in and around Sikkim. He is a young inspired innovator who has innovated much other equipment besides vehicle disinfectants, such as the Noha Seleoti maker, Sena 05 Broom, Corn Roaster, Security foot mat, Milk carrying tank, and Crocodile fork, Handset fork. His vehicle disinfectant bay was a useful innovation during COVID-19 and helped the state government maintain the score of zero coronavirus cases. machine device https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l-hdwRdCaec', '{"innovation_slug":"vehicle-disinfectant-bay-by-bisu-hang-limbu-sikkim","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/vehicle-disinfectant-bay-by-bisu-hang-limbu-sikkim/","innovation_title":"Vehicle disinfectant bay by Bisu Hang Limbu (Sikkim)","innovator_name":"Bisu Hang Limbu","location":"West Sikkim","innovator_bio":"Bisu, a young innovation enthusiast, noted tedious and time-consuming non-safe methods used at check posts to sanitize cars. He then prototyped a device that can be used at the checkpost for vehicle sanitization in no time. The vehicle sanitization bay is a gate-like structure containing nozzles for spraying disinfectant. The device is attached to a storage tank, and the force and pressure of the liquid to be sprayed are decided by the motor of 250 volts attached to the bay. Bisu’s machine was a miracle for the government in the tough time of COVID-19 and was approved by the Sikkim state government to be used at the checkpost of Melli and Rangpo.","innovation_details":"A 22-year-old innovator, Bisu Hang Limbu from West Sikkim, developed an electric disinfecting device designated to sanitize vehicles at checkposts to regulate the spread of coronavirus. GIAN and the Honey Bee Network appreciated and supported this innovation to ensure it can reach the maximum places in and around Sikkim. He is a young inspired innovator who has innovated much other equipment besides vehicle disinfectants, such as the Noha Seleoti maker, Sena 05 Broom, Corn Roaster, Security foot mat, Milk carrying tank, and Crocodile fork, Handset fork. His vehicle disinfectant bay was a useful innovation during COVID-19 and helped the state government maintain the score of zero coronavirus cases.","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Bishu-limbu.jpeg"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG-20200815-WA0006-472x1024.jpg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG-20200815-WA0006.jpg"],"multimedia_links":["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l-hdwRdCaec"],"tags":["machine","device"],"latitude":27.3158027,"longitude":88.2753144,"listing_excerpt":"A 22-year-old innovator, Bisu Hang Limbu from West Sikkim, developed an electric disinfecting device designated to sanitize vehicles at checkposts to regulate the spread of"}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('solar-weeder-and-seed-drill-by-bharatbhai-agrawat-gujarat', 'bharatbhai-agrawat-junagadh-gujarat', 'Bharatbhai Agrawat', 'Solar Weeder and seed drill by Bharatbhai Agrawat (Gujarat)', 'As a farmer, Bharatbhai always had a soft spot for small-scale farmers who struggled due to a lack of high-technology equipment. When he observed that the manual method of seed plantation and weeding resulted in the irregular placement of seeds, efficient spacing, and fatigue for the area sown, he decided to make a seed sowing and weeding machine to reduce the drudgery involved. He made a manual cycle sowing and weeding machine which helps overcome the downsides of manual seeding. He sold more than 6000 units of this manual machine. Then after getting feedback from local farmers who used his product, he decided to attach a battery and solar panel to make the machine auto-operated and an easy-to-use eco-friendly device. In one charging, the machines can work on 2 acres. The labor cost would be Rs 5000; even if a tractor were used, the price would be around 1200. In the battery unit, it takes 2 unit expenses (“Rs 16) with one labor (cost Rs 500). The machine size is small and portable. It is very effective in intercrop farming. He sold a total of 6 battery-operated seed drills and a weeder. All products were made while researching, and he has not started mass production. The hand-operated weeder is sold at Rs 1100, the hand-operated seed driller costs Rs 3000, and the battery-operated seeder/weeder/trolly’s selling price is Rs 38,000. His company also collaborates with Universities and students to make a working model of a prototype. Bharatbhai’s innovative drill and weeder are self-selling; hence, several units of this device have already been sold. Also, the innovator has one community fabrication lab supported by NIFIndia.org. He also displayed his innovation at IIC’s People’s Innovation Festival in Delhi. He has also received the Life Time Achievement Award from Pratibha Patil and Pranab Mukherjee', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/solar-weeder-and-seed-drill-by-bharatbhai-agrawat-gujarat/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-01-19-at-01.00.47-768x1024.jpeg', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-01-19-at-01.00.47-768x1024.jpeg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-01-19-at-01.00.47.jpeg"]'::jsonb, '["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1pk-I2mTp0U"]'::jsonb, 'Junagadh , Gujarat', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Bharatbhai Agrawat"},{"key":"Location","value":"Junagadh , Gujarat"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"As a farmer, Bharatbhai always had a soft spot for small-scale farmers who struggled due to a lack of high-technology equipment. When he observed that the manual method of seed plantation and weeding resulted in the irregular placement of seeds, efficient spacing, and fatigue for the area sown, he decided to make a seed sowing and weeding machine to reduce the drudgery involved. He made a manual cycle sowing and weeding machine which helps overcome the downsides of manual seeding. He sold more than 6000 units of this manual machine. Then after getting feedback from local farmers who used his product, he decided to attach a battery and solar panel to make the machine auto-operated and an easy-to-use eco-friendly device. In one charging, the machines can work on 2 acres. The labor cost would be Rs 5000; even if a tractor were used, the price would be around 1200. In the battery unit, it takes 2 unit expenses (“Rs 16) with one labor (cost Rs 500). The machine size is small and portable. It is very effective in intercrop farming. He sold a total of 6 battery-operated seed drills and a weeder. All products were made while researching, and he has not started mass production. The hand-operated weeder is sold at Rs 1100, the hand-operated seed driller costs Rs 3000, and the battery-operated seeder/weeder/trolly’s selling price is Rs 38,000. His company also collaborates with Universities and students to make a working model of a prototype. Bharatbhai’s innovative drill and weeder are self-selling; hence, several units of this device have already been sold. Also, the innovator has one community fabrication lab supported by NIFIndia.org. He also displayed his innovation at IIC’s People’s Innovation Festival in Delhi. He has also received the Life Time Achievement Award from Pratibha Patil and Pranab Mukherjee"},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1pk-I2mTp0U"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['solar', 'machine', 'device', 'farmer']::text[], 'Solar Weeder and seed drill by Bharatbhai Agrawat (Gujarat) Bharatbhai Agrawat Junagadh , Gujarat Serial innovator Bharatbhai Agrawat from Gujarat has developed a solar weeder and seed drill machine. His innovation was appreciated and supported by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network. This innovation is a boon to many small to medium-scale farmers around the globe, and hence the drill and weeder technology was transferred to Kenya by the Honey Bee Network, GIAN, and SRISTI under the USAID project. Following his father’s footsteps, Bharatbhai has sold many of his solar weeder and sea drills to needy farmers. The innovation is a success. Apart from this, he also prototyped a diesel-operated tractor. Bharatbhai is very motivated and likes to spend most of his time innovating new technologies. As a farmer, Bharatbhai always had a soft spot for small-scale farmers who struggled due to a lack of high-technology equipment. When he observed that the manual method of seed plantation and weeding resulted in the irregular placement of seeds, efficient spacing, and fatigue for the area sown, he decided to make a seed sowing and weeding machine to reduce the drudgery involved. He made a manual cycle sowing and weeding machine which helps overcome the downsides of manual seeding. He sold more than 6000 units of this manual machine. Then after getting feedback from local farmers who used his product, he decided to attach a battery and solar panel to make the machine auto-operated and an easy-to-use eco-friendly device. In one charging, the machines can work on 2 acres. The labor cost would be Rs 5000; even if a tractor were used, the price would be around 1200. In the battery unit, it takes 2 unit expenses (“Rs 16) with one labor (cost Rs 500). The machine size is small and portable. It is very effective in intercrop farming. He sold a total of 6 battery-operated seed drills and a weeder. All products were made while researching, and he has not started mass production. The hand-operated weeder is sold at Rs 1100, the hand-operated seed driller costs Rs 3000, and the battery-operated seeder/weeder/trolly’s selling price is Rs 38,000. His company also collaborates with Universities and students to make a working model of a prototype. Bharatbhai’s innovative drill and weeder are self-selling; hence, several units of this device have already been sold. Also, the innovator has one community fabrication lab supported by NIFIndia.org. He also displayed his innovation at IIC’s People’s Innovation Festival in Delhi. He has also received the Life Time Achievement Award from Pratibha Patil and Pranab Mukherjee solar machine device farmer https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1pk-I2mTp0U', '{"innovation_slug":"solar-weeder-and-seed-drill-by-bharatbhai-agrawat-gujarat","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/solar-weeder-and-seed-drill-by-bharatbhai-agrawat-gujarat/","innovation_title":"Solar Weeder and seed drill by Bharatbhai Agrawat (Gujarat)","innovator_name":"Bharatbhai Agrawat","location":"Junagadh , Gujarat","innovator_bio":"Serial innovator Bharatbhai Agrawat from Gujarat has developed a solar weeder and seed drill machine. His innovation was appreciated and supported by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network. This innovation is a boon to many small to medium-scale farmers around the globe, and hence the drill and weeder technology was transferred to Kenya by the Honey Bee Network, GIAN, and SRISTI under the USAID project. Following his father’s footsteps, Bharatbhai has sold many of his solar weeder and sea drills to needy farmers. The innovation is a success. Apart from this, he also prototyped a diesel-operated tractor. Bharatbhai is very motivated and likes to spend most of his time innovating new technologies.","innovation_details":"As a farmer, Bharatbhai always had a soft spot for small-scale farmers who struggled due to a lack of high-technology equipment. When he observed that the manual method of seed plantation and weeding resulted in the irregular placement of seeds, efficient spacing, and fatigue for the area sown, he decided to make a seed sowing and weeding machine to reduce the drudgery involved. He made a manual cycle sowing and weeding machine which helps overcome the downsides of manual seeding. He sold more than 6000 units of this manual machine. Then after getting feedback from local farmers who used his product, he decided to attach a battery and solar panel to make the machine auto-operated and an easy-to-use eco-friendly device. In one charging, the machines can work on 2 acres. The labor cost would be Rs 5000; even if a tractor were used, the price would be around 1200. In the battery unit, it takes 2 unit expenses (“Rs 16) with one labor (cost Rs 500). The machine size is small and portable. It is very effective in intercrop farming. He sold a total of 6 battery-operated seed drills and a weeder. All products were made while researching, and he has not started mass production. The hand-operated weeder is sold at Rs 1100, the hand-operated seed driller costs Rs 3000, and the battery-operated seeder/weeder/trolly’s selling price is Rs 38,000. His company also collaborates with Universities and students to make a working model of a prototype. Bharatbhai’s innovative drill and weeder are self-selling; hence, several units of this device have already been sold. Also, the innovator has one community fabrication lab supported by NIFIndia.org. He also displayed his innovation at IIC’s People’s Innovation Festival in Delhi. He has also received the Life Time Achievement Award from Pratibha Patil and Pranab Mukherjee","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Solar-Weeder-and-seed-drill-Bharatbhai-Agrawat-1.jpg"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-01-19-at-01.00.47-768x1024.jpeg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-01-19-at-01.00.47.jpeg"],"multimedia_links":["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1pk-I2mTp0U"],"tags":["solar","machine","device","farmer"],"latitude":21.1751921,"longitude":70.3598758,"listing_excerpt":"Bharatbhai Agrawat"}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('richa-2000', 'rajkumar-rathore-sehore-madhya-pradesh', 'Rajkumar Rathore', 'RICHA 2000', 'Once when Rathore was on a routine round on his pigeon pea field, one distinctive plant attracted his attention. Features that made this plant unique were: two colored bigger flowers than normal plants, longer leaves, and a lavish green plant that remained greener for a longer period. Observing these unique features, he decided to increase the yield of this plant by optimizing the number of branches and increasing the pod bearings. After inspecting and analyzing the plant, he collected the seeds and harvested them separately the next season to keep note of the growth and distinct characteristics of the plants. Henceforth, the variety of unique pigeon peas was fascinating in 2000. Rathore named his innovation after his daughter ‘Richa 2000’. This distinctive pigeon pea seed is a perennial variety and can be harvested twice a year. It gives more pods per plant and a high 18-24 q/ac yield. They contain more seeds per pod and are disease tolerant. With support from GIAN and the Honey Bee Network, the ‘Richa 2000’ has been disseminated to Gujarat, Madhya Pradesh, Karnataka, Tamil Nadu, Chhattisgarh, Orissa, Telangana, and Andhra Pradesh, and Maharashtra farmers. Rajkumar and his innovation were appreciated at the state and national levels. He was awarded at the 4th National Grassroots Innovation Awards. At different events, our former presidents Dr. A P J Abdul Kalam, Pratibha Patil, and Pranab Mukharji, honored him.', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/richa-2000/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/9768RICHA-2000-Seeds-2.jpg', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/9768RICHA-2000-Seeds-2.jpg"]'::jsonb, '["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YYKocc0ep6o"]'::jsonb, 'Sehore , Madhya Pradesh', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Rajkumar Rathore"},{"key":"Location","value":"Sehore , Madhya Pradesh"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"Once when Rathore was on a routine round on his pigeon pea field, one distinctive plant attracted his attention. Features that made this plant unique were: two colored bigger flowers than normal plants, longer leaves, and a lavish green plant that remained greener for a longer period. Observing these unique features, he decided to increase the yield of this plant by optimizing the number of branches and increasing the pod bearings. After inspecting and analyzing the plant, he collected the seeds and harvested them separately the next season to keep note of the growth and distinct characteristics of the plants. Henceforth, the variety of unique pigeon peas was fascinating in 2000. Rathore named his innovation after his daughter ‘Richa 2000’. This distinctive pigeon pea seed is a perennial variety and can be harvested twice a year. It gives more pods per plant and a high 18-24 q/ac yield. They contain more seeds per pod and are disease tolerant. With support from GIAN and the Honey Bee Network, the ‘Richa 2000’ has been disseminated to Gujarat, Madhya Pradesh, Karnataka, Tamil Nadu, Chhattisgarh, Orissa, Telangana, and Andhra Pradesh, and Maharashtra farmers. Rajkumar and his innovation were appreciated at the state and national levels. He was awarded at the 4th National Grassroots Innovation Awards. At different events, our former presidents Dr. A P J Abdul Kalam, Pratibha Patil, and Pranab Mukharji, honored him."},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YYKocc0ep6o"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['farmer']::text[], 'RICHA 2000 Rajkumar Rathore Sehore , Madhya Pradesh Rajkumar Rathore, a progressive innovator who studied up to the 12th standard from Sehore Madhya Pradesh, developed a variety of persistent pigeon pea that provides good yield and has bushy growth. The registration application was filed by GIAN on behalf of the innovator under PPV and FRA with the help of NIF. GIAN and the Honey Bee Network helped capitalize on the innovation under MVIF. Rathore owns 18 acres of land, of which one acre is dedicated especially to pigeon pea seed production, and today with his innovation, he managed to help plenty of farmers. Once when Rathore was on a routine round on his pigeon pea field, one distinctive plant attracted his attention. Features that made this plant unique were: two colored bigger flowers than normal plants, longer leaves, and a lavish green plant that remained greener for a longer period. Observing these unique features, he decided to increase the yield of this plant by optimizing the number of branches and increasing the pod bearings. After inspecting and analyzing the plant, he collected the seeds and harvested them separately the next season to keep note of the growth and distinct characteristics of the plants. Henceforth, the variety of unique pigeon peas was fascinating in 2000. Rathore named his innovation after his daughter ‘Richa 2000’. This distinctive pigeon pea seed is a perennial variety and can be harvested twice a year. It gives more pods per plant and a high 18-24 q/ac yield. They contain more seeds per pod and are disease tolerant. With support from GIAN and the Honey Bee Network, the ‘Richa 2000’ has been disseminated to Gujarat, Madhya Pradesh, Karnataka, Tamil Nadu, Chhattisgarh, Orissa, Telangana, and Andhra Pradesh, and Maharashtra farmers. Rajkumar and his innovation were appreciated at the state and national levels. He was awarded at the 4th National Grassroots Innovation Awards. At different events, our former presidents Dr. A P J Abdul Kalam, Pratibha Patil, and Pranab Mukharji, honored him. farmer https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YYKocc0ep6o', '{"innovation_slug":"richa-2000","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/richa-2000/","innovation_title":"RICHA 2000","innovator_name":"Rajkumar Rathore","location":"Sehore , Madhya Pradesh","innovator_bio":"Rajkumar Rathore, a progressive innovator who studied up to the 12th standard from Sehore Madhya Pradesh, developed a variety of persistent pigeon pea that provides good yield and has bushy growth. The registration application was filed by GIAN on behalf of the innovator under PPV and FRA with the help of NIF. GIAN and the Honey Bee Network helped capitalize on the innovation under MVIF. Rathore owns 18 acres of land, of which one acre is dedicated especially to pigeon pea seed production, and today with his innovation, he managed to help plenty of farmers.","innovation_details":"Once when Rathore was on a routine round on his pigeon pea field, one distinctive plant attracted his attention. Features that made this plant unique were: two colored bigger flowers than normal plants, longer leaves, and a lavish green plant that remained greener for a longer period. Observing these unique features, he decided to increase the yield of this plant by optimizing the number of branches and increasing the pod bearings. After inspecting and analyzing the plant, he collected the seeds and harvested them separately the next season to keep note of the growth and distinct characteristics of the plants. Henceforth, the variety of unique pigeon peas was fascinating in 2000. Rathore named his innovation after his daughter ‘Richa 2000’. This distinctive pigeon pea seed is a perennial variety and can be harvested twice a year. It gives more pods per plant and a high 18-24 q/ac yield. They contain more seeds per pod and are disease tolerant. With support from GIAN and the Honey Bee Network, the ‘Richa 2000’ has been disseminated to Gujarat, Madhya Pradesh, Karnataka, Tamil Nadu, Chhattisgarh, Orissa, Telangana, and Andhra Pradesh, and Maharashtra farmers. Rajkumar and his innovation were appreciated at the state and national levels. He was awarded at the 4th National Grassroots Innovation Awards. At different events, our former presidents Dr. A P J Abdul Kalam, Pratibha Patil, and Pranab Mukharji, honored him.","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/IMG-20231129-WA0012-scaled.jpg"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/9768RICHA-2000-Seeds-2.jpg"],"multimedia_links":["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YYKocc0ep6o"],"tags":["farmer"],"latitude":23.1774034,"longitude":77.0564464,"listing_excerpt":"RICHA 2000 by Rajkumar Rathore"}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('dryland-agroforestry', 'sundaram-verma-sikar-rajasthan', 'Sundaram Verma', 'Dryland agroforestry', 'Growing up in an arid region of Rajasthan, Sundaram realized the value of agroforestry plantations. The survival rate in arid and semi-arid regions sapling is just 35%. The agroforestry in the dryland region augments farmers’ income and induces climate resilience. The dryland agroforestry technique by Sundaram Verma involves plowing the field up to one foot deep before the rains. The field is planked and pressed to break the capillaries after the rain. The rainwater has charged the soil, so it cannot evaporate easily. A 6 ft deep pit is made to sow the seeds, which are then covered with soil and water (one liter) in October-November. The idea behind this is that these trees will have to send roots deeper as there is no moisture in the upper layer of soil like in monsoon. This technique utilizes just 1 l of water; it is the best-suited method for water conservation in arid and semi-arid regions, along with avenues of agroforestry landing to land management and revenue generation. Apart from this amazing innovation, he pursued many other advancements in rainwater conservation in farming and evaluating crop varieties from Chili, mung beans, chickpeas, cluster beans, etc. In 2021, he was honored with Padmashree, among countless other awards.', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/dryland-agroforestry/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/sundaram-varma-768x1024.jpeg', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/sundaram-varma-768x1024.jpeg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/sundaram-varma.jpeg"]'::jsonb, '["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QN-MJG7WA_8"]'::jsonb, 'Sikar , Rajasthan', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Sundaram Verma"},{"key":"Location","value":"Sikar , Rajasthan"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"Growing up in an arid region of Rajasthan, Sundaram realized the value of agroforestry plantations. The survival rate in arid and semi-arid regions sapling is just 35%. The agroforestry in the dryland region augments farmers’ income and induces climate resilience. The dryland agroforestry technique by Sundaram Verma involves plowing the field up to one foot deep before the rains. The field is planked and pressed to break the capillaries after the rain. The rainwater has charged the soil, so it cannot evaporate easily. A 6 ft deep pit is made to sow the seeds, which are then covered with soil and water (one liter) in October-November. The idea behind this is that these trees will have to send roots deeper as there is no moisture in the upper layer of soil like in monsoon. This technique utilizes just 1 l of water; it is the best-suited method for water conservation in arid and semi-arid regions, along with avenues of agroforestry landing to land management and revenue generation. Apart from this amazing innovation, he pursued many other advancements in rainwater conservation in farming and evaluating crop varieties from Chili, mung beans, chickpeas, cluster beans, etc. In 2021, he was honored with Padmashree, among countless other awards."},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QN-MJG7WA_8"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['tree', 'water', 'farmer']::text[], 'Dryland agroforestry Sundaram Verma Sikar , Rajasthan Shri Sundaram Verma, an Indian environmentalist from the village of Sikar, Rajasthan, studied dryland farming at the Indian Agricultural Research Institution, New Delhi. After graduation, he innovated a dryland agroforestry technique for arid and semi-arid regions. Using this technique, all kinds of trees can be planted with an 80% survival rate of plants with just 1 l of water throughout the plant’s lifetime. Sundaram Verma has been a dedicated collaborator of GIAN and the Honey Bee Network and has helped scout other grassroots innovators. Using his dryland agroforestry technique, he has planted over 50,000 trees in the arid region of Shekhawati located in Rajasthan. Growing up in an arid region of Rajasthan, Sundaram realized the value of agroforestry plantations. The survival rate in arid and semi-arid regions sapling is just 35%. The agroforestry in the dryland region augments farmers’ income and induces climate resilience. The dryland agroforestry technique by Sundaram Verma involves plowing the field up to one foot deep before the rains. The field is planked and pressed to break the capillaries after the rain. The rainwater has charged the soil, so it cannot evaporate easily. A 6 ft deep pit is made to sow the seeds, which are then covered with soil and water (one liter) in October-November. The idea behind this is that these trees will have to send roots deeper as there is no moisture in the upper layer of soil like in monsoon. This technique utilizes just 1 l of water; it is the best-suited method for water conservation in arid and semi-arid regions, along with avenues of agroforestry landing to land management and revenue generation. Apart from this amazing innovation, he pursued many other advancements in rainwater conservation in farming and evaluating crop varieties from Chili, mung beans, chickpeas, cluster beans, etc. In 2021, he was honored with Padmashree, among countless other awards. tree water farmer https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QN-MJG7WA_8', '{"innovation_slug":"dryland-agroforestry","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/dryland-agroforestry/","innovation_title":"Dryland agroforestry","innovator_name":"Sundaram Verma","location":"Sikar , Rajasthan","innovator_bio":"Shri Sundaram Verma, an Indian environmentalist from the village of Sikar, Rajasthan, studied dryland farming at the Indian Agricultural Research Institution, New Delhi. After graduation, he innovated a dryland agroforestry technique for arid and semi-arid regions. Using this technique, all kinds of trees can be planted with an 80% survival rate of plants with just 1 l of water throughout the plant’s lifetime. Sundaram Verma has been a dedicated collaborator of GIAN and the Honey Bee Network and has helped scout other grassroots innovators. Using his dryland agroforestry technique, he has planted over 50,000 trees in the arid region of Shekhawati located in Rajasthan.","innovation_details":"Growing up in an arid region of Rajasthan, Sundaram realized the value of agroforestry plantations. The survival rate in arid and semi-arid regions sapling is just 35%. The agroforestry in the dryland region augments farmers’ income and induces climate resilience. The dryland agroforestry technique by Sundaram Verma involves plowing the field up to one foot deep before the rains. The field is planked and pressed to break the capillaries after the rain. The rainwater has charged the soil, so it cannot evaporate easily. A 6 ft deep pit is made to sow the seeds, which are then covered with soil and water (one liter) in October-November. The idea behind this is that these trees will have to send roots deeper as there is no moisture in the upper layer of soil like in monsoon. This technique utilizes just 1 l of water; it is the best-suited method for water conservation in arid and semi-arid regions, along with avenues of agroforestry landing to land management and revenue generation. Apart from this amazing innovation, he pursued many other advancements in rainwater conservation in farming and evaluating crop varieties from Chili, mung beans, chickpeas, cluster beans, etc. In 2021, he was honored with Padmashree, among countless other awards.","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/sundaram-varma.jpeg"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/sundaram-varma-768x1024.jpeg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/sundaram-varma.jpeg"],"multimedia_links":["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QN-MJG7WA_8"],"tags":["tree","water","farmer"],"latitude":27.2961064,"longitude":75.2245693,"listing_excerpt":"Sundaram Verma"}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('hyacinth-remover-machine', 'godasu-narsimha-nalgonda-telangana', 'Godasu Narsimha', 'Hyacinth Remover machine', 'Narsimha, a humble man from the fishing community, noticed the problem and labor involved in removing hyacinth (unwanted weed) from the water. Due to excessive hyacinth growth, the fish’s health is affected, and fishermen need to spend many rupees on the removal; the health of the fishermen involved in removal is also affected. Narsimha used a 5 HP motor and eight cutters to design the hyacinth machine that cuts the hyacinth into small 3 to 4-inch pieces and then flows down with the downstream water. For larger water bodies, he modified the machine by attaching the conveyor belt that transfers the cut pieces of hyacinth to the truck and transports them for disposal. This innovative technology can compel the remover using only 8000 to 10000 rupees and a minimum number of men’s power which is approximately one-third the cost of the manual method. The Hyderabad Municipal Corporation appreciated the innovation and was used to clean its bodies of water. The machine was exported to Lake Victoria through GIAN, the Honey Bee Network, and MEA. Also, Narsimha was able to represent his innovation at various places, including LBSNAA and Rashtrapati Bhavan', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/hyacinth-remover-machine/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2024-03-07-at-1.04.29-PM-1024x680.jpeg', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2024-03-07-at-1.04.29-PM-1024x680.jpeg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2024-03-07-at-1.04.29-PM.jpeg"]'::jsonb, '["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D6mgI9k1ucg"]'::jsonb, 'Nalgonda , Telangana', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Godasu Narsimha"},{"key":"Location","value":"Nalgonda , Telangana"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"Narsimha, a humble man from the fishing community, noticed the problem and labor involved in removing hyacinth (unwanted weed) from the water. Due to excessive hyacinth growth, the fish’s health is affected, and fishermen need to spend many rupees on the removal; the health of the fishermen involved in removal is also affected. Narsimha used a 5 HP motor and eight cutters to design the hyacinth machine that cuts the hyacinth into small 3 to 4-inch pieces and then flows down with the downstream water. For larger water bodies, he modified the machine by attaching the conveyor belt that transfers the cut pieces of hyacinth to the truck and transports them for disposal. This innovative technology can compel the remover using only 8000 to 10000 rupees and a minimum number of men’s power which is approximately one-third the cost of the manual method. The Hyderabad Municipal Corporation appreciated the innovation and was used to clean its bodies of water. The machine was exported to Lake Victoria through GIAN, the Honey Bee Network, and MEA. Also, Narsimha was able to represent his innovation at various places, including LBSNAA and Rashtrapati Bhavan"},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D6mgI9k1ucg"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['machine', 'health', 'water']::text[], 'Hyacinth Remover machine Godasu Narsimha Nalgonda , Telangana Narsimha, an innovator, a teacher, and a fisherman from Nalgonda, Andhra Pradesh, developed a hyacinth remover machine to help the fishing community and transform the ecosystem. His innovation was supported and directed by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network Narsimha’s innovation is a blessing for the ecosystem and the fishing community; he has sold many machines. Narsimha, a humble man from the fishing community, noticed the problem and labor involved in removing hyacinth (unwanted weed) from the water. Due to excessive hyacinth growth, the fish’s health is affected, and fishermen need to spend many rupees on the removal; the health of the fishermen involved in removal is also affected. Narsimha used a 5 HP motor and eight cutters to design the hyacinth machine that cuts the hyacinth into small 3 to 4-inch pieces and then flows down with the downstream water. For larger water bodies, he modified the machine by attaching the conveyor belt that transfers the cut pieces of hyacinth to the truck and transports them for disposal. This innovative technology can compel the remover using only 8000 to 10000 rupees and a minimum number of men’s power which is approximately one-third the cost of the manual method. The Hyderabad Municipal Corporation appreciated the innovation and was used to clean its bodies of water. The machine was exported to Lake Victoria through GIAN, the Honey Bee Network, and MEA. Also, Narsimha was able to represent his innovation at various places, including LBSNAA and Rashtrapati Bhavan machine health water https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D6mgI9k1ucg', '{"innovation_slug":"hyacinth-remover-machine","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/hyacinth-remover-machine/","innovation_title":"Hyacinth Remover machine","innovator_name":"Godasu Narsimha","location":"Nalgonda , Telangana","innovator_bio":"Narsimha, an innovator, a teacher, and a fisherman from Nalgonda, Andhra Pradesh, developed a hyacinth remover machine to help the fishing community and transform the ecosystem. His innovation was supported and directed by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network Narsimha’s innovation is a blessing for the ecosystem and the fishing community; he has sold many machines.","innovation_details":"Narsimha, a humble man from the fishing community, noticed the problem and labor involved in removing hyacinth (unwanted weed) from the water. Due to excessive hyacinth growth, the fish’s health is affected, and fishermen need to spend many rupees on the removal; the health of the fishermen involved in removal is also affected. Narsimha used a 5 HP motor and eight cutters to design the hyacinth machine that cuts the hyacinth into small 3 to 4-inch pieces and then flows down with the downstream water. For larger water bodies, he modified the machine by attaching the conveyor belt that transfers the cut pieces of hyacinth to the truck and transports them for disposal. This innovative technology can compel the remover using only 8000 to 10000 rupees and a minimum number of men’s power which is approximately one-third the cost of the manual method. The Hyderabad Municipal Corporation appreciated the innovation and was used to clean its bodies of water. The machine was exported to Lake Victoria through GIAN, the Honey Bee Network, and MEA. Also, Narsimha was able to represent his innovation at various places, including LBSNAA and Rashtrapati Bhavan","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Narsinha.png"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2024-03-07-at-1.04.29-PM-1024x680.jpeg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2024-03-07-at-1.04.29-PM.jpeg"],"multimedia_links":["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=D6mgI9k1ucg"],"tags":["machine","health","water"],"latitude":17.3413528,"longitude":78.8042828,"listing_excerpt":"Godasu Narsimha"}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('neerain-private-limited', 'amit-doshi-gandhinagar-gujarat', 'Amit Doshi', 'NeeRain Private Limited', 'After quitting his corporate job, Amit Doshi diligently sought a startup idea. He researched for a while in different fields of sustainable environment, but the only proposal that left an impression on his mind was rainwater harvesting. After learning about the problems the government and local people faced in water conservation, he developed a product that could resolve all the issues and gaps of conventional water harvesting systems. Succeeding in research, creativity, and hard work, Amit closed in with a tangible solution of affordable and maintenance-free Rainwater harvesting. He successfully launched his startup NeeRain Pvt. Ltd in the year 2018. The NeeRain water harvesting device overcomes all the issues related to traditional water harvesting systems, such as simple and easily installable devices, cost-effectiveness, and minimum to no maintenance. The NeeRain system is a portable device that can be attached to the pipes collecting water from the rooftop and further channelizing it to the ground. It is a two-stage filtration process in which fresh, clean, and pure rainwater is collected when it passes out of the filtration system. NeeRain has created awareness about the global water crises and empowered the common people to live water-secure lives. Amit’s NeeRain device has won awards at different levels, including CII’s National Award for Excellence in Water Management in the innovative water-saving product category.', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/neerain-private-limited/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Neerain.jpg', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Neerain.jpg"]'::jsonb, '["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NWD_hIwS8-w"]'::jsonb, 'Gandhinagar Gujarat', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Amit Doshi"},{"key":"Location","value":"Gandhinagar Gujarat"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"After quitting his corporate job, Amit Doshi diligently sought a startup idea. He researched for a while in different fields of sustainable environment, but the only proposal that left an impression on his mind was rainwater harvesting. After learning about the problems the government and local people faced in water conservation, he developed a product that could resolve all the issues and gaps of conventional water harvesting systems. Succeeding in research, creativity, and hard work, Amit closed in with a tangible solution of affordable and maintenance-free Rainwater harvesting. He successfully launched his startup NeeRain Pvt. Ltd in the year 2018. The NeeRain water harvesting device overcomes all the issues related to traditional water harvesting systems, such as simple and easily installable devices, cost-effectiveness, and minimum to no maintenance. The NeeRain system is a portable device that can be attached to the pipes collecting water from the rooftop and further channelizing it to the ground. It is a two-stage filtration process in which fresh, clean, and pure rainwater is collected when it passes out of the filtration system. NeeRain has created awareness about the global water crises and empowered the common people to live water-secure lives. Amit’s NeeRain device has won awards at different levels, including CII’s National Award for Excellence in Water Management in the innovative water-saving product category."},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NWD_hIwS8-w"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['device', 'water']::text[], 'NeeRain Private Limited Amit Doshi Gandhinagar Gujarat Innovator Amit Doshi from Gandhinagar, Gujarat, was appreciated and supported by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network for entrepreneur development and feedback for improved technology for his rainwater harvesting system. Amit quit his well-paid corporate job in the waste management sector to jump into sustainable technology to make a difference. Today he has a successful startup company YIM NeeRain Pvt. ltd, that saves around 60,000 liters of water by rainwater harvesting. After quitting his corporate job, Amit Doshi diligently sought a startup idea. He researched for a while in different fields of sustainable environment, but the only proposal that left an impression on his mind was rainwater harvesting. After learning about the problems the government and local people faced in water conservation, he developed a product that could resolve all the issues and gaps of conventional water harvesting systems. Succeeding in research, creativity, and hard work, Amit closed in with a tangible solution of affordable and maintenance-free Rainwater harvesting. He successfully launched his startup NeeRain Pvt. Ltd in the year 2018. The NeeRain water harvesting device overcomes all the issues related to traditional water harvesting systems, such as simple and easily installable devices, cost-effectiveness, and minimum to no maintenance. The NeeRain system is a portable device that can be attached to the pipes collecting water from the rooftop and further channelizing it to the ground. It is a two-stage filtration process in which fresh, clean, and pure rainwater is collected when it passes out of the filtration system. NeeRain has created awareness about the global water crises and empowered the common people to live water-secure lives. Amit’s NeeRain device has won awards at different levels, including CII’s National Award for Excellence in Water Management in the innovative water-saving product category. device water https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NWD_hIwS8-w', '{"innovation_slug":"neerain-private-limited","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/neerain-private-limited/","innovation_title":"NeeRain Private Limited","innovator_name":"Amit Doshi","location":"Gandhinagar Gujarat","innovator_bio":"Innovator Amit Doshi from Gandhinagar, Gujarat, was appreciated and supported by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network for entrepreneur development and feedback for improved technology for his rainwater harvesting system. Amit quit his well-paid corporate job in the waste management sector to jump into sustainable technology to make a difference. Today he has a successful startup company YIM NeeRain Pvt. ltd, that saves around 60,000 liters of water by rainwater harvesting.","innovation_details":"After quitting his corporate job, Amit Doshi diligently sought a startup idea. He researched for a while in different fields of sustainable environment, but the only proposal that left an impression on his mind was rainwater harvesting. After learning about the problems the government and local people faced in water conservation, he developed a product that could resolve all the issues and gaps of conventional water harvesting systems. Succeeding in research, creativity, and hard work, Amit closed in with a tangible solution of affordable and maintenance-free Rainwater harvesting. He successfully launched his startup NeeRain Pvt. Ltd in the year 2018. The NeeRain water harvesting device overcomes all the issues related to traditional water harvesting systems, such as simple and easily installable devices, cost-effectiveness, and minimum to no maintenance. The NeeRain system is a portable device that can be attached to the pipes collecting water from the rooftop and further channelizing it to the ground. It is a two-stage filtration process in which fresh, clean, and pure rainwater is collected when it passes out of the filtration system. NeeRain has created awareness about the global water crises and empowered the common people to live water-secure lives. Amit’s NeeRain device has won awards at different levels, including CII’s National Award for Excellence in Water Management in the innovative water-saving product category.","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Neerain-Amit-Doshi.jpg"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/Neerain.jpg"],"multimedia_links":["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=NWD_hIwS8-w"],"tags":["device","water"],"latitude":23.1077747,"longitude":72.6397984,"listing_excerpt":"Amit Doshi"}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('modified-boiler-based-mawa-maker', 'subhash-ola-alwar-rajasthan', 'Subhash Ola', 'Modified Boiler-based Mawa Maker', 'When Subhash was trying to design an improved boiler, he visited an industry in Jaipur where he saw a boiler-based mawa-making machine. He was flustered after knowing that the amount of wood and water consumed to make mawa is 100 kg and 4000 liters, respectively. This much fuel extracts mawa from 100 lit of milk. It also consumed a hefty amount of electricity, thus making the whole process very costly. Knowing this, he started modifying the boiler design used in mawa making. After ten years of hard work, Subhash successfully developed the enhanced version of a boiler-based machine for making mawa. In this mawa maker, the steam circuit (boiler, kadai, condenser, pipe) is made with a closed leakproof design, improving fuel efficiency and minimal wastage. It is leakproof and hence requires no additional water. It has automated boiler operation and automatic steering operation, reducing wood consumption and labor work. The boiler-based mawa-making machine was awarded at the national level in the 8th National Grassroots Innovation Awards 2015. He won the first prize in the Amazon Sambhav Entrepreneurship Challenge 2022; also, his startup was awarded the Startup of the Year award. He received the 8th Biennial National Grassroots Innovation and Outstanding Traditional Knowledge award in 2015. He was also invited to be a part of the fourth batch of innovation scholars in the residence program of the Rashtrapati Bhavan', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/modified-boiler-based-mawa-maker/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-04-20-at-12.56.20-1-1024x768.jpeg', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-04-20-at-12.56.20-1-1024x768.jpeg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-04-20-at-12.56.20-1.jpeg"]'::jsonb, '["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Nk8WzkL5h6w"]'::jsonb, 'Alwar , Rajasthan', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Subhash Ola"},{"key":"Location","value":"Alwar , Rajasthan"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"When Subhash was trying to design an improved boiler, he visited an industry in Jaipur where he saw a boiler-based mawa-making machine. He was flustered after knowing that the amount of wood and water consumed to make mawa is 100 kg and 4000 liters, respectively. This much fuel extracts mawa from 100 lit of milk. It also consumed a hefty amount of electricity, thus making the whole process very costly. Knowing this, he started modifying the boiler design used in mawa making. After ten years of hard work, Subhash successfully developed the enhanced version of a boiler-based machine for making mawa. In this mawa maker, the steam circuit (boiler, kadai, condenser, pipe) is made with a closed leakproof design, improving fuel efficiency and minimal wastage. It is leakproof and hence requires no additional water. It has automated boiler operation and automatic steering operation, reducing wood consumption and labor work. The boiler-based mawa-making machine was awarded at the national level in the 8th National Grassroots Innovation Awards 2015. He won the first prize in the Amazon Sambhav Entrepreneurship Challenge 2022; also, his startup was awarded the Startup of the Year award. He received the 8th Biennial National Grassroots Innovation and Outstanding Traditional Knowledge award in 2015. He was also invited to be a part of the fourth batch of innovation scholars in the residence program of the Rashtrapati Bhavan"},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Nk8WzkL5h6w"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['machine', 'water']::text[], 'Modified Boiler-based Mawa Maker Subhash Ola Alwar , Rajasthan The innovator, Subhash from Alwar Rajasthan, was scouted by Swabhiman, a volunteer at the Honey Bee Network. Subhash modified a boiler used in conventional mawa-making machines and made it energy-efficient. His innovation was guided and carried forward by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network, who also helped with the marketing and funding, along with NIF. Apart from helping his father with drilling bore wells and farming Subhash was a steam energy enthusiast. In different parts of North India, he sold around 60 machines and started his own startup company. Today, he makes machines with different capacities according to customers’ demands. When Subhash was trying to design an improved boiler, he visited an industry in Jaipur where he saw a boiler-based mawa-making machine. He was flustered after knowing that the amount of wood and water consumed to make mawa is 100 kg and 4000 liters, respectively. This much fuel extracts mawa from 100 lit of milk. It also consumed a hefty amount of electricity, thus making the whole process very costly. Knowing this, he started modifying the boiler design used in mawa making. After ten years of hard work, Subhash successfully developed the enhanced version of a boiler-based machine for making mawa. In this mawa maker, the steam circuit (boiler, kadai, condenser, pipe) is made with a closed leakproof design, improving fuel efficiency and minimal wastage. It is leakproof and hence requires no additional water. It has automated boiler operation and automatic steering operation, reducing wood consumption and labor work. The boiler-based mawa-making machine was awarded at the national level in the 8th National Grassroots Innovation Awards 2015. He won the first prize in the Amazon Sambhav Entrepreneurship Challenge 2022; also, his startup was awarded the Startup of the Year award. He received the 8th Biennial National Grassroots Innovation and Outstanding Traditional Knowledge award in 2015. He was also invited to be a part of the fourth batch of innovation scholars in the residence program of the Rashtrapati Bhavan machine water https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Nk8WzkL5h6w', '{"innovation_slug":"modified-boiler-based-mawa-maker","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/modified-boiler-based-mawa-maker/","innovation_title":"Modified Boiler-based Mawa Maker","innovator_name":"Subhash Ola","location":"Alwar , Rajasthan","innovator_bio":"The innovator, Subhash from Alwar Rajasthan, was scouted by Swabhiman, a volunteer at the Honey Bee Network. Subhash modified a boiler used in conventional mawa-making machines and made it energy-efficient. His innovation was guided and carried forward by GIAN and the Honey Bee Network, who also helped with the marketing and funding, along with NIF. Apart from helping his father with drilling bore wells and farming Subhash was a steam energy enthusiast. In different parts of North India, he sold around 60 machines and started his own startup company. Today, he makes machines with different capacities according to customers’ demands.","innovation_details":"When Subhash was trying to design an improved boiler, he visited an industry in Jaipur where he saw a boiler-based mawa-making machine. He was flustered after knowing that the amount of wood and water consumed to make mawa is 100 kg and 4000 liters, respectively. This much fuel extracts mawa from 100 lit of milk. It also consumed a hefty amount of electricity, thus making the whole process very costly. Knowing this, he started modifying the boiler design used in mawa making. After ten years of hard work, Subhash successfully developed the enhanced version of a boiler-based machine for making mawa. In this mawa maker, the steam circuit (boiler, kadai, condenser, pipe) is made with a closed leakproof design, improving fuel efficiency and minimal wastage. It is leakproof and hence requires no additional water. It has automated boiler operation and automatic steering operation, reducing wood consumption and labor work. The boiler-based mawa-making machine was awarded at the national level in the 8th National Grassroots Innovation Awards 2015. He won the first prize in the Amazon Sambhav Entrepreneurship Challenge 2022; also, his startup was awarded the Startup of the Year award. He received the 8th Biennial National Grassroots Innovation and Outstanding Traditional Knowledge award in 2015. He was also invited to be a part of the fourth batch of innovation scholars in the residence program of the Rashtrapati Bhavan","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/subhash-ola-Modified-boiler-based-mawa-maker.jpg"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-04-20-at-12.56.20-1-1024x768.jpeg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-04-20-at-12.56.20-1.jpeg"],"multimedia_links":["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Nk8WzkL5h6w"],"tags":["machine","water"],"latitude":27.5993852,"longitude":76.8490328,"listing_excerpt":"Subhash Ola"}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('bullet-santi', 'mansukhbhai-jagani-amreli-gujarat', 'Mansukhbhai Jagani', 'Bullet Santi', 'Jagani belonged to a poor farmer’s family and tried different work at a very young age to fulfil his family’s needs. At last, he started a small workshop in his village and helped farmers by repairing different agricultural equipment. Once there was a drought in his village, and the agriculture and farmers suffered a lot; hence, many farmers sold their bullocks as it was hard to feed them. During all of these, he met one of his friends who sold his bullocks and needed an alternative to continuing his farming. At that time, Mansukhbhai considered converting a Bullet into a farm tractor, bought a second-hand bullet, and converted it into portable agricultural equipment. This was a success for different agricultural activities. The Bullet Santi can plow about 2 acres using one litre of diesel. Also, the distance between the rear wheels can be adjusted per crop spacing. There was a provision for a plow lifting mechanism and reverse gears for easier field operations. It is an all-in-one agricultural device smaller than tillers and tractors but stronger than draft animals. Very few are efficient and easy to handle and operate. It can be dismantled and again reused as a motorbike. As it is lighter than a tractor, it prevents soil compaction. He prototyped equipment such as an adjustable spraying device, seeding device, fertilisers, sprayers, and welding device that can all be attached to the Bullet Santi. After the year 2000, he faced problems in getting bullets to modify, and hence, he developed his automobile from the engine to attachments known as “Sanedo”. Today he manufactures his automobile of different HP capacities from scratch and sells it all over Gujarat and Kenya. “Sanedo” is available in three-wheel and four-wheel configurations as the customer requires. Mansukhbhai’s innovation became popular in India and South Africa, and farmers in South Africa appreciated the device. He was awarded a national award in the 1st National Grassroots Innovation Awards in 2001. He was invited by Jomo Kenyatta University in Kenya and South Africa. His company is government-approved, and soon farmers can access a subsidiary to purchase his product. His new upgraded version of the Bullet Santi, locally known as “Sanedo,” is a patented product, and he has a manufacturing capacity of around 1000 units. Today his innovation helps many farmers continue farming, even if they cannot afford a tractor', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/bullet-santi/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-04-18-at-18.23.40-Copy-1-1024x768.jpeg', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-04-18-at-18.23.40-Copy-1-1024x768.jpeg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-04-18-at-18.23.40-Copy-1.jpeg"]'::jsonb, '["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d7lBF1irqWs"]'::jsonb, 'Amreli , Gujarat', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Mansukhbhai Jagani"},{"key":"Location","value":"Amreli , Gujarat"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"Jagani belonged to a poor farmer’s family and tried different work at a very young age to fulfil his family’s needs. At last, he started a small workshop in his village and helped farmers by repairing different agricultural equipment. Once there was a drought in his village, and the agriculture and farmers suffered a lot; hence, many farmers sold their bullocks as it was hard to feed them. During all of these, he met one of his friends who sold his bullocks and needed an alternative to continuing his farming. At that time, Mansukhbhai considered converting a Bullet into a farm tractor, bought a second-hand bullet, and converted it into portable agricultural equipment. This was a success for different agricultural activities. The Bullet Santi can plow about 2 acres using one litre of diesel. Also, the distance between the rear wheels can be adjusted per crop spacing. There was a provision for a plow lifting mechanism and reverse gears for easier field operations. It is an all-in-one agricultural device smaller than tillers and tractors but stronger than draft animals. Very few are efficient and easy to handle and operate. It can be dismantled and again reused as a motorbike. As it is lighter than a tractor, it prevents soil compaction. He prototyped equipment such as an adjustable spraying device, seeding device, fertilisers, sprayers, and welding device that can all be attached to the Bullet Santi. After the year 2000, he faced problems in getting bullets to modify, and hence, he developed his automobile from the engine to attachments known as “Sanedo”. Today he manufactures his automobile of different HP capacities from scratch and sells it all over Gujarat and Kenya. “Sanedo” is available in three-wheel and four-wheel configurations as the customer requires. Mansukhbhai’s innovation became popular in India and South Africa, and farmers in South Africa appreciated the device. He was awarded a national award in the 1st National Grassroots Innovation Awards in 2001. He was invited by Jomo Kenyatta University in Kenya and South Africa. His company is government-approved, and soon farmers can access a subsidiary to purchase his product. His new upgraded version of the Bullet Santi, locally known as “Sanedo,” is a patented product, and he has a manufacturing capacity of around 1000 units. Today his innovation helps many farmers continue farming, even if they cannot afford a tractor"},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d7lBF1irqWs"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['agriculture', 'device', 'farmer']::text[], 'Bullet Santi Mansukhbhai Jagani Amreli , Gujarat A hard-working innovator Mansukhbhai Jagani, who left school early, a native of Amreli, Gujarat, innovated a portable tractor from a Bullet motorcycle that can be used in agriculture for diverse amounts of farm work. He also innovated many different equipment used in farming for assorted work disciplines and started a workshop of his products known today as Jai Khodiyar Welding Works. GIAN and the Honey Bee Network were the key supporters of the innovator. Prof. Anil Gupta helped Mansukhbhai file a patent for his prototype in India and the USA with the help of NIF. GIAN supported the innovation with all the hardships faced in the market. From a small agriculture equipment repair workshop, Mansukhbhai owns the reputed workshop, Jai Khodiyar Welding Works. He has sold more than 1500 Bullet Santi along with his other innovative Agri-devices. Jagani belonged to a poor farmer’s family and tried different work at a very young age to fulfil his family’s needs. At last, he started a small workshop in his village and helped farmers by repairing different agricultural equipment. Once there was a drought in his village, and the agriculture and farmers suffered a lot; hence, many farmers sold their bullocks as it was hard to feed them. During all of these, he met one of his friends who sold his bullocks and needed an alternative to continuing his farming. At that time, Mansukhbhai considered converting a Bullet into a farm tractor, bought a second-hand bullet, and converted it into portable agricultural equipment. This was a success for different agricultural activities. The Bullet Santi can plow about 2 acres using one litre of diesel. Also, the distance between the rear wheels can be adjusted per crop spacing. There was a provision for a plow lifting mechanism and reverse gears for easier field operations. It is an all-in-one agricultural device smaller than tillers and tractors but stronger than draft animals. Very few are efficient and easy to handle and operate. It can be dismantled and again reused as a motorbike. As it is lighter than a tractor, it prevents soil compaction. He prototyped equipment such as an adjustable spraying device, seeding device, fertilisers, sprayers, and welding device that can all be attached to the Bullet Santi. After the year 2000, he faced problems in getting bullets to modify, and hence, he developed his automobile from the engine to attachments known as “Sanedo”. Today he manufactures his automobile of different HP capacities from scratch and sells it all over Gujarat and Kenya. “Sanedo” is available in three-wheel and four-wheel configurations as the customer requires. Mansukhbhai’s innovation became popular in India and South Africa, and farmers in South Africa appreciated the device. He was awarded a national award in the 1st National Grassroots Innovation Awards in 2001. He was invited by Jomo Kenyatta University in Kenya and South Africa. His company is government-approved, and soon farmers can access a subsidiary to purchase his product. His new upgraded version of the Bullet Santi, locally known as “Sanedo,” is a patented product, and he has a manufacturing capacity of around 1000 units. Today his innovation helps many farmers continue farming, even if they cannot afford a tractor agriculture device farmer https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d7lBF1irqWs', '{"innovation_slug":"bullet-santi","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/bullet-santi/","innovation_title":"Bullet Santi","innovator_name":"Mansukhbhai Jagani","location":"Amreli , Gujarat","innovator_bio":"A hard-working innovator Mansukhbhai Jagani, who left school early, a native of Amreli, Gujarat, innovated a portable tractor from a Bullet motorcycle that can be used in agriculture for diverse amounts of farm work. He also innovated many different equipment used in farming for assorted work disciplines and started a workshop of his products known today as Jai Khodiyar Welding Works. GIAN and the Honey Bee Network were the key supporters of the innovator. Prof. Anil Gupta helped Mansukhbhai file a patent for his prototype in India and the USA with the help of NIF. GIAN supported the innovation with all the hardships faced in the market. From a small agriculture equipment repair workshop, Mansukhbhai owns the reputed workshop, Jai Khodiyar Welding Works. He has sold more than 1500 Bullet Santi along with his other innovative Agri-devices.","innovation_details":"Jagani belonged to a poor farmer’s family and tried different work at a very young age to fulfil his family’s needs. At last, he started a small workshop in his village and helped farmers by repairing different agricultural equipment. Once there was a drought in his village, and the agriculture and farmers suffered a lot; hence, many farmers sold their bullocks as it was hard to feed them. During all of these, he met one of his friends who sold his bullocks and needed an alternative to continuing his farming. At that time, Mansukhbhai considered converting a Bullet into a farm tractor, bought a second-hand bullet, and converted it into portable agricultural equipment. This was a success for different agricultural activities. The Bullet Santi can plow about 2 acres using one litre of diesel. Also, the distance between the rear wheels can be adjusted per crop spacing. There was a provision for a plow lifting mechanism and reverse gears for easier field operations. It is an all-in-one agricultural device smaller than tillers and tractors but stronger than draft animals. Very few are efficient and easy to handle and operate. It can be dismantled and again reused as a motorbike. As it is lighter than a tractor, it prevents soil compaction. He prototyped equipment such as an adjustable spraying device, seeding device, fertilisers, sprayers, and welding device that can all be attached to the Bullet Santi. After the year 2000, he faced problems in getting bullets to modify, and hence, he developed his automobile from the engine to attachments known as “Sanedo”. Today he manufactures his automobile of different HP capacities from scratch and sells it all over Gujarat and Kenya. “Sanedo” is available in three-wheel and four-wheel configurations as the customer requires. Mansukhbhai’s innovation became popular in India and South Africa, and farmers in South Africa appreciated the device. He was awarded a national award in the 1st National Grassroots Innovation Awards in 2001. He was invited by Jomo Kenyatta University in Kenya and South Africa. His company is government-approved, and soon farmers can access a subsidiary to purchase his product. His new upgraded version of the Bullet Santi, locally known as “Sanedo,” is a patented product, and he has a manufacturing capacity of around 1000 units. Today his innovation helps many farmers continue farming, even if they cannot afford a tractor","innovator_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-04-18-at-18.23.40-Copy.jpeg"],"innovation_images":["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-04-18-at-18.23.40-Copy-1-1024x768.jpeg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-04-18-at-18.23.40-Copy-1.jpeg"],"multimedia_links":["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=d7lBF1irqWs"],"tags":["agriculture","device","farmer"],"latitude":21.8662172,"longitude":71.1686168,"listing_excerpt":"Bullet Santi By Mansukhbhai Jagani"}'::jsonb, now(), now());
insert into public.gian_innovations (portal_product_id, portal_vendor_id, vendor_name, product_name, product_description, product_link, product_image_url, product_gallery_urls, product_video_urls, product_location_text, product_categories, product_subcategories, product_specifications, tags, search_text, raw_product, synced_at, updated_at) values ('modified-wood-based-culturally-accepted-crematorium', 'arjunbhai-paghdhar-junagadh-gujarat', 'Arjunbhai Paghdhar', 'Modified Wood-Based, Culturally Accepted Crematorium', 'Arjunbhai Paghdhar belonged to a farmer’s family and is now engaged in the construction and brick-making business. Long ago, when he visited the crematorium, he saw precious wood burned to cremate the body. Through this, an indelible impact was made on the mind of a young tree lover. This inspired him to create something that can save trees and forests from being burned in cremation, as according to the Hindu rituals, the funeral is by cremation, and about 400 kg of wood is used to cremate a single body. The modified wood-based crematorium innovated by Arjunbhai is a biomass gasification-based cremation process. A closed mummy shape is made of refractory bricks to ensure minimum heat loss. At the front and rear ends of the structure, doors are provided to perform Hindu rituals. Cerra wool is used on the top cover’s inner side, which can tolerate high temperatures. Blowers and nozzles are attached to release air to accelerate the cremation process. Along with this, charcoal and caustic soda filters have been provided for air filtration. Also, a chimney is provided for the air exhaust. This innovation takes an average time of 70 to 90 minutes to burn a dead body (approx. 80kg weight) using around 70 to 80 kg of wood, which is approximately 80% less wood than that used in a conventional method.', 'https://gian.org/multilingual_data/modified-wood-based-culturally-accepted-crematorium/', 'https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-04-18-at-15.15.19-1024x472.jpeg', '["https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-04-18-at-15.15.19-1024x472.jpeg","https://gian.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/WhatsApp-Image-2023-04-18-at-15.15.19.jpeg"]'::jsonb, '["https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EC5nziBHKtI"]'::jsonb, 'Junagadh Gujarat', ARRAY[]::text[], ARRAY[]::text[], '[{"key":"Innovator Name","value":"Arjunbhai Paghdhar"},{"key":"Location","value":"Junagadh Gujarat"},{"key":"Details of Innovation","value":"Arjunbhai Paghdhar belonged to a farmer’s family and is now engaged in the construction and brick-making business. Long ago, when he visited the crematorium, he saw precious wood burned to cremate the body. Through this, an indelible impact was made on the mind of a young tree lover. This inspired him to create something that can save trees and forests from being burned in cremation, as according to the Hindu rituals, the funeral is by cremation, and about 400 kg of wood is used to cremate a single body. The modified wood-based crematorium innovated by Arjunbhai is a biomass gasification-based cremation process. A closed mummy shape is made of refractory bricks to ensure minimum heat loss. At the front and rear ends of the structure, doors are provided to perform Hindu rituals. Cerra wool is used on the top cover’s inner side, which can tolerate high temperatures. Blowers and nozzles are attached to release air to accelerate the cremation process. Along with this, charcoal and caustic soda filters have been provided for air filtration. Also, a chimney is provided for the air exhaust. This innovation takes an average time of 70 to 90 minutes to burn a dead body (approx. 80kg weight) using around 70 to 80 kg of wood, which is approximately 80% less wood than that used in a conventional method."},{"key":"Multimedia Links","value":"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EC5nziBHKtI"}]'::jsonb, ARRAY['tree', 'farmer']::text[], 'Modified Wood-Based, Culturally Accepted Crematorium Arjunbhai Paghdhar Junagadh Gujarat A 56-year-old farmer turned innovator constructed a modified wood-based, culturally accepted crematorium that can save around 40 acres of forest daily. GIAN and the Honey Bee Network supported the innovation to appreciate people’s environmentally friendly approaches and perspectives. Arjunbhai’s innovation was culturally accepted and was set up in different rural areas of Gujarat. It is an environmentally friendly crematorium service innovated without hurting religious aspirations. This innovation won a state-level award at the 10th National Grassroots Innovation awards 2019. Arjunbhai also received an Outstanding Traditional Knowledge award in 2019. The Gujarat energy development agency funded him to upgrade his model. Also, the government set up his crematorium in Veraval, Gir-Somnath district, Gujarat Arjunbhai Paghdhar belonged to a farmer’s family and is now engaged in the construction and brick-making business. Long ago, when he visited the crematorium, he saw precious wood burned to cremate the body. Through this, an indelible impact was made on the mind of a young tree lover. This inspired him to create something that can save trees and forests from being burned in cremation, as according to the Hindu rituals, the funeral is by cremation, and about 400 kg of wood is used to cremate a single body. The modified wood-based crematorium innovated by Arjunbhai is a biomass gasification-based cremation process. A closed mummy shape is made of refractory bricks to ensure minimum heat loss. At the front and rear ends of the structure, doors are provided to perform Hindu rituals. Cerra wool is used on the top cover’s inner side, which can tolerate high temperatures. Blowers and nozzles are attached to release air to accelerate the cremation process. Along with this, charcoal and caustic soda filters have been provided for air filtration. Also, a chimney is provided for the air exhaust. This innovation takes an average time of 70 to 90 minutes to burn a dead body (approx. 80kg weight) using around 70 to 80 kg of wood, which is approximately 80% less wood than that used in a conventional method. tree farmer https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EC5nziBHKtI', '{"innovation_slug":"modified-wood-based-culturally-accepted-crematorium","detail_url":"https://gian.org/multilingual_data/modified-wood-based-culturally-accepted-crematorium/","innovation_title":"Modified Wood-Based, Culturally Accepted Crematorium","innovator_name":"Arjunbhai Paghdhar","location":"Junagadh Gujarat","innovator_bio":"A 56-year-old farmer turned innovator constructed a modified wood-based, culturally accepted crematorium that can save around 40 acres of forest daily. GIAN and the Honey Bee Network supported the innovation to appreciate people’s environmentally friendly approaches and perspectives. Arjunbhai’s innovation was culturally accepted and was set up in different rural areas of Gujarat. It is an environmentally friendly crematorium service innovated without hurting religious aspirations. This innovation won a state-level award at the 10th National Grassroots Innovation awards 2019. Arjunbhai also received an Outstanding Traditional Knowledge award in 2019. The Gujarat energy development agency funded him to upgrade his model. Also, the government set up his crematorium in Veraval, Gir-Somnath district, Gujarat","innovation_details":"Arjunbhai Paghdhar belonged to a farmer’s family and is now engaged in the construction and brick-making business. Long ago, when he visited the crematorium, he saw precious wood burned to cremate the body. Through this, an indelible impact was made on the mind of a young tree lover. This inspired him to create something that can save trees and forests from being burned in cremation, as according to the Hindu rituals, the funeral is by cremation, and about 400 kg of wood is used to cremate a single body. The modified wood-based crematorium innovated by Arjunbhai is a biomass gasification-based cremation process. A closed